<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan     10-28 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Asks Californians to `Win One More For the Gipper' and Back
Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Pre-noon lede expected.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, saying ``there's no place
like home,'' is cranking up the nostalgia as he seeks to enlist
California and its bounty of 47 electoral votes for Republican
presidential nominee George Bush.
   ``California, here I come,'' Reagan said Thursday as he began his
last pre-election swing through his home state, where he made his
name in the movies and whose citizens twice elected him governor.
   Reagan, due to return home for good in January, is squeezing
every ounce of sentiment he can from a five-day stay here aimed at
bolstering his chosen successor's image in the Golden State.
   Before traveling north today for a two-night stop at his mountain
ranch, Reagan was scheduled to address the World Affairs Council, a
non-partisan organization formed to educate the public on world
affairs.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters heading
west with Reagan that the president was expected to touch on
U.S.-Soviet relations and the status of arms control negotiations,
and urge that Bush be elected to carry on his policies.
   The contest for the White House is close here, but Republicans
hope the Californian president will steer the state firmly into
Bush's column.
   Noting Reagan's series of stops this week in San Diego and Los
Angeles, as well as appearances next week in Fullerton and San
Bernadino, Fitzwater said, ``the president is doing everything he
can to help Bush win in California.''
   In San Diego on Thursday, Reagan told his audience of about
11,000 GOP supporters that he has ``a special place in my heart''
for Californians.
   ``You've given me so much, I hesitate to ask you anything else,''
the president said, pausing for effect. ``But will you do just one
more favor for me. Will you go out and win one for the Gipper?''
   The audience of party partisans exploded in cheers at Reagan's
use of his old nickname.
   ``As I say, there's no place like home. ... Yes, when January 20
rolls around, I'm going to be asking every one of you to open up
that Golden Gate, 'cause California, here I come,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan added that he has no doubts about passing the mantle of
the presidency to George Bush.
   ``I'll feel just fine because nobody knows better than I just how
capable and valuable are those two hands I'll be passing the torch
to,'' Reagan reassured his followers.
   The San Diego speech marked the president's second visit to his
home state since the GOP National Convention in New Orleans in
mid-August. During his previous visit in August, Reagan campaigned
in Orange County, a center of GOP conservatism south of Los Angeles.
   The president and his wife, Nancy, scheduled a weekend break at
their 688-acre ranch near Santa Barbara before Reagan resumes
campaigning.
   Fitzwater said Reagan planned to cast his absentee ballot during
the trip.
   Before he returns to Washington next Wednesday, Reagan will stump
for Bush and local GOP candidates in Reno, Nev., Milwaukee and in
another state the White House has not disclosed.
</TEXT>
