<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BBC     10-28 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BBC,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BBC World Service Revamps Stately Image _ Including Heavy Metal
Rock</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The BBC's worldwide radio service, recognized by
millions as the quintessential voice of Britain, is dropping some of
its upper-class accents and imperial signature tunes in an overhaul
of its stately image.
   Its boss is worried that ``the Beeb'' is sounding pompous and
out-of-date.
   This doesn't mean the BBC's external English-language service
plan to use announcers with broad northern England accents or
vowel-slewing Cockney tones.
   And it won't get rid of the chimes of Big Ben, the cricket scores
and the reassuring hourly announcement, ``This is London.''
   But nearly six decades after the calm, measured voice of the
British Broadcasting Corporation began beaming around the globe, its
executives have decided it risks ``verging on the pompous,'' said
John Tusa, managing director of the corporation's World Service.
   ``People kept saying `What a wonderful network,' as if that's the
end of the matter,'' Tusa said in an interview.
   ``That's exactly the time to examine it root and branch and make
sure you are improving and keeping ahead. You have to change before
the audience changes.''
   To some, the change is as inevitable as the disappearance of
Britain's bus conductors, its red pay telephone booths and its
shillings and pence. But some traditionalists are uneasy.
   ``Correct pronounciation is one of the things that have made
British broadcasting the best in the world,'' said Jocelyn Hay,
chairman of a pressure group called Voice of the Listener. ``It must
never degenerate into the slang and slovenly speech found on other
BBC (domestic) networks.''
   The overhaul, the most radical in the 57-year history of the
overseas English-language service, includes toning down the rousing,
brass-band march that for 48 years has introduced a prime news
program, ``Radio Newsreel.''
   Instead, a synthesiser-orchestrated version of ``Imperial
Echoes'' will be broadcast ahead of the program, itself restyled and
renamed ``Newsreel.''
   Elizabeth Smith, controller of the English-language service, said
critics, including some of the 60 U.S. American Public Radio
stations that relay BBC programs, found the old version ``strident
and inappropriately imperialistic.''
   ``We were brought up on this sort of tune, said Tusa, 52. ``I
thought it was just simply out of date, partly colored by the
knowledge it was called `Imperial Echoes.'''
   But he has stopped short of tampering with the BBC's famed
signature tune, ``Lilliburlero,'' the marching melody by Henry
Purcell that precedes hourly news bulletins.
   The service, taken as gospel by dozens of heads of state, is
renowned for its impartiality, and claims the world's largest
foreign audience with 25 million listeners, outstripping Voice of
America or Radio Moscow.
   Tusa, a former BBC-TV anchorman who took over the World Service
in 1986, is unmoved by the suggestion that he's meddling with an
institution.
   ``It's precisely when I hear the word institution that my hackles
rise,'' said Tusa. ``Once you're an institution you're half-way
downhill.''
   On accents, a topic which obsesses the British even more than the
weather, Tusa said: ``There's a difference between sounding
aggressively and oppressively Home Counties and just sounding more
neutral. But it will still be pretty southern standard Received
English.''
   Translated, that means replacing the clipped, slightly nasal
tones of the well-to-do in the five counties ringing London with the
accent of the educated southern English middle-classes _ who like to
think they don't have any accent.
   The 24-hour English-language service is the best-known of the
BBC's state-funded foreign broadcasts in 37 languages to an audience
of 120 million.
   The changes, which began gradually a year ago, are part of what
Tusa says is becoming less solemn and sounding more like ``today's
Britain'' for an audience that is mainly under 30, male, nearly
two-thirds in the Third World and often speaking English as a second
language.
   Other new programs are ``Newshour,'' a new nightly current
affairs program starting Monday, financial news bulletins up to 10
times a day, and ``Megamix,'' a program for young people that will
feature, among other things, heavy metal rock music.
   ``It's really communicating with young people,'' said Tusa.
``They are setting the tone.''
</TEXT>
