<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0794 10-28 0870</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0794,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis Trying to Scare Voters on Trade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Hope event; EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush accused Michael Dukakis on
Thursday of ``trying to scare the American people by putting
Japanese flags'' in his television commercials, and said the right
way to gain world markets for U.S. exports is by opening them, not
shrinking from competition.
   In a white, circus-sized tent at Applied Materials Co., in
California's Silicon Valley, the Republican presidential nominee
said he would promote U.S. trade, but not with protectionist
measures.
   ``It doesn't make sense to stick our heads in the sand, as some
in the other party have suggested, and try to build walls around
America,'' the vice president said. ``It doesn't make sense to
launch a trade war and plunge America and the world into a recession.
   ``And it is beneath the dignity of the presidency, and of the
voters, to try to incite fear of foreigners as a cheap means of
winning a few votes,'' Bush said.
   At the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles, Bush and his wife,
Barbara, toured a Holocaust museum and the vice president told a
courtyard audience, ``We owe the dead and survivors alike a promise
of vigilance.''
   The Bush campaign earlier dismissed seven members of an ethnic
advisory panel who had been accused of Nazi sympathies.
   ``We have no room in our communities for hidden Nazi fugitives or
war criminals,'' Bush said at the center. ``Every last one of them
must be found and brought to justice.
   ``Bigotry is not welcome. As president I will raise my voice and
the full force of federal law when it is violated against every hate
group, desecrater and demagogue, brown-shirt, white-shirt or bowtie,
Skokie, Brooklyn, Chicago, wherever it is. The villain is the same.''
   At a reception at the estate of comedian Bob Hope, outside Los
Angeles, Bush promised ``a kinder, gentler finish for this
campaign'' after all the criticism of negative vote-hunting. But he
followed that immediately with a repeat of his attack on Dukakis for
the Massachusetts prison furlough program, saying it amounts to
telling criminals to have a nice vacation.
   The $5,000-a-couple reception outside Hope's mansion drew
Hollywood names ranging from Jane Russell to Esther Williams to
Phyllis Diller.
   ``Campaigning must be rough, flying to all those different
cities,'' Hope told his guests, who included Barbara Bush. ``These
two people have seen almost as many hotel rooms as Jimmy Swaggart.''
   ``Welcome `Orel' Bush,'' proclaimed a banner atop the podium. It
was a humorous reference to Orel Hershiser, the Los Angeles Dodgers'
pitcher who was named Most Valuable Player in the World Series.
   As he campaigned in the West, Bush repeatedly vowed opposition to
federal gun controls, drawing cheers each time. His campaign issued
copies of a 1976 statement in which Dukakis called for tight handgun
restrictions.
   Dukakis, campaigning Wednesday in Colorado, had said his position
was being misrepresented and that he always had supported ``the
right of hunters and sportsmen and of people to protect themselves
in their own homes.''
   Bush said foreign investment in the United States is not the
threat the Democrats claim.
   He also said that Dukakis should explain ``why his thinly veiled
comments about foreign investment only mention Japan,''which he said
ranks only third as a source of foreign investment in the United
States.
   ``My opponent knows better, and he should stop trying to scare
the American people by putting Japanese flags on these American
television commercials of his,'' Bush said.
   The footage of the Japanese flag appears in a Dukakis ad
challenging Bush's record as head of a commission that examined
U.S.-Japanese trade relations. The ad is running in Ohio.
   ``Bush returned from Japan saying our trade relationship was
superb,'' the ad says. ``Superb for Japan, maybe. Superb for
Japanese workers, but bad news for American working families. Mike
Dukakis stands up to foreign competition.''
   Bush said the nations of the Pacific represent ``huge and growing
markets'' for American products, ``if we don't turn and run away.''
   ``I will make sure that our trading partners continue to
understand that our markets are vital to their growth as well,''
Bush said. ``Free trade must be fair trade. A Bush administration
will keep the heat on.''
   In Tacoma, Wash., Bush accepted the endorsement of the National
Marine Engineers Beneficial Association, a seamen's union with
50,000 members. ``It will send a signal nationwide,'' the vice
president said as he received an oversized union card as an honorary
member.
   A handful of hecklers infiltrated the endorsement rally in a
Tacoma hotel exhibition hall, and at least four of them were hustled
out by police. One man had a bloody nose, another was in handcuffs.
The Bush campaign said its policy was not to oust demonstrators.
Tacoma police said two were arrested for trespassing, one of them
also charged with resisting arrest.
   The ousters caused more of a stir than the heckling had. Bush, as
usual, aimed a speech line at the dissenters: ``None of `em leaned
over and said `Please raise my taxes.''' He said Dukakis likely
would raise taxes if elected.
</TEXT>
