<HEAD>Bob Hope Entertains for Vice President Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Bob Hope opened his Toluca Lake
mansion and Republican supporters opened their wallets at $5,000 a
couple Thursday night at a star-filled San Fernando Valley
presidential rally for George Bush.
   ``I thought it would be a nice idea to have a Hollywood party for
George,'' Hope said. ``He served Ronald Reagan for eight years, and
now maybe he'd like to meet some real actors.''
   Bush and his wife, Barbara, seemed to enjoy the respite from the
campaign trail. They mingled with the stellar supporters with the
zest of movie fans.
   The event raised $600,000 for the Bush campaign.
   Among those present: Shirley Jones; Tom Selleck; Efrem Zimbalist
Jr.; Cyd Charisse and Tony Martin; former ambassador and actor John
Gavin and Constance Tower; Glenn Ford; Jane Russell; Robert Mitchum;
Donald O'Connor; Telly Savalas; singer Jack Jones and actress Jaclyn
Smith; Gene Autry; Wayne Rogers; Chuck Norris; Don Sutton; Don
Rickles; Jamie Farr; Danny Thomas; Mary Hart and Phyllis Diller.
   ``Welcome `Orel' Bush,'' proclaimed a banner atop the podium, in
a humorous reference to Orel Hershiser the Los Angeles Dodgers'
pitcher who was named Most Valuable Player in the World Series.
   In introducing the vice president in his spacious, chilly back
yard, Hope remarked that he ``loved the last debate. Wasn't that
something? George Bush did so much better that they were testing him
for steroids.''
   The comedian added that the Secret Service had scoured his estate
for a week before the Bush visit and their bomb-sniffing dogs
``stopped by my joke file.''
   Hope also remarked on the Bushes' strenuous campaigning.
   ``They have seen almost as many hotel rooms as Jimmy Swaggart,''
he said.
   Introduced to a standing ovation, Bush tried a few one-liners of
his own.
   ``People ask me how I feel,'' he remarked. ``And I say there are
12 days before the election and I've got Hope.''
   Bush and his wife remained long after the program, shaking hands
with celebrities and thanking them for their support.
   ``I believe in him,'' Hope said.
   ``The first time I played golf with Dwight Eisenhower, I also
played with George's father, Prescott Bush. He was a real class
gentlemen, and a lot of it rubbed off on his son.''
