<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CommodityCertificates     10-28 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Commodity Certificates,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Says USDA Accounting Slip Could Hurt Grain Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department's inability to
account for up to $1.6 billion of commodity certificates is a ``huge
unknown'' that could seriously affect grain markets, a House
subcommittee chairman says.
   ``These certificates are just like stocks that represent millions
of dollars of U.S. grain reserves. We can't just gloss over this
problem,'' Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., said Thursday.
   The certificates, which have a specific dollar value, can be
redeemed for cash, used to buy government-owned commodities, repay
government crop price support loans or resold to other individuals.
   Glickman's remarks came in response to a General Accounting
Office report that said USDA has not resolved recordkeeping
discrepancies, potentially worth $1.6 billion, for thousands of
commodity certificates issued as partial government subsidy payments
to farmers.
   The report said there are growing numbers of unreconciled
discrepancies. In some instances, there are no records of issuance
for certificates that have been reported as redeemed; in others,
redeemed certificates are recorded with a higher or lower value than
as issued.
   The agency recommended that USDA develop an immediate plan for
eliminating the problem.
   Glickman, who requested the GAO report as chairman of the
Agriculture subcommittee on wheat, soybeans and feed grains, said
the ``existence of the discrepancies has potentially large
implications for the markets, particularly in an environment of
increasing tightness and increased volatility.''
   That the government's commodity operation ``cannot account
accurately for such a large claim on its assets, which represent
potential grain supplies to the market, represents a disturbingly
huge unknown,'' Glickman said in a letter to Agriculture Secretary
Richard E. Lyng.
   Between 1986 and April 1988, USDA issued more than 16 million
certificates valued at $18.7 billion to farmers. About 3 million
remain outstanding, worth about $3 billion, the GAO said.
   The Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service, which
administers farm subsidy programs, has assigned a team to correct
certificates with discrepancies and has approved a plan for reducing
the backlog. But GAO said the actions would not resolve the problem
and a backlog of 116,000 certificates would remain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ReverseMortgages Bjt   10-28 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reverse Mortgages, Bjt,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HUD Plans Program For `House Rich, Cash Poor'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reverse mortgage plan designed to help the
nation's ``house rich and cash poor'' would provide elderly
homeowners with up to hundreds of dollars monthly for the rest of
their lives and no need to pay it back unless they sell.
   The Home Equity Conversion Mortgage Insurance program announced
Thursday by the Department of Housing and Urban Development
initially will insure 2,500 no-payment loans to older Americans who
own homes but need cash to keep them up or lead decent lives.
   Under the demonstration program ordered in a 1987 law, the lender
takes an interest in the elderly borrower's property in exchange for
supplementing his or her income. The limited number of reverse
mortgages are to be available through banks and other lenders by
next April, HUD officials said.
   The mortgage principal, interest and insurance fees will be
collected when the house is sold or when a borrower dies, just as a
conventional mortgage would have to be settled before heirs could
take possession of a property.
   ``It will be possible for the elderly to take out a reverse
mortgage without putting out a penny,'' said Judith V. May, HUD
policy analyst who helped design the program and described it at a
briefing.
   The loans differ from regular home equity loans in that the money
does not have to be paid back during the lifetime of the borrower,
interest rates would be lower and there is no way for the borrower
to default on the loan or lose the house.
   There is a possibility that the homeowner may accumulate debts
that exceed the value of the house _ if he or she lives long enough
_ but a built-in insurance program would ensure that neither the
borrower nor heirs to the estate would have to repay the overrun.
   To qualify, a homeowner must be at least 62, own his or her home
outright or with a minimal mortgage and submit to counseling by HUD
housing experts.
   Heirs to the property would generally be included in the
counseling, said Ms. May, so they would understand the effect the
program would have on the value of the property.
   Ms. May said an elderly borrower would have the option of
receiving monthly payments for life or larger payments for a set
term or a line of credit to be drawn upon when needed.
   The older the borrower and the more valuable the house, the
bigger the payments could be.
   Maximum loans would range from $67,500 to $101,250, depending on
Federal Housing Administration maximum insurance for different parts
of the country.
   Monthly benefits on a 10 percent mortgage would range from $81
for a 62-year-old borrower in a house valued at $50,000 to $662 for
an 85-year-old in a house valued at $100,000 or more.
   A person who takes out a maximum loan on a $100,000 house at age
75 and lives to be 100 could accumulate a debt of $538,861 but would
still own the house until he or she died, and there could be no lien
against any other property even though the debt may exceed the value
of the house.
   Along with the payments, small mortgage insurance premiums would
be deducted from the home's value, so that the program could cover
any losses.
   Officials said the 2,500 loans would be available in every region
of the country, in proportion to the number of elderly homeowners in
each area.
   ``This is another option to help older people survive and thrive
in our country,'' said Carol Fraser Fisk, national commissioner on
aging.
   Representatives of the Federal National Mortgage Association,
known as Fannie Mae, and the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., known
as Freddie Mac, announced they would purchase loans under the plan.
   HUD says 73 percent of America's 18.9 million elderly own their
own homes and 83 percent of those, or 11.5 million, owe nothing on
them.
   That creates a potential reverse mortgage market of $700 billion,
said William A. Schainker, Fannie Mae senior vice president.
   The reverse mortgages will be available from regular lending
institutions but will be insured by HUD so there will be no risk of
payments being cut off or of loss to the lender, said Kenneth J.
Beirne, assistant housing secretary.
   ``Too many Americans who work most of their lives to pay off
their mortgages wake up one morning to find that they are house rich
and cash poor,'' said Rep. George C. Wortley, R-N.Y., who worked on
the legislation setting up the program.
   The project will effectively double the number of reverse
mortgages available in the United States. About 2,000 have been
issued by private lenders in seven states.
   Some adjustments could be made before final rules are adopted,
following a 60-day period for public comment, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
