<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SuperpowerRelations Bjt   10-28 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Superpower Relations, Bjt,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: The Awful Autumn of '83: A Vintage Era for the
Cold War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The serenity now shrouding East-West relations
makes it difficult to recall just how wretched things were in the
awful autumn of 1983, just five years ago.
   The same West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl who jetted off to
Moscow this week for a friendly chat with Mikhail S. Gorbachev was
busy on a less fraternal undertaking five falls ago: the
installation of U.S. nuclear weapons pointed at Soviet targets.
   Western Europe was awash in protest over the missile deployments
in five countries and the governments which backed the move were on
the defensive.
   To counter the deployments, the Soviets at one point threatened
to install their own nuclear missiles in the Caribbean, aiming them
at American targets.
   It was a time when the high hopes engendered by two sets of
nuclear arms reduction talks between the superpowers were shattered
by Soviet walkouts from both.
   South Korea was rocked by twin tragedies which occurred less than
seven weeks apart: the shooting down of KAL flight 007 by a Soviet
missile and a North Korean-inspired terrorist bombing in Burma that
killed much of the Seoul government's top leadership.
   With the downing of the KAL flight, Soviet-American relations
dropped to a low point. At a September meeting with then Foreign
Minister Andrei Gromyko, Secretary of State George P. Shultz refused
to discuss anything else.
   It seemed the relationship had hit bottom but with the Soviet
suspension of both arms reduction talks a few weeks later, new
depths were reached.
   It was a time when the pro-Soviet government on Grenada was
ousted by a U.S.-led invasion force, the first time any Marxist
government had ever been dislodged.
   It was a bad fall but the preceding period had set the tone. It
was a vintage year for cold warriors, the year when President Reagan
called the Soviet Union an ``evil empire'' and then, barely two
weeks later, unveiled the program which to this day remains a core
issue in Soviet-American relations _ the Strategic Defense
Initiative, ``Star Wars.''
   It was a time when the prophets of doom were in vogue but the
reality nowadays is altogether different. Since 1985, there have
been four Soviet-American summits and, even more significant, there
is less talk of nuclear war than at any time since 1945.
   The relaxation in Soviet-American tensions is such that some
analysts wonder why, in the current presidential campaign, there are
so few ideas being aired about what the new mood means and what new
policies would be appropriate to deal with it.
   Says Graham Fuller, a former senior official at the Central
Intelligence Agency, ``When you have hostile Soviet Union, it is
clear what is the basis of U.S. alliance. But what if the threat
isn't present any longer? What's the premise of U.S. alliances and
what's the role of U.S. power?''
   Fuller contends that the changes in Soviet foreign policy are
such that the next president should begin to ask: What's the problem
between us?
   Less sanguine about the more upbeat tone in Soviet-American
relations is former Secretary of State Henry A. Kissinger, who said
Wednesday that it would be a mistake for the United States to base
its foreign policy on the good will of a single individual, namely
Gorbachev.
   Look at history, Kissinger warned. At the end of every preceding
century, Russian borders have expanded in every direction. Beyond
that, he said, every Soviet Communist Party secretary general has
repudiated his predecessor, meaning that Gorbachev may be only a
transient phenomenon.
   A former Kissinger deputy at the State Department, Lawrence
Eagleburger, believes that the changes in East-West relations since
the nightmare year of 1983 signal a turning point that requires
wisdom and foresight, neither of which he says are in abundant
supply in the current campaign.
   ``What worries me is that nobody is talking about these issues,''
Eagleburger says. ``Unless we recognize the transition that's taking
place and reorganize the West to deal with it, the problems of the
next 20 years will eat us alive.''
   
   EDITOR`S NOTE __ George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
