<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Powell-Nicaragua     10-28 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Powell-Nicaragua,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Aide Paints Grim Picture Of Nicaraguan Peace Prospects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan rebels are struggling in their quest
to force democratic reforms upon the Central American nation because
of erratic support from the United States, President Reagan's
national security adviser says.
   As a result, says Army Lt. Gen. Colin D. Powell, ``we face the
grim prospect of further deterioration and continuing crisis in that
country.''
   In a speech to the National Press Club Thursday, Powell said the
move toward peaceful settlements of conflicts elsewhere around the
world, including Afghanistan, Angola and Cambodia, is a reflection
of ``effective resistance to aggression.''
   ``One lesson here is that sometimes leaders have the wit to see
the futility of war and to seek diplomatic solutions,'' he said. ``A
so-called `peace'' purchased at the price of surender is not real
peace, or security.''
   Powell, who succeeded Frank C. Carlucci in the national security
adviser's job when Carlucci became secretary of defense last
November, said that in Afghanistan, Angola and Cambodia, ``a kind of
exhaustion has set in'' after years of brutal conflict.
   ``In all these cases of success, we also benefited from solid
bipartisan congressional support and the support of the American
people,'' he said, noting that in the case of Afghanistan, the
Mujahedeen anti-government rebels enjoyed the support of the United
States and several other countries.
   ``I believe this administration understood this lesson, and
therefore deserves some of the credit for the winding down of those
various conflicts,'' Powell said.
   Without mentioning the pitched battles the administration has had
with Congress over military assistance for the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels, he said that ``diplomacy is not going well and freedom is
not winning, precisely because effective resistance has been
undercut.''
   The administration recently abandoned hope of getting Congress to
release $16.5 million in weapons stockpiled in Honduras for use by
the Contras, indicating the problem would have to be addressed by
the next administration. The Congress did approve a $27 million
humanitarian aid package.
   Powell also said that Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev should
be given credit for attempting to bring about economic reform. But
he said it ``remains to be seen'' how much improvement can be made
under a communist, one-party system.
   Powell also said it has become clear that the Soviets have chosen
to pursue a policy of declining adventurism in foreign policy so
they can focus ``energies and resources on internal economic
reform.''
   ``The bold new leadership in the Kremlin has candidly
acknowledged the problems the Soviet system faces,'' he said. ``But
the problems are fundamental, even structural.''
   Soviet officials in Moscow on Thursday said they will begin
liquidating unprofitable businesses and farms to bolster the
nation's economy and overcome a budget deficit expected to reach $58
billion next year.
   Finance Minister Boris Gostev told the Supreme Soviet legislature
that Gorbachev's government is finding it difficult to bring deficit
spending under control.
   ``Our adversaries face a systemic crisis,'' Powell said. ``They
sense that their system is wrong but they are seeking to fix it
without changing it wholesale. It is not yet clear whether they can
succeed.
   ``The immediate problem they're facing is an economic system that
is not up to the demands of the 1990s and the 21st century,'' he
said in answer to a question from the audience.
   Powell said the Soviets will be ``left behind'' in global
economic competition ``unless they make the necessarty adjustments.''
</TEXT>
