<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Portugal-Opposition     10-28 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Portugal-Opposition,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opoosition Socialist Leader Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vitor Constancio, leader of the main
opposition Socialist Party, has resigned in a surprise move that
could delay revision of the leftist-inspired constitution.
   Constancio, 45, said Thursday that he was stepping down as
secretary general because of opposition to his leadership style.
   ``Many consider my rational, pedagogic style is holding the
Socialists back. They want more showmanship and more demagogy,''
Constancio said.
   Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva said Constancio ``deserves the
greatest respect'' for contributing to stabilizing democracy in
Portugal.
   The resignation raises questions about the direction the
Socialists will take as the leading opposition party to Cavaco
Silva's center-right Social Democratic government.
   Constancio and Cavaco Silva signed an accord two weeks ago to
ensure the two-thirds majority needed to push constitutional reforms
through Parliament. But the Socialist leadership crisis could delay
debate on the changes.
   The reforms will permit the sale of many companies nationalized
after the 1974 leftist revolution. They are seen as essential for
modernization as Portugal prepares for a single European Economic
Community, or Common Market, in 1992.
   Constancio, former finance minister and governor of the Bank of
Portugal, was elected Socialist leader in June 1986 when veteran
party leader Mario Soares was elected president.
   The Socialists' vote increased in the last legislative elections
in July 1987, but the Social Democrats won a landslide victory and
formed Portugal's first majority government.
   The Social Democrats hold 148 seats to the Socialists' 60 seats
in the 250-seat Assembly of the Republic. Smaller parties and
factions hold the remaining seats.
</TEXT>
