<DOCNO> AP881028-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     10-28 0876</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Year Was Bountiful For American Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers made a dramatic recovery in 1987 after
years of financial torment, says a new Agriculture Department review.
   Higher incomes, lower operating costs, a 45 percent increase in
government payments and a modest rise in farm product sales
contributed to the improvement, the department's Economic Research
Service said Thursday.
   The report said net income in 1987 reached $38 billion after
adjusting for inflation, the highest level since the mid-1970s and
``was on a par with that of the 1950s and 1960s.''
   The 176-page analysis did not forecast 1988 financial returns or
assess the impact of this year's drought. However, other reports
have pointed to net cash income at or near the record 1987 level.
   But economists quickly note that thousands of farmers have been
hurt severely in 1988 by drought losses to crops and livestock while
others have prospered because of the reduced supplies and higher
prices.
   In 1987, rising land values, which represent 70 percent of all
farm assets, and lower debt boosted the equity, or net worth, of
farmers as of Jan. 1, 1988, to $571 billion from $537 billion a year
earlier, the report said. That reversed a six-year decline.
   ``The most dramatic farm financial change in the past few years
has been the improvement in the solvency position of farms,'' the
report said.
   Solvency, or the ability to pay debts, is one of the measures of
financial health in the farm sector. Others include liquidity, or
the capability of making payments when they come due, and
profitability, or net farm income.
   ``Higher net farm income in 1987 helped farmers reduce or pay off
debt and provided more farms with enough capital to avoid new debt
financing than in previous years,'' the report said. ``Asset values
rose 3 percent over those of 1986, while debt fell 8 percent to $143
billion in 1987 (the fourth annual decline in a row), leaving the
sector in the best position at any time in the 1980s to meet debt
service obligations.''
   According to the annual survey of farm costs and returns, nearly
80 percent of the nation's farms were profitable in 1987, up from 70
percent in 1986. The report said that nearly 44 percent of all farms
were free of debt at the beginning of 1988, compared with less than
39 percent a year earlier.
   There was a large variation, however, in debt owed by different
size farms. Only 16 percent of the largest _ those with sales of
more than $500,000 a year _ were free of debt at the start of this
year, compared with almost 60 percent of the smallest farms, or
those with sales of less than $10,000 annually.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's drought-shriveled soybean harvest
has reduced U.S. supplies and boosted market prices, but Agriculture
Department experts say the biggest impact will be on foreign sales.
   Soybean production is estimated at about 1.5 billion bushels,
down 22 percent from last year, with the yield per harvested acre
dropping to 26.4 bushels from an average of 33.7 in 1987.
   On Sept. 1, the beginning of the new season, the U.S. soybean
stockpile was 302 million bushels, compared with 436 million a year
earlier.
   A new outlook report by the department's Economic Research
Service said Thursday that the season average price received for
soybeans in 1988-89 is expected to average $7 to $9 per bushel,
while meal prices may be in the range of $225 to $275 per ton, and
oil prices 22 cents to 27 cents per pound.
   ``Most of the adjustment to smaller soybean supplies will occur
in the export accounts,'' the report said. ``Domestic crush (for
meal and oil) will be reduced 13 percent to 1.02 billion bushels,
but soybean exports will be lowered nearly 30 percent to 565 million
bushels.''
   Soybean meal exports will decline even more sharply, by 38
percent to 4.2 million tons, the report said.
   But analysts added that domestic use of meal is forecast to drop
only 6 percent in 1988-89 because livestock and poultry inventories
are not expected to decline significantly, mainly because corn
prices have not soared as much as in other drought years.
   Soybean oil exports are expected to decline to about 1.35 billion
pounds from last year's ``unusually high'' level of 1.9 billion
pounds, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Max Lennon, president of Clemson University,
will be honored Nov. 14 at a meeting of land-grant universities,
Agriculture Department and Cooperative Extension officials in Dallas.
   Lennon, 48, will receive the department's Seaman A. Knapp
Memorial Lecture Award for ``his outstanding career achievements,
contributions to the principles of Cooperative Extension education,
and his ability to speak to future needs of the organization.''
   Extension Service administrator Myron D. Johnsrud said Thursday
that ``in 24 years, Dr. Lennon has gone from being a young
agricultural student and crop and livestock farmer in North Carolina
to professorial and administrative posts'' at universities and in
private industry.
   Lennon was named president of Clemson in 1986. The award is named
after Seaman A. Knapp, the founder of the Cooperative Extension
Service and the county agent concept, which officially came into
being in 1914.
