<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NYCCrime     10-28 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NYC Crime,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Killings Jump in New York City In First Seven Months of 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violent crime in New York City rose a startling
12.9 percent in the first seven months of this year, due mainly to
``an explosion in crack'' and the summer heat wave, police said.
   Murder and manslaughter was up 10.9 percent in the first seven
months of 1988 as compared to the same period in 1987, and was 27.7
percent higher this July as compared to July 1987, said Deputy Chief
Allan Hoehl of the department's Office of Management Analysis and
Planning.
   ``If murder rates keep increasing at the same pace, we'll wind up
coming close to the all-time high we hit in 1981,'' Hoehl said
Thursday. That year the city recorded 1,826 murder and manslaughter
cases.
   In the first seven months of this year 1,030 people died at the
hands of criminals. A total of 1,672 people were killed in 1987.
   In July, when temperatures soared into the 90s for days at a
time, the city averaged six murders a day. Forty murders were logged
in one weekend.
   Hoehl said there was no doubt in his mind that drug use, and
crack in particular, was the main culprit in the figures released
Wednesday at Police Headquarters.
   ``There was a lot of hot weather in July, but the main reason is
the explosion of crack,'' said Hoehl.
   Aggravated assault also was up for the first seven months of this
year, rising 12.9 percent to 41,566 over a year ago.
</TEXT>
