<DOCNO> AP881028-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     10-28 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joffrey Ballet Dedicates Season to Founder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York premiere of a dance commissioned by
last winter's Olympic Games in Canada was the highlight of the
second night of the Joffrey Ballet's season at the City Center.
   ``Concerto Grosso,'' choreographed by James Kudelka to music by
Jean Papineau-Couture of Quebec, is attractive and completely
balletic, but it doesn't compete with the Olympics for excitement.
   Kudelka is resident choreographer of Les Grands Ballets
Canadiens. The Joffrey danced ``Concerto Grosso'' for the first time
last February in Calgary, Alberta, Canada.
   The 25-minute ballet consists of variations on a single theme,
danced by nine couples.
   The man often lifts his ballerina, often turns her. The woman
twirls around her partner. In the second movement, they do this
slowly. Sometimes a ballerina will bend her knees and be swung, low
to the ground, around her partner, as ice skaters do. There are no
solos. Toward the end, patterns such as one in which two couples
danced in front of a center couple then danced apart to frame the
center couple were developed.
   The evening began and ended with ``The Dream'' choreographed by
Frederick Ashton and ``Arden Court'' choreographed by Paul Taylor.
   The season is dedicated to Robert Joffrey, who died in March. He
co-founded the company in 1956 with Gerald Arpino, who now is
artistic director.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
