<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ZZZZBest     10-28 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ZZZZ Best,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fallen Whiz Kid Tells Tale of Gangsterlike Coercion in ZZZZ Best
Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fallen whiz kid has tried to convince jurors
at his fraud trial that he was forced to commit crimes by shady
characters, including a muscular loan shark, his bodyguard and a
reputed mobster.
   In his third day on the witness stand Thursday, 22-year-old Barry
Minkow cited the late Jack Catain, a reputed underworld figure who
Minkow said helped bankroll the troubled ZZZZ Best carpet cleaning
company.
   Minkow said he met Catain in 1985 when he repaired a carpet at
Catain's home. At the time, he said, he was deeply in debt and being
pressured for money by a loan shark named Dan Krowpman and his bulky
bodyguard named Mel.
   ``Everything was terrible,'' Minkow said. ``I was bouncing
payroll checks.''
   By then, he said, he had committed credit card fraud, insurance
fraud and tax fraud on the orders of Krowpman and Mel, who
threatened him with a gun.
   Minkow, who was 16 when he started his business in his parents
garage, has portrayed himself as a youth victimized by greedy older
men. He is charged with 57 counts of securities fraud, credit card
fraud and mail fraud.
   Prosecutors have portrayed him as a shrewd con man who bilked
investors out of millions.
   Minkow, who had hired a public relations firm to promote himself,
said newspapers were writing about him as a whiz kid when he met
Catain.
   He said Catain knew about ZZZZ Best's difficulties and offered to
help.
   ``I don't know how he knew,'' said Minkow. ``But he knew I was
having financial problems.''
   After Minkow paid $2,500 in ``up-front money,'' Catain arranged
for him to receive $75,000 in loans from two small banks. He said
Catain also set him up with a new accountant who filed fictitious
income tax returns without consulting Minkow.
   Meanwhile, he said, Krowpman had a new scam, urging Minkow to get
loans from banks for carpet restoration work which was never done
and to continue committing credit card fraud to raise more funds.
   ``I didn't want to do this,'' said Minkow. ``I said, `The
business is moving well. We don't need to do this.'''
   But he was persuaded, he said, by the 6-foot-7-inch Mel.
   ``Mel pulled out a gun from under the sofa and said, `You have no
choice but to do this,''' Minkow testified.
   ``I was paranoid and I was on these steroids,'' he said. ``I was
scared.''
   Krowpman and 10 other co-defendants pleaded guilty to various
charges related to the ZZZZ Best operation. Accountant Norman
Rothberg is on trial with Minkow, accused of taking a bribe to cover
up ZZZZ Best's frauds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Politburo Bjt   10-28 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Politburo, Bjt,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Member Who Suggested Gromyko Be Ousted Says It Was His Idea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party secretary who shocked the world
by criticizing Politburo members Andrei A. Gromyko and Mikhail S.
Solomentsev on national television says he had no idea they would be
retired three months later.
   The blunt call for resignations ``was my idea, and nobody
prompted me,'' said Vladimir I. Melnikov, a provincial party
secretary and delegate to the Supreme Soviet, the legislature, which
is meeting this week in Moscow.
   But the rotund Russian laughed during an interview Thursday and
said that when he returned home to Komi, an autonomous region in the
frozen Far North, ``everybody asked me if it was sanctioned by
somebody.''
   Melnikov became a celebrity when he suggested _ in an exchange
televised first in the Soviet Union and then on news shows worldwide
_ that aging Soviet leaders who ``actively promoted the policy of
stagnation may not serve and work on the central party and
government bodies now, at the time of perestroika. They should
answer for everything and do so personally.''
   He made the remarks June 30 at a Communist Party conference.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who spearheaded perestroika,
or restructuring of Soviet society, then asked Melnikov to be more
specific.
   ``Maybe you have some concrete suggestions?'' Gorbachev asked.
``We're sitting here and don't know: Is he talking about me, or
somebody else?''
   Melnikov replied that he was speaking about four people: the
78-year-old Gromyko, then president and previously foreign minister
for 28 years; the 74-year-old Solomentsev, then head of the Party
Control Commission; Viktor G. Afanasyev, editor of the Communist
Party newspaper Pravda; and Georgy A. Arbatov, a Soviet expert on
the United States.
   Solomentsev and Gromyko were retired in the Politburo shake-up
Sept. 30 that solidified Gorbachev's power.
   Afanasyev will be the next to go, and soon, diplomatic sources in
Moscow said on condition of anonymity. These sources said Arbatov
seems secure, so far.
   Melnikov said the fate of Afanasyev and Arbatov was a ``ticklish
question'' and left it up to the party leadership to decide.
   ``I already expressed my opinion,'' he said.
   Melnikov said he sat up late on the night before his speech
deciding what he wanted to say. For two days, he had watched an
unprecedented demonstration of glasnost, Gorbachev's policy of
openness.
   ``I decided I should reply what I think,'' Melnikov said. And he
thought that part of the blame for stagnation, the description now
given to the rule of Soviet President Leonid I. Brezhnev, ``should
be laid on people who were working then.''
   At the last minute, he thought it possible that Gorbachev, who
had been commenting on many of the speeches, might ask him to be
specific. So he scribbled the names of the four men on the cover of
his speech text.
   ``I think that this is a question that ripened a long time ago,''
Melnikov said. ``I expressed not only my opinion, but also that of
many delegates at the conference.''
   At home, ``the attitude toward me completely changed,'' Melnikov
said. ``Obviously, I expressed what the people thought.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NewYork-Presidency 1stLd-Writethru a0410 10-28 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New York-Presidency, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0410,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Cuomo and More Democrats, Dukakis In Close Fight in New
York</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf, `A Marist,' to ADD margin of error for the
polls.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis is locked in a close fight in
New York despite a hefty Democratic enrollment advantage and the
presence of popular Gov. Mario Cuomo in his corner.
   Independent polls released Thursday indicate that the Democratic
stronghold, once considered firmly in the Dukakis column, has become
a tossup with 11 days remaining until Election Day.
   A Marist College Institute for Public Opinion poll had Dukakis
leading Republican presidential nominee George Bush, 47 percent to
43 percent, while a New York Post poll had Bush ahead, 46-44. The
Marist poll had a margin of error of four percentage points while
the Post survey's margin was five points.
   ``He (Bush) is ahead in New York, there's no question about that
in my mind,'' Rep. Guy Molinari, Bush's New York campaign chairman,
said Thursday.
   Al Gordon, a Cuomo political operative who is serving as Dukakis'
New York campaign director, said the race has become ``one of those
dead-even situations.''
   New York, its 36 electoral votes making it second only to
California, is considered crucial to Dukakis. Bush strategists look
upon it as potential icing on the cake.
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle made one of his
rare visits to a major state with a stop in Syracuse, N.Y., Thursday
night. And with a win possible, Molinari said he's lobbying hard to
get Bush to make a swing across the state next week.
   The idea that Bush might take New York, despite a 3-2 enrollment
edge for Democrats, shouldn't come as a complete surprise. Ronald
Reagan carried the state in both 1980 and 1984.
   ``One of the misnomers is that New York is such a Democratic
state that whatever happens nationally doesn't affect it,'' said
Gordon. ``That obviously isn't true. Six out of the last 10
presidential elections (in New York) have gone to Republicans.''
   In hopes of preventing No. 7, Cuomo has been campaigning steadily
for Dukakis in recent weeks, with the New York governor spending at
least one day a week on the road for the Democratic nominee.
   Cuomo's itinerary has included California, Texas, Connecticut,
Rhode Island and Massachusetts. Earlier this week, the New York
governor traveled to Chicago and Indianapolis to talk up Dukakis.
   But top Democratic media specialist David Garth said he thinks
it's strange that the Dukakis campaign, in danger of losing New
York, hasn't asked Cuomo to make pro-Dukakis television ads that
could be used in the huge New York City media market.
   ``I have a feeling they're going through the motions more than
anything else in New York,'' complained the New York City-based
consultant to Dukakis' national campaign organization. ``Have they
asked Mario to make a spot for them? That's got to be crazy if they
didn't.''
   Gordon said that while the national campaign had been approached
about making some TV ads featuring Cuomo for use in New York, the
idea was rejected by a Dukakis headquarters that favored relying on
their national ad campaign.
   ``That's one thing they've been pretty firm on out of Boston,
that they want to keep on their pattern of commercials,'' said the
New York campaign director.
   Gordon said Dukakis' national campaign had authorized a radio ad
featuring Cuomo that will begin running in New York this weekend.
   New York's two other big-name Democrats, New York City Mayor
Edward Koch and U.S. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, have been barely
visible on the Dukakis campaign.
   Koch, who upset many New York blacks when he said during April's
New York primary campaign that Jews would have to be ``crazy'' to
vote for Democratic candidate Jesse Jackson, was dispatched to
Florida earlier this month by the Dukakis camp to campaign for that
state's sizable Jewish vote.
   Koch proceeded to praise President Reagan as a great friend of
Israel. The mayor hasn't been back out on the Dukakis campaign trail
since.
   Moynihan, facing a nominal challenge in his bid for a third
Senate term, recently said he hadn't been doing much Dukakis
campaigning because he hadn't been asked.
   ``He will mention Dukakis in Saturday's debate. He's vowed to do
so because he's been asked about it,'' said Moynihan campaign
spokesman Lawrence O'Donnell Jr. of the senator's plans for his
final debate against Republican challenger Robert McMillan.
   In their first debate Monday night, Moynihan didn't mention
Dukakis. In an interview with the New York Post on Wednesday,
however, Moynihan did talk about Dukakis, saying that he didn't
think the Democratic nominee would win nationally and that Cuomo
would have been a better candidate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0053EDT</FILEID>
