<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SKorea-US     10-28 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SKorea-US,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Masked Students Hurl Firebombs, Rocks At Police, U.S. Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked students burned an effigy of
Uncle Sam and pelted riot police and an American bank with firebombs
and rocks in protests Thursday against the U.S. and South Korean
governments.
   Columns of students shouting ``Let's drive the Yankees out!''
streamed off campus, hurled dozens of firebombs and clashed with
riot police at universities in Seoul, Dongkuk and Konkuk, where the
effigy was burned.
   Dozens of policemen were hit with rocks or burned by exploding
firebombs.
   Earlier Thursday, about 20 students shouting ``Yankee go home!''
threw firebombs and stones at a building housing a Citibank branch
and the Koram Bank, a joint Korea-U.S. venture in southern Seoul.
Police said two students were arrested. About 10 windows were
reported broken.
   Anti-U.S. protests have been on the rise in recent weeks, fanned
by radical students demanding, among other things, the withdrawal of
the 42,000 U.S. troops stationed under a mutual defense pact.
   In the latest demonstrations, the students also demanded the
arrest of former President Chun Doo-hwan, who opponents accuse of
corruption and violation of human rights during his seven-year
tenure. Chun left office in February.
   About 300 students staged a peaceful demonstration at Seoul
National University, demanding the removal of nuclear weapons they
claim the U.S. military keeps in South Korea. They also urged the
U.S. government to repeal its agreement with South Korea that allows
the U.S. military jurisdiction over armed forces personnel and their
dependents involved in criminal proceedings.
   U.S. military authorities confirmed Thursday that tight security
measures adopted at U.S. installations during the Olympic Games that
ended Oct. 2 would continue due to ``continued unsettled
conditions.''
   Bill Fullerton, a U.S. Army spokesman, said an advisory urged
U.S. troops not to interfere in South Korean political affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     10-28 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic Violence Leaves At Least 14 People Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Sinhaese extremists killed 10
people in central and southern Sri Lanka, and Tamil rebels fatally
shot four Moslems in the north, authorities say.
   Police imposed a daylight curfew in two industrial towns, fearing
anti-government demonstrations by opponents of the government's
peace overtures with Tamil militants, state radio said Thursday.
   The curfew was imposed in Mount Lavinia and the neighboring town
of Ratmalana, 6 miles south of Colombo.
   Police said suspected members of the People's Liberation Front, a
radical Sinhalese group, shot and a Railway Department employee
Thursday in the Colombo suburb of Dematagoda who was a government
supporter.
   Front members also have been blamed for killing nine people
Wednesday, most of them supporters of the governing United National
Party, according to a military spokesman at the Joint Operations
Command.
   The Front opposes a July 1987 peace accord aimed at ending the
5-year insurgency by Tamil rebels demanding a separate homeland in
the northeastern province. The group, which claims the accord
concedes too much to the Tamils, has been accused of killing about
500 people, most from the ruling party.
   Militant Tamils also oppose the agreement, saying it does not
meet enough of their demands.
   In Vavuniya, about 130 miles northeast of Colombo, suspected
Tamil guerrillas shot and killed four Moslems aged 19 to 28,
military officials said.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, make up 18 percent of the island's
16 million people. They claim they are oppressed by the
predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the
population.
   More than 8,500 people have died since fighting started in 1983.
</TEXT>
