<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru   10-28 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0811,0671</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill 7, U.S. AID Building Attacked</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS 6 grafs to UPDATE with attack on U.S. AID building.
Picks up graf 3 pvs, `Radio Venceremos ... '</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels attacked electric
power facilities, city buses and a bordello and killed seven people,
authorities said Thursday. A U.S. agency also was attacked and
slightly damaged.
   The offices of the U.S. Agency for International Development in
San Salvador were struck by a projectile late Thursday that cracked
several windows and caused minor damage, police guards at the site
said.
   None of the AID employees inside were hurt and no group
immediately claimed responsibility. A National Police guard outside
said he did not know what type of device had been used but described
the projectile as larger than a bullet.
   Officials with AID, the U.S. Embassy, the Defense Ministry and
National Police headquarters, consulted by The Associated Press,
said they could provide no information.
   To date, the AID offices have not suffered attacks by leftist
rebels engaged in a 9-year civil war against the U.S.-backed
government. The guerrillas have struck the American Embassy, located
in the northwest of the capital, several times without serious
incident.
   The armed forces said in addition to the seven deaths, three
people were injured in attacks this week by the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front.
   Radio Venceremos, the rebels' clandestine station whose name
means We Will Win, issued a statement in Mexico City on Thursday
claiming responsibility for the ``intensification of actions''
throughout El Salvador.
   In the most recent attack, a national guardsman was killed and a
soldier injured Thursday in the military zone around San Vicente,
about 34 miles east of the capital, an armed forces spokesman said.
   The rebels blew up four electrical towers and a gasoline station,
the spokesman said. Three electricity poles were destroyed in a
nearby town, he said.
   Police said five government soldiers and a rebel were killed in
guerrilla attacks in the capital on Wednesday.
   Three of the soldiers and the guerrilla were killed when rebels
shot at a bus guarded by soldiers. Two civilian passengers were
reported injured.
   Gunmen shot and killed the two two other soldiers as they stood
outside a movie house in the northern suburbs, police said.
   Also in San Salvador, suspected rebels on Thursday dynamited a
bordello's garage, damaging the entryway and breaking the windows of
nearby buildings, police said. No injuries or deaths were reported.
   It was the second rebel attack on a house of prostitution in the
past month. Guerrillas dynamited another such business Oct. 13.
   The rebels say they attack bordellos because they are centers of
vice and are operated by the military.
   On Tuesday, rebels assassinated the right-wing mayor of Sociedad,
a town 106 miles northeast of the capital, the government of Morazan
Department said.
   Mayor Lucio Salvador, 66, was a member of the conservative
Nationalist Republican Party, known by its Spanish acronym ARENA.
   Salvador is the third mayor the rebels have killed in a year.
   In another development, a union leader said Thursday that police
and soldiers have beat striking public works employees with rifle
butts and forcing them to work at gunpoint.
   The 20,000-member Ministry of Public Works Employees Association
went on strike Monday for higher wages.
   ``The same night, national police agents broke into workplaces in
five departments of the country, breaking chains and padlocks.
Yesterday, they beat, captured, and interrogated 15 of our
leaders,'' said union secretary-general Luis Villalta.
   Military units also occupied workplaces, he said in an interview.
He said five workers in the department of Sonsonate, 40 miles from
San Salvador, were detained for more than nine hours.
   Troops detained 10 more strikers in the department of Usulutan,
68 miles from the capital, he said.
   Villalta said the public works employees haven't had a raise in
five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
