<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     10-28 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Eases Ownership Rule for Nearby Radio Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
decided to relax its rule on ownership of more than one radio
station.
   The new rule would allow commonly owned stations to be as close
as 25 miles apart, as long as they are in different markets.
   The rule would reduce by about half the distance required between
two stations owned by the same person or company, and it would allow
common ownership of stations in adjacent markets.
   The FCC said the new rule will enable more station owners to take
greater advantage of the economies of scale and cost savings that
result from common ownership of stations.
   The FCC also agreed to recommend that Congress require cable
companies to negotiate with out-of-town TV stations for the rights
to carry their signals. The commission is expected to extend that
recommendation to cover local TV signals before it issues a final
order in the matter.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vehicles Recalled to Replace Defective Switch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost 750,000 1984-model Chevrolet, Pontiac
and GMC cars and trucks are being recalled to replace a defective
switch in the pollution control system.
   The Environmental Protection Agency said Thursday the General
Motors recall brings to 2.4 million the number of GM cars and trucks
from the 1982, 1983 and 1984 model years recalled to install new
thermal vacuum switches, which control emissions during warmup.
   A defective switch can cause excessive emissions of carbon
monoxide and unburned gasoline.
   Models affected are the Chevrolet Impala, Caprice Classic,
Camaro, Monte Carlo and El Camino; the Pontiac Firebird, Bonneville,
Grand Prix and Parisienne and the GMC Caballero. They are equipped
with 3.8-liter (231 cubic inches) six-cylinder and 5.0-liter (305
cubic inches) and 5.7-liter (350 cubic inches) V-8 engines.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Business Executive Says Deficit Panel Leans Toward $120 Billion</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Cuts
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A business executive says Robert Strauss,
co-chairman of the National Economic Commission, has said he
believes his panel will support a $120 billion deficit reduction
package split evenly between budget cuts and increased taxes.
   John Sloan, president of the National Federation of Independent
Business, said Strauss told business leaders on Wednesday that ``he
thinks he has nine votes'' on the 12-member commission for $60
billion in government spending cuts and $60 billion in tax increases
to close the budget gap.
   But James Hildreth, a spokesman for the commission, quoted
Strauss as terming Sloan's version of the meeting ``totally
inaccurate.''
   ``All he said at the dinner was that the most support he could
hope to get for any program would probably be eight or nine votes
out of the current 12 members,'' Hildreth said. ``But he denies
saying in any way, shape or form what the final package will be.''
   The commission was created by Congress to recommend how to
eliminate the federal budget deficit, which totaled an estimated
$150 billion for the fiscal year ending Sept. 30.
   The panel has set a deadline of finishing its work by Dec. 21.
</TEXT>
