<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     10-28 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Repuplicans Don't Grasp Global Competition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Speech at noon EDT; will be topped.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican policies have turned the United
States into an international debtor, dependent on foreign investors
to sustain an economy saddled with huge trade and budget deficits,
Democrat Lloyd Bentsen told a Los Angeles foreign affairs group.
   Saying the Republicans didn't recognize the threat of
international economic competition, Bentsen told the World Affairs
Council ``the United States must be able to compete not only
militarily but economically'' if it is to lead the free world and
set an example for developing nations.
   ``I would suggest that it will profit America little to gain the
whole world of military superiority if we lose the soul of our
economic capacity,'' he said Thursday. ``It will profit us little to
be military hawks if the competition is between economic eagles and
we are sitting ducks.''
   Bentsen said the Republicans were instead spending their time
distorting the Democrats' position.
   They have ``twisted the truth to imply that Gov. Dukakis is an
apostle of military weakness,'' he said. ``That's just not so.''
   Both parties planned to spend the same money on defense, he said,
but the Democrats wanted to spend more on planes, tanks and guns and
less on nuclear weapons and star wars, he said.
   Bentsen also argued that American allies should within four years
be made to pay an equal share of the costs of defending the free
world, and he said Japan should cover the $3.5 billion cost for
keeping U.S. troops there.
   While the U.S. spends more than 6 percent of its production on
the military, European nations spend far less and Japan only 1
percent, he said.
   The burden should be equalized, and he wanted to ``get that one
done in our first term,'' he said.
   Taking questions from the group afterward, Bentsen said he
supported some forgiveness of the international debt owed by Mexico
on a ``case by case basis'' and not as a nation as a whole. Mexico
needed to be treated ``like a company that went bankrupt'' that pays
part but not all on its obligations, he said.
   Both banks and the U.S. government may have to write off some of
the debt, he said. The situation with other debtor nations would
have to be reviewed individually, he said.
   Bentsen planned to continue campaigning in California this
morning and then return to his native Texas, where he will spend the
bulk of the time remaining before the election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
