<DOCNO> AP881028-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SKorea-Economy     10-28 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SKorea-Economy,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Bank Predicts 11 Percent Annual Growth Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's gross national product is
expected to grow 11 percent this year, instead of the 10 percent
previously projected, the Bank of Korea reported today.
   Kim Kon of the Central Bank attributed the revised projection to
strong export earnings, high domestic demand for products and the
continued expansion in capital investment field.
   If the projection is accurate, it would be the third consecutive
year Korea has registered a double-digit growth rate. The rate was
12.3 percent in 1986 and 12 percent in 1987.
   Kim said the GNP was estimated to have grown 13 percent in the
third quarter from a year ago, and was expected to grow
substantially in the fourth quarter even if there is some slowdown
in overall business activity. The GNP grew 10.3 percent in the third
quarter of 1987.
   The GNP advanced 14.9 percent in the first quarter of this year,
but gained a lower 9.1 percent in the second quarter when many
Koreans industries were hit by labor strikes in demand of higher
wages and improved working conditions.
</TEXT>
