<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Hope-Bush     10-28 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hope-Bush,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bob Hope, Movie Stars Fete George Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Hope said you never know who'll show up
when you leave the porch light on. In this case it was George Bush.
   Bush and a lawnful of Hollywood's senior celebrities.
   The vice president promised to spare them the boredom of the
issues, and reminded them about the myth of Martin Van Buren, the
last sitting vice president elected to the White House.
   It wasn't just any lawn, it was Hope's, in elegant Toluca Lake,
overlooking the private golf holes, the swimming pool and Hollywood.
   Hope spouted one-liners. Bush ventured one joke, saying the
85-year-old comedian was the only one around who could remember Van
Buren. He was elected in 1836.
   It cost $5,000 a couple to take in the Republican party at the
Hope compound Thursday night, and spend about 90 minutes with the
vice president and Mrs. Bush.
   The celebrity list included a cast of movies out of the past _
Esther Williams, Glenn Ford, Jane Russell, Robert Mitchum.
   Hope called the roll, summoning them to a stage set up behind his
vast home, and the names kept coming.
   Among them Telly Savalas, Danny Thomas, Pat Boone, Phyllis
Diller, Tony Martin, Gene Autry. ``I'll tell you,'' Hope said of the
aging Hollywood cowboy, ``if he makes it to the stage he gets
decorated.''
   With Bush and his wife at a ringside lawn table, Hope warmed up
the crowd.
   ``You leave your porch light on, you never know who's going to
show up,'' he said, looking down at the Bushes.
   ``These last few weeks they've been making more public
appearances than Elvis.''
   ``These two have seen almost as many hotel rooms as Jimmy
Swaggart.''
   Hope said he'd asked Bush over because the vice president has
been working for Ronald Reagan for eight years, ``and I thought that
now he'd like to meet some real actors.''
   But Hope said there had been inconveniences because of security.
He said the Secret Service arrived with bomb-sniffing dogs. ``They
stopped twice by my joke file.''
   Hope said that in his second presidential debate, Bush ``did so
much better than usual that they're testing him for steroids.''
   After that debate in Los Angeles, singer Barbra Streisand threw a
reception for Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Bush's briefing paper on Thursday's campaign events said the Hope
reception would offset the Streisand affair.
   The vice president said the GOP fundraising reception was
spectacular.
   ``Bob Hope has agreed to be the head of our 51-member seniors for
Bush coalition,'' he then announced. The audience laughed.
   ``That's no joke . . . He's heading it nationwide,'' said Bush.
   ``And we picked him because, some of you may remember the myth of
Martin Van Buren, the last time a vice president was ever elected
president of the United States. And Bob was the only one who could
remember old Martin.''
   ``I'm not going to bore you with the issues and all the
campaign,'' Bush said. ``. . . When they say how do you feel I say,
look, 12 days before the election I've got Hope.''
</TEXT>
