<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Polls, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0421,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC-Journal Poll: Bush Leading by Nine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT source of poll and conform;
picks up 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``Those polls...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis has the support of more than half
the Democrats who previously voted for Ronald Reagan, but George
Bush is still ahead by nine points overall, according to an NBC
News-Wall Street Journal poll.
   The poll, released Thursday, also found many voters dissatisfied
with both major-party candidates.
   In the survey of 1,285 likely voters conducted Sunday through
Wednesday, Bush led Dukakis 51 percent to 42 percent. The lead by
the Republican vice president over Massachusetts' Democratic
governor was similar to the 52-44 margin Bush held in an
ABC-Washington Post poll conducted during the seven days ending
Tuesday.
   Those polls found a closer race than the 13- and 14-point Bush
leads among likely voters in two polls over the weekend, and
considerably closer than the 17 points in an NBC-Journal poll just
after the Oct. 13 debate.
   The survey found Bush capturing the support of more than a third
of the Democrats who voted for President Reagan in 1984, while 56
percent went for Dukakis. And the two split blue-collar voters
evenly.
   Only 35 percent in the NBC-Journal poll said they were pleased
with their choices, and 61 percent said they wished others were
running. Pollsters have said that unhappiness with the candidates
and their relatively weak support could create continuing
fluctuations in the race.
   Statewide polls in New York, meanwhile, indicate a close battle
between Bush and Dukakis in that Democratic bastion. A Missouri poll
has found a close race in that state. A Colorado poll said Bush's
lead over Dukakis has narrowed significantly, as a result of a
recent Dukakis visit.
   In New York, the Marist College Institute for Public Opinion
released a poll giving Dukakis a 47-43 lead. The survey of 654
likely New York voters had a margin of error of four points. A New
York Post survey gave Bush a 46-44 lead, but the five-point margin
of error in the survey of 677 registered voters put the two
candidates in a statistical dead heat.
   A poll in the Kansas City (Mo.) Times, showed Bush's lead over
Dukakis narrowing from nine points in a previous survey to just one
point. The survey of 550 likely Missouri voters showed Bush with 44
percent of the vote compared with 43 percent for Dukakis. The survey
had a margin of error of plus or minus four points.
   A Denver Post-NewsCenter 4 Poll showed Bush leading 50 percent to
41 percent. Dukakis had been trailing Bush by as much as 19 points.
   No margin of error was available on the survey of 450 registered
voters.
