<1ST_LINE>r u PM-Japan-Earthquake     10-28 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Earthquake,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mild Tremor Jolts Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake registering 5.0 on the Richter scale
shook the Tokyo area today but there were no immediate reports of
damage or casualties. The Central Meteorological Agency said the
tremor was minor and was unlikely to trigger a tsunami, or tidal
wave.
   The meteorological agency said the quake's epicenter was 50 miles
under the sea off Chiba, southeast of Tokyo, shaking buildings in
Chiba and Yokohama, and to a lesser extent Kofu, Utsunomiya, Choshi
and Mito in the Tokyo metropolitan area.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means the ground motion is
10 times greater.
   A quake of magnitude 2 is the smallest normally felt by humans. A
quake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable damage in populated
areas, and the highest, a quake of magnitude 8, is a ``great''
earthquake, capable of tremendous damage in populated areas.
</TEXT>
