<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CivilityDay Bjt   10-28 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Civility Day, Bjt,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 2,500 Students Rally Against Racism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,500 University of Massachusetts
students clasped hands in a mile-long cordon against racism on the
second anniversary of a racial clash that began as a fight between
baseball fans but set off two years of unrest.
   ``I'm so proud. We did it,'' said Lori Edmonds, president of the
Afrik-Am Society, as she ran along the line of students Thursday,
hugging friends with tears streaming down her cheeks.
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young praised the ``Hands Across UMass''
demonstration but said overcoming racism is not a one-day affair.
   ``This atmosphere of civility has to be more than just holding
hands with each other once a year,'' he told 600 students in an
evening speech.
   ``Ethnic insecurity is not something that you overcome just by
getting educated,'' he added, urging students to make an effort to
get to know others with different ethnic, religious and geographic
backgrounds.
   The line of students, most of them white, stretched more than a
mile diagonally across the campus in this western Massachusetts
town, from dormitories on the northwest side to dormitories on the
southwest.
   It was in the southwest sector that fights broke out between
black New York Mets fans and white Boston Red Sox boosters after the
Mets' victory in the 1986 World Series. Ten students were injured in
the fracas, which administrators blamed on underlying racial tension.
   The incident was the first of a series of campus racial clashes.
In one, students occupied a campus center for six days to draw
attention to their demand that school officials discipline five
white students accused of beating two black students.
   Chancellor Joseph Duffey said he had initially viewed Hands
Across UMass, part of a campus-wide Civility Day program, ``with
some uncertainty.''
   ``It was a bold and maybe a bit risky thing to do,'' he said.
   But the chancellor said he was pleased with the outcome. ``It was
a very moving event.''
   Music professor Horace Boyer played ``We Shall Overcome'' on the
campus carillon as the students spread out from the campus pond.
Some sang as the bright autumn sun caught the flaming maples and
oaks. But most did not know the words to the song that stirred
earlier generations of civil rights demonstrators.
   ``So many things promote separatism and ethnicity on this campus
and elsewhere that there comes a time when you need to look at the
things we have in common,'' Duffey said as he stood between a black
student and a white student.
   Jason Rabinowitz, co-president elect of the Student Government
Association, said students, both black and white, remained skeptical
about the affirmative action commitment of the 26,000-student state
university that has a 2.5 percent black enrollment.
   ``The administration made a number of promises in the wake of the
Hurst report (on the World Series fight) and the occupation of New
Africa House (a campus Third World center) last February, but they
have not followed through,'' Rabinowitz told a noontime rally.
   Students ended their occupation after administrators agreed to a
number of concessions, including increasing the number of minority
students.
   ``The programs for minority students they promised to increase
have actually been cut,'' Rabinowitz said. ``The renovations they
promised to New Africa House have not begun. And the numbers of
black students enrolled has not changed.''
   But Rabinowitz praised Civility Day.
   ``What it says about the UMass community is that our campus is
one that is overwhelmingly opposed to racism and people are willing
to come together in fighting it.''
</TEXT>
