<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Hawtrey     10-28 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Hawtrey,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charles Hawtrey, ``Carry On'' Film Comedy Stalwart, Dead At 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Hawtrey, a stalwart of the ``Carry On''
comedy film series that became a British institution, has died in
southeast England. He was 73.
   Hawtrey died Thursday at the Windthorpe Lodge nursing home at the
seaside village of Walmer, 70 miles from London.
   He had been suffering from an artery problem, and the British
domestic news agency Press Association said his death came a month
after Hawtrey refused to have his legs amputated to combat it.
   Hawtrey, whose outrageously camp screen persona was once
described by a movie critic as ``a thin wet hen in granny specs,''
appeared in 23 of the 28 ``Carry On'' films.
   The series began in 1958 with ``Carry On Sergeant'' and carried
on nearly two decades at a production rate of roughly two movies a
year. The films included ``Carry On Nurse,'' ``Carry On Teacher,''
``Carry On England'' and ``Carry On Emmanuelle.''
   Spindle-legged and squawky-voiced, Hawtrey popped up in one
absurdly unlikely role after another as the series progressed.
   The formula of bawdy slapstick, old jokes, sexual innuendo and
outrageous double-entendres rarely varied but proved hugely popular
with undemanding British audiences intent on belly laughs.
   The movies are often repeated on television.
   Born George Frederick Joffre Hartree, he came from a family with
theatrical roots, although his father was a motor mechanic.
   He borrowed the name Charles Hawtrey from the celebrated
actor-manager Sir Charles Hawtrey, who died in 1923. He made his
debut on the London stage in 1927, and in 1929 began a long career
in radio comedy roles.
   Hawtrey was unmarried. Press Association said his nearest
surviving relatives, a brother Jack and sister-in-law Rose, live in
Australia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0515EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-28 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer glitch gave a 21-year-old
student a rare chance to get rich quick, but a spell of honesty
stopped the man from withdrawing thousands of dollars from an
instant cash machine.
   Although Neil Martin had not applied for money machine
privileges, two new cards arrived in the mail last week. He tried
one _ inappropriately named Safecard _ and was amazed when the
screen told him $999,999.99 was in his account.
   The second card registered another $999,999.99 available for
withdrawal.
   The DeVry Institute of Technology student considered the
situation overnight, and returned to a machine Thursday morning,
where he withdrew $10 from each account. The balances did not change.
   ``Now don't make me out to be a criminal,'' Martin said. ``I just
think it's so hilarious. It's such a blunder I can't believe it
happened. I never applied for these cards.''
   Apparently, Martin was not the only Home Savings Association
customer who became an instant millionaire this week, said Jerry
Gentry, a regional vice president of the savings and loan.
   ``It's just a little fluke,'' Gentry said.
   Home Savings is merging with Safety Federal Savings and Loan
Association, and a switch to a new computer system created the crazy
account balance messages Wednesday and Thursday, Gentry said.
   The firm will investigate the glitches, he said.
   Martin tried to turn in the money Thursday, but a savings and
loan official told him his real account would reflect the
withdrawals.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WESTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Why would somebody buy a house for nearly $1
million and then knock it down? To put up a $3.5 million house, of
course.
   ``People think we're a little crazy,'' said developer Charles
Bourque. But he said that in the case of the property overlooking
the 18th hole at the Weston Country Club, what he's doing makes good
economic sense.
   In July, Bourque and his father, Ulysse Bourque, who run Fine
Homes Inc. of Lexington, bought a large Colonial-style house on
three acres of land in this posh Boston suburb.
   Bourque said the house was in disrepair, so he razed it and is
putting up an 11-room Georgian colonial, which he plans to offer for
$3.5 million when it is completed in about five months.
   ``There has been a lot of buzzing in town and people on the golf
course are shaking their heads,'' he said. But he said the return on
the investment made the project worthwhile.
</TEXT>
