<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Shuttle 1stLd-Writethru   10-28 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0482,0767</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Test Flight A Reversal Of Policy After Criticism Of U.S. Shuttle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 18 beginning: The Buran ... to CORRECT that it can
haul 11,000 pounds more than U.S. shuttle. Picks up graf 19 pvs,
`While Soviet ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Shuttle Comparison, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet space shuttle that looks much like the
U.S. version is set for an unmanned test flight this weekend, a
belated Soviet acknowledgement that a shuttle is a good idea after
all.
   The shuttle named Buran, Russian for snowstorm, is scheduled for
launch at 6:23 a.m. Moscow time Saturday (11:23 p.m. EDT Friday)
from the Baikonur Cosmodrome on the Central Asian steppes of
Kazakhstan.
   A Soviet TV announcer has indicated the launch time could be
pushed back because tests of systems may take longer than
anticipated. A Tass dispatch late Thursday from the launch site said
``final operations are under way.''
   For years, the Soviets wouldn't admit they were developing their
own shuttle, or ``chelnok,'' even though Western specialists date
the program back to 1982.
   In June 1980, 10 months before the United States launched the
Columbia, the chief of cosmonaut training said Soviet officials
``consider that the employment of these spacecraft is not justified
for Soviet research because present tasks can be solved with the
well-tested methods in an economical way.''
   Former cosmonaut Konstantin P. Feoktistov, writing in 1984 in a
Soviet newspaper, praised the American shuttle as ``an impressive
engineering achievement.'' But, he added, ``this system is not sound
economically and technologically.''
   Soviet officials appeared to become believers after settling on a
different focus for their shuttle than the one NASA chose.
   The U.S. shuttle was designed primarily to ferry satellites into
orbit. But Alexander I. Dunayev, the head of the Soviet space agency
Glavkosmos, said in 1987 that shuttles are not as economical as
single-use rocket boosters for placing satellites into orbit.
   In the clearest hint of the Soviet shuttle's purpose, he said
such craft are valuable for servicing space stations and satellites
and recovering objects from orbit.
   The reasoning seems sound because ever since they pioneered space
flight with the 1957 launch of Sputnik, the Soviets have forged a
proven track record for launching satellites on single-use rockets.
They put up more than 150 satellites a year, more than any other
country.
   In addition, the Soviets have concentrated on maintaining a
permanent manned presence in space aboard the orbiting space station
Mir. While Soviet officials have not said whether the shuttle is
capable of doing so, the shuttle might be able to ferry supplies and
cosmonauts to Mir.
   The Soviets have repeatedly criticized the military use of the
American shuttle, and the next U.S. flight, of the Atlantis
scheduled for late November, is a mission for the Pentagon.
   As with the American shuttle, the Soviets might use the Buran for
military missions. The U.S. Defense Department says the Soviet
shuttle could be used to deploy anti-satellite and ballistic missile
defense weapons.
   Soviet officials say the first flight of their shuttle was
designed to be pilotless to avoid danger to cosmonauts. They point
to the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the Challenger when its crew of
seven was killed as an example of the hazards they are trying to
avoid.
   It isn't clear whether the Soviets will offer the shuttle's
services to foreign customers, as they have done with their Proton
rocket boosters. If foreign customers are sought, competition will
come not only from the United States but from Western Europe.
   The Buran clearly has advantages over its American cousin. Its
separate booster rocket, the Energia, is powered only by liquid
fuels, which can be extinguished in an emergency. It has no
solid-fuel boosters like the one that failed on the Challenger.
   In addition, the Soviet shuttle can use jet engines in its tail,
giving it more maneuverability in landing than its American
counterpart, which can only glide onto a runway.
   The Buran can carry 66,000 pounds of payload, about 11,000 more
than the U.S. shuttle's payload capacity. Energia can hoist 100 tons.
   While Soviet officials maintain they did not copy the American
shuttle, the Pentagon has a different view.
   ``By using U.S. propulsion, computer, materials and airframe
technology and design, the Soviets were able to produce an orbiter
years earlier, and at far less cost, than if they had depended
solely on their own technology and engineering,'' the Defense
Department said in its 1988 report Soviet Military Power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
