<DOCNO> AP881028-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0555EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraArms     10-28 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Arms,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Aid Defendants Briefed FBI, Military Intelligence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a private aid network for the Nicaraguan
rebels regularly briefed the FBI and military intelligence about
their activities while allegedly violating the U.S. Neutrality Act,
government reports show.
   Seven of the men were indicted by a Fort Lauderdale grand jury in
June for violating the Neutrality Act by supplying mercenaries and
guns to the rebel Contras in 1984 and 1985. But they have challenged
the federal indictment, saying they were working closely with the
Reagan administration.
   FBI and Defense Intelligence Agency documents submitted by the
defense confirm that at least two of the indicted network members _
Thomas Posey, head of the Contra-supporting group called Civilian
Materiel Assistance, and his Miami coordinator, Jose Coutin _ were
regularly reporting to government officials at various levels,
including the National Security Council.
   ``The documents show the FBI knew, the FBI was sharing the
information with Oliver North'' at the National Security Council,
said attorney John Mattes, who represents co-defendant Jack Terrell.
``At one point Posey was calling the National Security Council from
the Miami FBI office ... the FBI acquiesced in all this conduct.''
   North, a former National Security Council officer and retired
Marine lieutentant colonel, has been charged with conspiring to
defraud the government by illegally diverting proceeds from arms
sales to Iran to a criminal ``enterprise'' that financed the
Contras. No date has been set for his trial.
   Miami FBI spokesman Paul Miller said Thursday he could not
comment on his agency's reports because the matter is before the
courts.
   A declassified report from military intelligence agent Franklin
Camper showed his agency not only knew of the activities in April
1984, but outlined for Posey and a Contra official a plan for raids
into Nicaragua by U.S. volunteers and Nicaraguan rebels. One plan
was to blow up a dam at a hydroelectric plant, leaving much of
Nicaragua without power.
   A January 1985 Miami FBI report showed that Larry Spivey, a
well-connected film producer who was working and traveling with
Posey, called the FBI to tell them about the network's plans.
   Posey, Terrell and possibly Coutin ``were getting ready to travel
to Costa Rica to take part in some type of `major military action
against Nicaragua,''' the FBI report stated.
   In all, Spivey, Coutin and Posey talked to FBI agents in Miami,
Birmingham and Los Angeles at least 10 times in Janauary 1985, and
Posey also spoke to agents in New Orleans.
   One FBI report quotes Posey as warning an agent that month that
``all hell is going to break loose in Central America'' in February.
   The documents also show Miami police informed the bureau in
September 1984 of the network's existence, and that drug-trafficking
money was being used to finance the Contra cause.
   The Miami FBI in turn directed the police and its own reports to
North at the request of FBI headquarters in Washington, according to
the bureau documents.
   Even as Posey talked to the FBI about his activities, it was
clear both he and the bureau were aware the network might violate
the U.S. Neutrality Act, which bars launching military activities
against a government with which the nation is at peace.
   The FBI even titled its internal memos on Posey and Coutin
``Neutrality Matters _ Nicaragua.''
   The other defendants are Mario Calero, brother of Contra leader
Adolfo Calero; Maco Stewart and Alex Martinez. The declassified
documents mentioned the three in passing, but they apparently did
not brief the FBI or other governmental agencies.
   The seventh defendant, Joe Adams, previously pleaded guilty to
the Neutrality Act charges, and was given one day's probation by
U.S. District Judge Norman Roettger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-AbortionPill     10-28 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Pill,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Demand Company Resume Production Or Allow Other Firm To
Produce It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA GENASCI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of physicians at an
international convention have called on a French company to resume
making an abortion pill or pass the patent onto another manufacturer.
   Roussel Uclaf, the company making RU 486, suspended production
Wednesday after groups threatened to boycott company products, but
said Thursday it may eventually distribute the drug once the outcry
dies down.
   Many of the 9,000 doctors and researchers at the weeklong World
Congress of Gynecology and Obstetrics in Rio de Janeiro signed a
petition demanding Roussel Uclaf allow another company to produce
the drug.
   ``We are calling for health workers and doctors worldwide to
mobilize forces to demand the drug be taken from the drawer,'' said
Etienne Emile Baulieu, the professor who played a major role in
developing the pill. ``The suspension is a serious blow to women's
health.''
   Social groups, scientists, and politicians have criticized the
decision by Roussel Uclaf to suspend production.
   Anti-abortion groups, including the Roman Catholic Church, hailed
it. Foes of RU 486 say it puts abortions at womens' fingertips,
making abortion an easy form of contraception.
   In France, the drug can be taken only under medical supervision.
   Company officials in Paris said when they announced their
decision to suspend production that they were reacting to
international outcry against sale of the drug.
   ``We could resume distribution if the atmosphere returns to
normal,'' Pierre Joly, vice president of Roussel Uclaf, said on
French radio Thursday.
   Baulieu told The Associated Press: ``Roussel Uclaf has taken a
moralistic decision. There is absolutely no medical basis for the
suspension, which comes despite the approval of the drug by both the
French and Chinese governments in terms of safety and efficacy.
   ``The company is bowing to pressure from church groups and
conservative sectors of society,'' he added.
   Andre Ulmann, the RU 486 development chief, told a news
conference in Rio that production was suspended to avoid a
threatened international boycott of company products.
   Joly said the company acted because it was worried the anti-drug
climate might lead a woman under treatment to stop taking the drug
and risk birth defects. The company says the drug does tend to cause
such defects if it fails.
   Sheldon Segal, director of population sciences at the U.S.-based
Rockefeller Foundation, said in Rio, ``More than 500,000 women die
each year as a result of pregnancy _ more than 150,000 of those
after a dangerous surgical abortion.
   Women can take RU 486, also known as Mifepristone, for up to 49
days after conception. More than 100 clinics and hospitals in France
were using the drug and it was undergoing testing for use in China
and India.
   It was shown to effectively terminate pregnancy in 95 percent of
cases and started being used last month on a limited basis. It also
was being tested for such therapeutic purposes as treatment of
uterine cancer.
   RU 486, an anti-hormone, blocks the action of progesterone, the
hormone essential to pregnancy. Reasearchers say it is highly
effective, particularly when used with a second product called
Sulprotone, or prostaglandine E.
   Roussel Uclaf is part of the giant West German chemical group
Hoescht. The French government owns a 36 percent share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
