<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Steinberg     10-28 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses: Steinberg Appeared Unconcerned About Lisa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney accused of beating his 6-year-old
illegally adopted daughter to death, when told she was probably
brain dead, replied, ``Is there anything else wrong with her?'' a
nurse testified in his murder trial.
   Joel Steinberg, 47, ``was not overly concerned about what was
going on,'' said Nancy Dodenhoff, who was working in the emergency
room of St. Vincent's Hospital when a comatose Lisa Steinberg was
brought in Nov. 2.
   Lisa's death drew national attention and made her a symbol of the
plight of abused children. The girl was obtained illegally from an
unmarried teen-ager and raised from birth by Steinberg and his
live-in lover, Hedda Nussbaum.
   Ms. Dodenoff testified Thurdsay that Steinberg didn't cry and his
tone of voice was ``very flat, very bland, unemotional'' when she
told him Lisa was likely brain dead. Steinberg left the emergency
room ``very quickly,'' she said.
   Medical technician Brian Gearity also testified that Steinberg
seemed unmoved by Lisa's condition.
   ``Mr. Steinberg was very cool, very calm, seemed very
unconcerned,'' said Gearity, who took the unconscious girl to the
hospital.
   Gearity said that when he and his partner arrived at Steinberg's
Greenwich Village apartment early Nov. 2, a woman he later learned
was Ms. Nussbaum answered the door.
   He said she had numerous facial injuries, including bruised eyes,
inflamed lips, a split on one lip and gash on her nose, which he
later learned had been broken.
   ``She looked like an old person in a young body,'' Gearity said.
``With all due respect to Ms. Nussbaum, she looked like the lion in
the `Beauty and the Beast' '' television show.
   Murder charges against Ms. Nussbaum were dropped Wednesday at the
request of prosecutors. She is expected to be the star government
witness against Steinberg.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, has undergone surgery and psychiatric treatment
for physical and emotional injuries her lawyer says were inflicted
by Steinberg.
   Gearity said Steinberg carried Lisa's nude, limp body into the
living room holding her under her armpits with his arms outstretched.
   ``She looked lifeless, like a limp doll, nothing moving,''
Gearity said.
   He said he and his partner cleared her throat of food, then took
her down to the ambulance.
   The child had marks on her body, Gearity's partner, John
Filangeri testified Tuesday.
   During cross-examination Thursday, one of Steinberg's attorneys,
Adrian DiLuzio, suggested that the marks on the child's chest were
caused by Steinberg's thumbs.
   Steinberg told police the marks on Lisa's chest and back were
caused by his attempts to revive her.
   Filangeri said he also found a large, swollen bruise on the
child's right temple.
   Lisa died of a head injury three days after being taken to St.
Vincent's.
   A 16-month-old boy, Mitchell, was found in the apartment sitting
in a dirty diaper and tethered to a playpen, authorities said. He
also was illegally adopted, and now lives with his biological mother.
</TEXT>
