<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0625EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CoptersCrash     10-28 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Copters Crash,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines Say Copters Probably Collided Causing Crash; Services
Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YUMA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Marine helicopters that crashed at night,
killing 10 servicemen, apparently collided less than 200 feet above
the Arizona desert, officials said.
   The Boeing CH-46 and Bell UH-1N helicopters were on a training
mission when the crash occurred Tuesday. A memorial service for the
nine Marines and one Air Force officer killed was set for this
afternoon at the chapel of the Marine Corps Air Station here.
   Investigators continued searching Thursday for clues in the
crash, said 1st Lt. Mary Baldwin, a Marine spokeswoman. She said she
was unsure how long it would take to complete the investigation.
   ``We feel confident enough to say a midair collision was more
than likely,'' said Gunnery Sgt. Hal Wheeler, a spokesman at the Air
Station.
   At the time of the accident, the CH-46, which was stationed at
the Marine Corps Air Station in New River, N.C., and the UH-1N out
of Camp Pendleton, Calif., were taking part in a training exercise.
Both were from 100 to 200 feet off the ground at the time of the
accident, officials said.
   The pilots were wearing night-vision goggles, Maj. Gen. Donald
E.P. Miller, 3rd Marine Aircraft Wing commander at the Marine Corps
Air Station in El Toro, Calif., said in a statement read by Baldwin.
The statement did not say whether the goggles contributed to the
crash.
   Efforts to recover the bodies were hampered by the rough terrain
around the crash site at the foot of mountains on the Goldwater Air
Force Range about 125 miles east of the Yuma base.
   The remote desert area is accessible only by four-wheel drive
vehicles or helicopter, and the last body was not recovered until
Wednesday afternoon, Baldwin said.
   The exercise culminated a seven-week weapons-and-tactics
instructors course taught twice a year at the Yuma base.
   The crash was the second in the instructor course's history. In
1984, two Marines were killed when their light observation plane
crashed on the range.
   The twin-rotor CH-46 Sea Knight, built by Boeing until 1971, is
the Marines' main assault helicopter and has been involved in
several fatal crashes over the past few years.
   Tuesday's crash was the second in as many days involving military
helicopters in the Southwest.
   On Monday, a UH-1H helicopter hit a power line and crashed near
the U.S.-Mexico border in California, killing five lawmen and three
National Guardsmen during the first mission of a joint anti-drug
smuggling program.
</TEXT>
