<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CadetsStricken     10-28 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cadets Stricken,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents, Former Cadets Testify On Rigors Of Massachusetts Police
Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents of police cadets at a training
academy where 16 trainees were hospitalized last month told of
alleged mistreatment at the hands of academy instructors.
   One cadet's mother said her son's arms swelled ``like Popeye's''
after a day of training at the Agawam academy. She was among the 100
people who packed a hearing Thursday on police training methods,
held by a panel of 21 law enforcement and medical experts appointed
by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   The review of training procedures was ordered after nearly a
third of the 50 cadets at the western Massachusetts academy became
ill after one day of training Sept. 19. One cadet required a liver
transplant and was in a coma for two weeks; the rest suffered from
kidney problems, dehydration and exhaustion.
   Cadets reported undergoing 10 hours of pushups, laps and other
exercise while only being allowed to drink a few cups of water.
   ``No one can convince me that our officers are in any more
control of a situation because of how many pushups they can do or
whether they can take being called a wimp or a sow,'' North Adams
Mayor John Barrett III testified at the hearing. Three North Adams
cadets were among the rookies hospitalized.
   Cadet Timothy Shepard of Pittsfield remained in serious condition
Thursday at a Pittsburgh hospital, where he underwent a liver
transplant last month. He collapsed from heat stroke during the
training.
   Michael Purcell, a former Army helicopter gunner, dropped out of
the academy after the first day. His mother, Elizabeth, said before
the hearing that his arms swelled ``like Popeye's'' after the
training.
   She criticized rules of the panel that barred any discussion of
training at Agawam last month. The panel has agreed not to probe the
subject, which is under investigation by the state attorney general,
and to concentrate instead on statewide training policies.
   ``Who are they kidding? In their minds (the Agawam academy) is
going to stay the way it is,'' she said.
   Joseph Lemay, who retired from the Chicopee police force after 36
years, testified that his daughter was forced to resign after her
fourth week at the academy in 1987.
   ``From the day she got in, they wanted her to resign because she
was a little slow in her running,'' he said. ``When they realized
they couldn't break her, they told her they would kick her out; they
made her resign.''
   He said the program forced 16 cadets in his daughter's class to
drop out.
   Colleen Griswold, an Amherst police officer who attended an
Agawam academy class last winter, said the training was tough but
necessary. She said instructors were fair, although some women and
minorities who failed the course have filed suit alleging
discrimination.
   ``I did not feel discrimination against me, nor did Hispanics in
my class feel discrimination,'' she testified. ``Our trainers did
the best they could with what was available.''
   The state has provided training for municipal police since 1984
under the Massachusetts Criminal Justice Training Council, which is
run by a 24-member board of law enforcement and appointed officials.
   The hearing opened a day after the director of the embattled
council took a leave of absence, saying the agency has been hampered
by the spotlight put on him since the Agawam incident. The academy
has been closed since Sept. 21.
</TEXT>
