<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Wallace     10-28 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Wallace,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Gov. Wallace's Mother Dies At Age 90</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mozelle Wallace, the mother of former
Gov. George C. Wallace, died at age 90.
   She died Thursday evening at her Montgomery home after an
extended illness, said Elvin Stanton, the former governor's
executive assistant.
   She was hospitalized recently for kidney and heart problems, said
Marianne Dauphin, Mrs. Wallace's daughter.
   ``She was a very special, very strong, very gracious lady. I can
certainly understand where Dad got a lot of his strength and
character,'' said State Treasurer George Wallace Jr., son of the
former governor.
   Mrs. Wallace was born in Florida, but moved to Alabama as a
child, where she married farmer George C. Wallace Sr. After his
death in 1937, she supported her children by teaching music and a
girl's sewing class under a New Deal program. She moved to
Montgomery in 1942 and later worked for the Alabama Department of
Public Health. She retired in 1969 after 25 years with the agency.
   George Wallace served a record four terms as Alabama governor
before he left office in 1986. He ran for president four times,
including a 1972 bid cut short by an assassin's bullet which left
him confined to a wheelchair.
   Wallace, who has been bedridden for several months, was ``very,
very sad'' about his mother's death, said the younger Wallace.
   Mrs. Wallace is survived by four children, 11 grandchildren and
11 great-grandchildren.
   Funeral services were scheduled for Saturday morning.
</TEXT>
