<DOCNO> AP881028-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0706EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonHostages     10-28 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Hostages,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Civilians Held Hostage At Prison, Freed Unharmed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two convicted murderers who held two women
hostage at a state prison before releasing them unharmed have
histories of violence inside jail, prison records show.
   Inmate Edward Robinson, 27, was disciplined by prison officials
in 1985 for threatening another person and again in 1986 for
assault. Robinson lost 180 days of compensation time that would have
moved up his 1994 parole eligibility. He is serving a life sentence
for murdering a man with a gunshot in the back of the head.
   Inmate Angel Guzman, 26, was disciplined in 1987 for disruptive
conduct and in 1983 had six months added to his 1989 parole date for
a weapon's charge and for assault, prison records show.
   Guzman, who has a tattoo on his forehead reading ``Lucifer Prince
of Darkness,'' is serving a life sentence for shooing his uncle
during an argument over $70.
   After taking the hostages Thursday, the two inmates demanded they
be transferred to a federal prison outside New Jersey and that
officials take no reprisals because of the hostage taking,
Department of Corrections spokesman James Stabile said.
   ``The negotiators agreed that the grievances of the two inmates
would be reviewed,'' said Gary Hilton, deputy corrections
commissioner.
   Robinson also asked to be allowed to call his mother, a demand
Hilton said would be granted.
   Annette Martin, a teaching assistant, and Joan Mason, a
vocational counselor, were taken hostage a 9:07 a.m. Thursday as
they conducted a teaching demonstration in the year-old Northern
State Prison's library, authorities said.
   ``It's hard to tell whether I'll go back to work,'' Mrs. Martin,
46, said after she was released. She declined to comment further.
   Negotiators spent hours talking through a mesh metal window to
the inmates, who used the women as shields while threatening them
with sharpened metal rods.
   ``There were repeated threats that they were prepared to do
violence to the hostages,'' said Hilton.
   He said the women were not physically harmed, but described them
as ``emotionally battered.''
   Mrs. Martin was released at 1:34 p.m.
   Her husband, Isaac Martin, said in a telephone interview that he
learned of his wife's plight from a noon radio broadcast.
   ``I just had to pray that it would come to a happy ending,'' he
said.
   Ms. Mason, 51, was taken from the library on a stretcher at 4:06
p.m., ending nearly seven hours as a hostage.
   Guzman and Robinson were to be transferred temporarily to the
Garden State Reception and Youth Correction Center, Hilton said. He
described the inmates as ``longtime friends'' who had been
imprisoned together before.
</TEXT>
