<HEAD>Hospital Receives DeSillers Checks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh has received
three checks totaling $235,070 from Ronnie DeSillers' estate after a
judge's ruling that the payments be made despite the protests of the
dead boy's mother.
   The payments drawn from Florida banks satisfy charges for three
liver transplants and related treatment for the boy who died in
April 1987.
   Hospital spokeswoman Lynn McMahon on Thursday displayed checks
for $90,000 from Coral Gables Federal bank, $85,070 from Grovegate
Bank of Coconut Grove and $60,000 from United National Bank of Miami
at Hialeah. All were drawn on accounts for DeSillers' estate and
made out to the hospital.
   Ms. McMahon said the checks were sent by the hospital's Florida
attorneys by overnight mail after Dade Circuit Judge Francis
Christie on Monday approved a settlement for the unpaid balance on
the boy's medical bills.
   The settlement amounted to 90 percent of the hospital's
outstanding charges of $261,000 for the boy's care.
   The boy's mother, Maria DeSillers, has been involved in legal
disputes for refusing to pay the balance of the boy's medical bills.
She is accused of withdrawing about $260,000 from the Coral Gables
Federal account, but less than $60,000 has been recovered. The money
was allegedly spent on a used BMW car and jewelry, and some was
given to her ex-husband and her boyfriend.
   Mrs. DeSillers had opposed payment of the balance, at first
claiming her son received inadequate treatment and this week
claiming he contracted the AIDS virus during treatment. The hospital
said the charges are false.
