<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Shamir     10-28 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Shamir,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir: Arab Countries Must Play Role In Any Peace Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said today peace
talks with the Palestinians would be impossible without Arab
countries playing a role and that Egypt and Jordan eventually would
have to join in such negotiations.
   But the right-wing Likud Party leader rejected an international
peace conference proposed by his chief rival in next Tuesday's
parliamentary elections, Foreign Minister and Labor Party leader
Shimon Peres.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Shamir said he backed
U.S. help in the Middle East peace process but opposed participation
by the Soviets or the United Nations.
   Shamir insisted any move toward peace would have to come under
the U.S.-sponsored Camp David Accords signed in 1979 and would have
to include Egypt and Jordan.
   ``I cannot imagine any agreement with the Palestinians without
the help of some Arab countries,'' Shamir said in his office in
Israel's Knesset, or parliament.
   ``I am repeating my demand to resume negotiations about
implementation of the (Camp David) agreement, especially autonomy''
for the Palestinians, he said.
   The 73-year-old prime minister, wearing a gray suit, was relaxed
and smiling throughout the half-hour interview.
   He repeated his objections to an international Middle East peace
conference supported by Peres. He said if his Likud bloc is elected,
Egypt and Jordan would see it as a sign that Israel's people reject
a Peres' proposed international conference.
   ``Therefore, the chances of resuming negotiations in the
framework of Camp David will re-emerge,'' he said.
   Shamir also noted, however, that he has done everything possible
to implement the Camp David agreement, which calls for limited
Palestinian autonomy with their final status to be worked out later.
   He said he did not expect Egypt and Jordan to move quickly toward
talks even if Likud is elected.
   ``There is a necessity for patience and perseverance in the
efforts to convince potential partners to change their minds and
accept our proposals,'' he said.
   Shamir defined the Camp David accords as calling for negotiations
between Israel and representatives of Jordan, Egypt and responsible
Palestinians from within the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
captured from the neighboring Arab nations in 1967.
   In a second stage, Shamir said, elections would be held for a
Palestinian administrative council representing the Arabs in the
occupied lands in talks about the future of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Asked about his initial opposition to the Egyptian-Israeli peace
agreement, Shamir said he had feared it would set a precedent of
returning to pre-1967 borders and destroying Jewish settlements in
the then-occupied Sinai.
   In the campaign he has promised to expand such settlements in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip and vowed not to return any
territory to Arab control.
   Calling the United States ``more than a friend'' of Israel,
Shamir said he would welcome a U.S. role in arranging negotiations
between his government and the Arabs.
   ``We cannot say the same ... about the United Nations,'' he said.
``The U.N. represents a permanent anti-Israeli majority.''
   Asked about a Soviet role, he replied that the Soviet Union has
played a negative role in the Middle East.
   ``The Soviet Union has a very strong anti-Israeli position
regarding our conflict with the Arab world,'' he said.
   Shamir refused to give details about what he would do to end the
``intefadeh,'' the uprising in the occupied lands that led to more
than 300 deaths since it erupted Dec. 8.
   He said he could not rule out the use of greater force but
admitted force could spur more resistance.
</TEXT>
