<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Spokesman Denies Solidarity Hampering Start of Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oppposition spokesman today denied
government allegations that the Solidarity trade union federation is
hampering talks between Polish officials and Solidarity leaders.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said late Thursday that
Solidarity set preconditions to the talks by refusing to drop two
members of its negotiating team _ members the government says do not
respect Poland's ``constitutional order.''
   The two are Adam Michnik and Jacek Kuron, Solidarity advisers and
government critics.
   Urban said Solidarity was trying to blame the government for the
delay in the start of talks but that it was not possible to reach
agreement with activists of a ``confrontational orientation who aim
to destabilize the state.''
   His statement was carried by the official PAP news agency.
   Opposition mediator Andrzej Stelmachowski responded, ``It is not
our side which has the stiff position.''
   ``Today it practically looks like a breakdown, but Lech Walesa
has not closed the door and the affair is open,'' Stelmachowski
said. ``The ball is on the other side now.''
   Walesa, the Solidarity leader, said he will not drop Michnik and
Kuron from the Solidarity delegation, because he said it would set a
precedent.
   ``I see a lack of political will to solve the problems that
divide us,'' Walesa said.
   In addition to the government's objections to Michnik and Kuron,
Walesa complained about the dismissals of at least 100 miners in
Silesia who took part in August strikes and had been promised job
security.
   He refused a government demand that he meet with Interior
Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak to clear up final obstacles to the
start of the talks on political, social and economic reform.
   The government said the talks have begun today if Walesa agreed
to meet Kiszczak.
   The talks were originally proposed in August during Poland's
worst wave of labor unrest in seven years.
   Walesa agreed Aug. 31 to join Kiszczak in talks after being
guaranteed that they could include the topic of the future of
Solidarity as well as broader issues of political and economic
reform.
   Solidarity was suppressed in a December 1981 military crackdown
and was outlawed the next fall.
