<2ND_LINE>PM-Hollywood Teamsters,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Studio Drivers Vote Overwhelmingly To End Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Studio drivers planned to return to
work Monday after voting to approve a new Teamsters contract, ending
their three-week strike against movie and television producers.
   The striking Teamsters voted 1,039-190 in favor of the new pact
during balloting Thursday night, said Earl Bush, secretary-treasurer
of Teamsters Local 399.
   ``That is the official tally,'' Bush said. ``We'll have tomorrow
and the weekend to remove the personnel they hired and we'll go back
to work on Monday.''
   Neither Bush nor producers officials would discuss terms of the
contract.
   Earlier in the evening, striking electricians voted 160-54 to
settle their strike with the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers.
   Neither union expressed satisfaction with the terms of the new
contracts.
   The Teamsters transport actors, equipment and props for
television and film producers. The strike began on Oct. 3. The
tentative settlement was reached last weekend in talks held in
Florida between the producers and Teamsters leaders.
   Joining the Teamsters on the picket lines were 1,000 members of
two other so-called Basic Crafts unions, the electricians and the
laborers. The laborers have since decided to end their strike.
   The strike by the three unions had less of an impact on Hollywood
production than this year's crippling five-month scriptwriters'
strike. Early reports of violence, however, did force the Cannell
Studios to halt production briefly on the NBC series ``Hunter'' and
``Sonny Spoon'' during the strike's first week.
   Key issues dividing the Teamsters and the producers included
overtime rules for weekend work, salary rates, wages for out-of-town
film and television production, studio seniority and guidelines for
the making of nonunion films.
   An earlier contract proposal by the producers had asked some
drivers to take pay cuts from $16.61 an hour to $14 an hour.
</TEXT>
