<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Zambia     10-28 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zambia,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kaunda Wins Landslide Election Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER HEARING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kenneth Kaunda, Zambia's founding
father, easily won another five-year term by receiving about 90
percent of the votes in an election in which he was the only
candidate for the only legal party.
   Three-quarters of the ballots had been tallied by midday today
from Wednesday's presidential and parliamentary election. The ballot
papers were printed with an eagle symbol for the president, a frog
to reject him.
   Kaunda, 64, who led the former British colony of Northern
Rhodesia to independence as Zambia Oct. 24, 1964, has won elections
every five years as the sole presidential candidate.
   The United National Independence Party, the country's only lawful
political movement since Kaunda declared a one-party state in 1972,
fielded 609 candidates vying for the 125 seats in the National
Assembly.
   Results announced from 90 of the 125 constituencies gave Kaunda
just over 90 percent of the vote. There are 2.6 million registered
voters in Zambia.
   The massive ``yes'' vote gave the head of state a mandate to
carry out economic reforms needed to check galloping inflation,
record unemployment and rising urban crime.
   Most government ministers clung to their posts, according to the
results, indicating continued support for a government often accused
of mismanagement and corruption.Three Cabinet ministers lost their
seats.
   Prime Minister Kebby Musokotwane held on to his constituency and
is expected to remain premier in the new Cabinet.
   Kaunda was unlikely to make any statement on the polling trend
until after the final results are announced Saturday, aides said.
   Kaunda needed a simple majority of the ballots cast to remain in
power, or two-thirds of the total registered voters' support.
</TEXT>
