<HEAD>Hearing Set on Question of Genetic Testing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pennsylvania couple who want genetic
testing of a girl they believe is their daughter will get a chance
to present their case to a judge on Nov. 4.
   Sarasota Circuit Judge Andy Owen said Thursday he would hear the
petition of Regina and Ernest Twigg of Langhorne, Pa., who want the
sophisticated blood test to determine parentage of Kimberly Michell
Mays, 9.
   The child is at the core of a developing battle between the
Twiggs and Robert Mays, a 43-year-old Sarasota roofing supply
salesman who has raised the fourth-grader as his daughter.
   The Twiggs allege that their newborn was swapped with a sickly
infant at a central Florida hospital in 1978 in a baby-selling
scheme. They think their baby was given to Mays. The child they took
home from the hospital, Arlena, died of a heart defect in August
after genetic testing that revealed she could not have been their
biological daughter.
   Mays opposes testing. He says the Twiggs base their claim on
speculation and have offered no proof that the child he loves and
raised is theirs.
   He vows to fight any effort to take Kimberly, no matter what any
genetic test might show.
   The Twiggs are prepared to push ahead with a legal custody battle
if necessary, their Clearwater attorney John Blakely said.
   ``If Kimberly is their daughter, they do not know of any fact at
this time that would cause them not to pursue custody of their
child,'' Blakely said. ``They are simply driven by their natural
paternal and maternal instincts to pursue and protect their own
offspring.''
