<HEAD>Dollar Rallies, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rallied from four-month lows against
most major currencies in light European trading early today. Gold
prices moved lower.
   Dealers said the dollar was likely to trade within a narrow range
for the rest of the day.
   The dollar had retreated after the U.S. government reported
Wednesday that the third-quarter gross national product rose at an
annual rate of 2.2 percent, the smallest rise in almost two years.
Dealers said signs of central bank support had kept the dollar from
sliding further.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.18 Japanese yen to a closing 126.08 yen. Later, in
London, it edged up further to 126.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.7830 West German marks, up from 1.7725; 1.5030
Swiss francs, up from 1.4915; 6.0855 French francs, up rom 6.0455;
2.0050 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9977; 1,324.95 Italian lire, up
from 1,320.00; 1.2015 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2024.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7645 from $1.7695 late
Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $407.50 a troy ounce,
unchanged from Thursday's late bid price. At midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$407.30.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $407.10, down from $407.20 bid
late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 65 cents to close at a bid
$409.87.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $6.20 a troy
ounce, down from $6.21 bid late Thursday.
