<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaTrial     10-28 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Trial,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Flying Illegally At Time of Crash, FAA Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of Delta Flight 191 was flying
illegally when his jetliner crashed during a thunderstorm at
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport, killing 137 people, a
federal offical said.
   The medical certification of Capt. Edward M. Connors was invalid
because the pilot failed to list prescription drugs and hospital
stays on his application for certification, Audie W. Davis, a
Federal Aviation Administration medical certification officer,
testified Thursday.
   Delta Air Lines attorneys contend the testimony about Connors'
use of prescription drugs is useless because the co-pilot, who also
was killed, was at the controls when the plane crashed attempting to
land during a 1985 thunderstorm.
   The applications are submitted after pilots take required
physical examinations at six-month intervals, Davis said.
   His testimony came in a non-jury trial of a lawsuit filed by
Delta against the government. The airline claims government
employees, such as air traffic controller and weather forecasters,
did not notify the crew of the doomed airliner that a severe
thunderstorm was located in their landing path.
   Davis, manager of the Aeromedical Certification Branch of the FAA
in Oklahoma City, spent two days on the witness stand.
   Connors failed to fully disclose on his application that he had
been treated at two Fort Worth hospitals and that he had been
prescribed drugs such as the tranquilizer Stelazine and the muscle
relaxer Robaxin, and other antihistamines, antibiotics and
decongestants, Davis said.
   ``The general problem (with the drugs) is how they affect general
alertness,'' Davis said. ``They could cause drowsiness or
dizziness.''
   The government is introducing the medical testimony in an attempt
to show that Connors could have made errors in judgment and was
medically unfit to fly.
   Three doctors testified earlier this week that they did not think
the dosage of Stelazine they prescribed for Connors was strong
enough to affect his flying performance.
   U.S. District Judge David O. Belew recessed the trial until
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
