<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Grosz,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grosz Says He'll Resign As Premier; Will Remain Party Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz said
in an interview published today that he will resign as premier next
month. He will retain the more important job as secretary-general of
the party.
   Grosz, 57, who has held the premier's post for 16 months, has
repeatedly said he wants to focus on party affairs and that the two
functions, of premier and party leader, are too much for one person.
   Grosz took over in May as secretary-general of the Communist
Party, which sets policy in Hungary.
   In an interview with the government daily newspaper Magyar
Hirlap, Grosz said he will ask the Communist Party's Central
Committee to relieve him of his duties as premier.
   The resignation is expected to be approved by the Parliament on
Nov. 24.
   Grosz said five people have emerged as possible successors, but
he did not identify them.
   According to unconfirmed reports, one person high on the list is
Miklos Nemeth, a Politburo member and a party secretary.
   Grosz said he felt ``highly dissatisfied'' with his performance
as premier but added that he was confident of a ``dynamic progress''
in the government's program of economic reforms.
   Under an austerity package passed last year, Hungarians are
suffering under the burden of an 18 percent inflation rate and $18
billion foreign debt.
   Hungary, however, has the Soviet bloc's most free-market oriented
economy.
   Among economic-development goals approved under Grosz are more
foreign investment, fewer restrictions on the ownership of foreign
capital and expansion of private initiatives.
   In his interview splashed over two pages, Grosz also referred to
an official ban on a demonstration Oct. 23 that was to mark the
start of the 1956 anti-communist uprising.
   Several hundred Hungarians defied the ban and police detained
five people for ``making offensive statements.''
   ``On Oct. 23, 1956, the character of the tragic events was mainly
counterrevolutionary, and we cannot permit the memory of a
counterrevolution being marked as a signal event,'' Grosz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
