<HEAD>Man Says IRS Sold Him Fake Gold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who paid $815 at an Internal Revenue Service
auction for what he thought was a 14-karat gold chain has discovered
that he actually bought a worthless imitation.
   Jack LaRue bought the chain this week at an IRS auction of
jewelry, furs and other items seized for back taxes from an
imprisoned heroin dealer.
   ``They had stated that it had a retail value of $1,920,'' LaRue
said.
   ``Right after the auction, I noticed that the clasp was broken,
so I went down to a jeweler,'' he said. ``About half an hour later,
he called me and said, `I hate to tell you this, but the chain is
worthless.'''
   The firm that first appraised the chain for the IRS examined it a
second time and confirmed that it was a phony.
   William Brantley, an IRS supervisor, said the agency can't help
LaRue.
   ``All our sales are final,'' he said. ``We had an appraisal done,
and that's what we went on.''
