<HEAD>Rebellious Gallery Owner Takes Rolls-Royce Fleet To The Street</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rebellious gallery owner, told he
couldn't park his Rolls-Royce for more than an hour on fashionable
Rodeo Drive, used a fleet of the elegant cars to get around the
order.
   David Spellerberg said he had chauffeurs take turns Thursday
parking five different classic Rolls-Royces in front of his art
gallery so that tourists visiting the city would get a taste of what
Beverly Hills is famous for.
   Spellerberg launched his new car show to get around a preliminary
injunction prohibiting him from parking his navy blue 1954 Silver
Wraith Rolls-Royce on Rodeo Drive for more than one hour at a time.
   The order was issued last week by Superior Court Judge Edward
Kakita in response to claims by the city that the $200,000 car is a
nuisance when it is parked continually on Rodeo Drive.
   Police Lt. Robert Curtis said officers carefully watched
Spellerberg's Rolls-Royce rotation and saw no violation of the court
order.
   According to the order, Spellerberg is required to move his car
at least 500 feet away after parking it for an hour in front of his
business and is not allowed to return it there until four hours
later.
   The gallery owner said he plans to continue rotating his cars six
days a week.
   ``We came with the idea of bringing glamour back to Rodeo
Drive,'' he said. ``People come here from all over the world and
expect to see something exciting. Beverly Hills has a tradition to
keep up.''
