<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0523 10-28 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0523,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Preaches ``11 Days an Eternity''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 9 grafs with Dukakis at church, picking up in
4th graf pvs, ``I cannot</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, turning to ``a
little preaching'' in a Baptist church, told black supporters today
they won't be shut out of a Dukakis White House.
   He was introduced at a church rally by the Rev. Wallace S.
Hartsfield, who said that during the Reagan administration there
have been ``a few at the head of the table who refuse to pass the
bread.''
   ``We're not only going to pass the bread, but you're going to be
at the table,'' Dukakis said.
   He opened his remarks by telling the crowd, ``I've got a little
preaching to do.''
   Dukakis also also promised an aggressive stance against the South
African government.
   ``With Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen as president and vice
president of the United States, this nation is going to take the
lead in breaking the back of apartheid,'' he said as the
predominantly black audience cheered.
   Dukakis is trailing in all national polls, but he told the church
audience, ``In politics, as you all know, 11 days is an eternity.
There is time to do it.''
   Dukakis played host at a town meeting Thursday night in nearby
Independence, Harry Truman's hometown, saying he was inspired by the
visit and confident he could, like Truman, pull off an upset.
   After a lively interview on CBS, the Democratic presidential
nominee carried his enthusiasm to the town meeting. Dukakis likened
his stances to Truman's on a number of issues and laughed at
Reagan's statement earlier in the day, during a campaign trip to
Missouri for Bush, that Truman would support the vice president and
the Republican Party today.
   ``I cannot imagine him supporting George Bush,'' Dukakis said,
laughing as he spoke. ``That has to be one of the most incredible
statements of all time. ... I know he'd be four-square behind the
Democratic ticket.''
   The visit to Independence came at a time when Dukakis, trailing
Bush in national polls, frequently invokes the name of Truman and
his 1948 upset over Thomas Dewey to support his prediction that the
same will happen this year.
   Among those questioning Dukakis at the town meeting was John
Truman, the great-great nephew of Harry Truman. John Truman asked
Dukakis if he had anything in common with the late president.
   ``We're a little behind but we're going to win,'' promised
Dukakis.
   ``My memory of President Truman was that he demonstrated his
passion by the things he did,'' said Dukakis, promising to do the
same with health care, child care, economic development and
education programs. ``We're going to put our government on the side
of average families.''
   He also invoked the ``L-word'' Republicans use at every
opportunity to describe Dukakis.
   ``Harry Truman was a liberal who balanced budgets,'' Dukakis
said. ``That's who I am. I'm someone who I like to think combines
those strong, progressive type values'' with fiscal conservatism, he
said.
   Dukakis promised to fulfill Truman's dream of providing basic
health insurance to all Americans.
   ``If Harry S. Truman were here tonight, he'd be urging us to do
it,'' Dukakis said.
   The Democrat also contended Bush had avoided questions in the
final weeks of the campaign.
   ``If you're not willing to get out among people and take
questions and respond in this kind of way, then how do we know what
you're going to do when you're president of the United States,''
said Dukakis, who has hosted three town meetings in less than a week.
   The CBS interview was part of the Dukakis campaign's effort to
broaden their candidate's exposure and to draw a contrast with Bush,
whose style since the second presidential debate appears designed to
protect his lead in the polls by stressing proven themes and
avoiding forums that could create openings for the Democrats.
   During the nearly 15-minute CBS appearance, Dukakis stressed his
theme that he and running mate Lloyd Bentsen are on the side of
average Americans while Bush is the candidate of privilege who wants
to dole out a multi-billion dollar tax break to the nation's
wealthiest 1 percent.
   ``I want the government of this country to be on the side of
average Americans and I think that's a fundamental difference
between me and George Bush,'' Dukakis said in the CBS interview.
   The candidate disputed Bush's portrayal of him as being soft on
crime, taking about the mugging of his father and the hit-and-run
death of his only brother.
   He also constrasted his choice of Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as his
running mate with Bush's pick of Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle.
   ``Dukakis made the presidential decision, Bush made the political
decision,'' Dukakis said.
</TEXT>
