<1ST_LINE>r i PM-FarmersProtest     10-28 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farmers Protest,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Indian Farmers Block Road</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of farmers demanding higher
prices for their crops camped out today with their tractors on a
road leading to the presidential palace and demanded to speak to
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.
   ``If the prime minister has any sympathy for farmers, he will
come to us,'' said Bhopal Singh, a protest leader. ``We will not
talk to his ministers.''
   It was the fourth day of their protest, and they say they won't
move until their demands are met. The farmers have been sleeping in
the shade of tractors by day and burning fires of dried cow dung by
night to keep warm.
   The farmers lined up their tractors on a road leading from the
India Gate war memorial to the presidential palace in New Delhi.
Police blockaded the road about a half mile from the palace but have
not attempted to move the farmers.
   Just in front of the police barrier lay the body of a farmer who
died Thursday of a heart attack. Protesters file past the body,
which was resting on ice slabs and draped in the green flag of the
Farmers' Union.
   The protest has embarrassed Gandhi's Congress Party because it
has scheduled a mass rally at the same place for Monday. That day
marks the fourth anniversary of the assassination of former Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi, Rajiv's mother.
   Protest leaders are demanding that the prime minister meet with
them. They say promises from local administrators were not kept
after the farmers ended a monthlong siege of government offices in
January outside New Delhi.
   The United News of India, a news agency, quoted Gandhi as telling
reporters that he was ``willing to do anything for farmers, but
nothing will be done under pressure.''
   The farmers say they want higher prices for their crops. Their
goods are sold primarily to the government, which stockpiles them
for distribution to the poor at subsidized rates. The protesters
also want the government to waive repayment of farm loans and to
subsidize their electricity bills.
</TEXT>
