<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeathCapDinner     10-28 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Death Cap Dinner,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poison Mushroom Eater Undergoes Liver Transplant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB BAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of five people who ate ``death cap''
mushrooms at a dinner party is recovering from a successful liver
transplant and a nationwide search is underway to find liver donors
for two others.
   The remaining two members of the dinner party who ate the
mushrooms Saturday were being evaluated hourly to determine if they
also will need transplants.
   Dr. C. Wright Pinson, director of the liver transplant program at
Oregon Health Sciences University, estimated the chances were
``50-50'' that enough donor livers could be found for all five.
   Even if they all undergo transplants, they could suffer permanent
brain damage, doctors said.
   At a news conference Thursday in Portland, Pinson said the
patient who underwent surgery and the two awaiting transplants had
suffered irreversible liver damage. When such damage occurs, he
said, the patient usually dies in two to four days.
   ``Even when you list a patient at a very high priority, as we've
listed our patients, it takes an average of 3{ days to find a graft,
so you see we have some inherent logistical problems here,'' Pinson
said.
   Dr. Emmet Keeffe, chairman of the committee that determines who
will get liver transplants at Oregon Health Sciences University,
said doctors believe only three liver transplants had been performed
in the United States because of death cap mushroom poisoning. All
three survived, he said.
   Preston Alexander, president of the Oregon Mycological Society,
identified the mushrooms as Amanita phalloides, which doctors say
are the most deadly of all mushrooms.
   Among other things, the poison prevents the liver from producing
protein. ``Basically, the liver just dies off,'' said Pat Forsyth,
spokeswoman for the University of California-San Francisco Medical
Center.
   The species is common in Europe but has been found only in recent
years in the western United States. Doctors had to speak at length
with doctors in Europe to learn more about the poison, Pinson said.
   Eating less than one of the mushrooms can be fatal, Alexander
said. Dr. Muhamud Daya, assistant professor of emergency medicine at
Oregon Health Sciences University, said the five who became ill ate
a total of at least 10.
   John and Teresa Duncan of Portland were the hosts of the dinner
party where the mushrooms were eaten, Alexander said.
   Alexander said the Duncans' daughter told him some members of the
dinner party had picked the mushrooms while searching for chestnuts
on the Washington side of the Columbia River Gorge.
   The mushrooms resemble a variety that is sold commercially in the
Orient, he said.
   Glenda Sabolyk, 41, of Clackamas, underwent transplant surgery
Thursday at the University of California-San Francisco Medical
Center. Dr. Nancy Ascher, director of the UCSF transplant program
and head surgeon during the operation, said the new liver appeared
to be functioning well.
   Doctors were searching for a donor liver for Mrs. Duncan, 43, who
was in critical condition at Oregon Health Sciences University
Hospital. Her husband, who declined to reveal his age, was in
serious condition at Bess Kaiser Hospital in Portland, where doctors
said he had improved Thursday.
   A fourth patient was at the San Francisco hospital awaiting a
suitable donor, and the fifth was being evaluated at University
Hospital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
