<HEAD>Woman Faces Up To Life In Prison If Convicted Of Perjury In Rape
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who faces up to life in
prison on charges that she falsely accused two men of rape to get
``even'' has been released on bail and ordered to get counseling.
   District Judge Kenneth Kosnic ordered the counseling at a
preliminary examination Thursday and released Christine Burzynski
from the Macomb County jail here on a $5,000 bond.
   Burzynski testified in January that two men raped her at gunpoint
outside a bowling alley in an eastern Detroit suburb.
   But in June, she admitted that she fabricated the charge,
Sterling Heights Detective Gino Hliebay testified Thursday.
   ``She said it had something to do with getting even with them for
some reason,'' Hliebay told the judge.
   After she recanted, prosecutors dropped charges against the men,
who had insisted they were innocent. Polygraph tests showed they
believed they were telling the truth, the detective said.
   Assistant prosecutor Steven Kaplan said the woman had sex with
the two men at a motel on Nov. 5, 1987, the day of the alleged rape,
and that they threatened to tell her boyfriend. The threat
apparently prompted the rape story she told her boyfriend, who in
turn talked her into contacting police, he said.
   ``She got herself cornered,'' Kaplan said.
   Burzynski was arraigned earlier this week on two charges of lying
under oath, which carries a penalty of up to life in prison. She has
not entered a plea and no trial date has been set.
