<1ST_LINE>r i PM-London-RailCrash     10-28 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-London-Rail Crash,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Locomotives Drop off Tracks, Block Highway</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto LON2</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two empty railroad locomotives rolled off an
elevated track today and fell 50 feet onto one of London's busiest
highway junctions.
   The roads were deserted when the pre-dawn crash occurred, and
there were no injuries or damaged vehicles, police said.
   The two 107-ton diesel engines, which were linked, rolled 400
yards forward, crashed through a barrier, and landed one on top of
the other.
   They partly blocked the cloverleaf junction connecting the M1,
London's main northbound exit, to the North Circular Road, the
capital's inner beltway.
   Scotland Yard said the junction, one of London's busiest, might
be shut for several days.
   A spokesman for state-owned British Rail said officials were
investigating.
   ``Clearly brakes don't just come off of their own accord, so
vandalism is not ruled out,'' said spokesman Francis Thomas.
</TEXT>
