<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-DalaiLama     10-28 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Dalai Lama,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Considering Dalai Lama's Proposal for a Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chinese government said today it is trying to
agree on a time and place for talks with the Dalai Lama, Tibet's
exiled leader.
   Chinese officials said in September they were willing to hold
talks with the Dalai Lama at a place of his choice, and the Dalai
Lama agreed.
   However, the Dalai Lama says talks should be based on his June
proposal that China allow Tibet autonomy in domestic affairs. China
rejected this.
   ``We have received the Dalai Lama's proposals for the time and
place of talks. We are considering them,'' Wu Jinguang, a spokesman
for the State Nationalities Affairs Commission, said today. His
department oversees Tibet.
   The Dalai Lama, spiritual leader of Tibetan Buddhists and former
head of Tibet's theocratic civil government, fled to India in 1959
after an abortive uprising by Tibetans against Chinese rule.
Communist China sent its forces to take over Tibet in 1950, acting
on an ancient claim to sovereignty over it.
   From exile, the Dalai Lama has called on China to reduce its
heavy troop presence in Tibet and end alleged human rights
violations. He says the Geneva talks will not center on his return
to Tibet but on the future of the Tibetan people.
   The Dalai Lama on Tuesday said the talks would begin in January
in Geneva. But a second official at China's Nationalities Commission
said the matter was not settled.
   The two sides held official talks in Beijing in 1982 and 1984
without reporting any progress.
</TEXT>
