<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hippie-Settlement     10-28 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hippie-Settlement,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settlement Ends Suit Against City Hall by `Hippies'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Terence in 2nd graf is correct.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple accepted a $220,000 settlement and
ended their four-year, $7 million civil rights suit charging that
officials of New Port Richey harassed them and tried to run them out
of town.
   Erin Sullivan and Terence Brennan claimed city officials labeled
them ``hippies'' and ``troublemakers'' and violated their rights by
trying to silence their protests of city actions.
   The settlement, which included lifting a 4-year-old lien against
their home, came Wednesday just as the case was to go to trial in
federal court here.
   ``We fought City Hall and we won,'' Ms. Sullivan said.
   ``It does close the book, and I'm happy for that,'' added Brennan.
   Brennan and Ms. Sullivan moved to Pasco County in 1981 from
Berkeley, Calif.
   In their lawsuit, they contended that as early as 1982 they drew
the ire of then-mayor George Henry when they attended council
meetings and opposed some of the mayor's favorite projects.
   Former city employees, including the former police chief and fire
chief, testified in depositions that Henry wanted to run the couple
out of town.
   Among other things, the couple were cited for building-code
violations for things such as peeling paint and keeping a dead tree
in their yard.
   When Brennan and Ms. Sullivan sought to dispute the citations,
they were fined. Over time, the fines added up to a cap of $25,000,
the approximate value of their home. Liens were placed on their home
and the city even began foreclosure proceedings.
   Present and past officials of the city just north of Tampa
stressed that the settlement did not constitute an admission of
wrongdoing.
   ``I'm glad it's all over, and there was no admission of guilt,''
Henry said.
   Wednesday's settlement is the second time they have collected
from New Port Richey.
   In 1986, they filed suit claiming city officials violated public
records laws by withholding documents they requested for their
federal case. They won that case, and the city agreed earlier this
year to pay them $49,000 for attorney's fees. The case also cost the
city $22,000 for its own legal fees.
</TEXT>
