<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JournalClosing     10-28 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Journal Closing,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>101-Year-Old Newspaper Begins Final Press Run</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a banner headline reading ``So
Long Jacksonville,'' the 101-year-old Jacksonville Journal ceased
publication today.
   The presses at the Florida Publishing Co. began printing the
final 44,467 copies of the afternoon newspaper at about 10:30 a.m.
in a press run estimated to take about two hours, officials said.
   There were no ceremonies planned to mark the final edition.
Current and past employees are gathering tonight for a party, which
some are describing as a wake.
   The entire front page and three other full pages of the 116-page
final edition were devoted to the newspaper's closing.
   ``The Journal has had a long and distinguished record of service,
commitment and leadership,'' William S. Morris, the publisher, said
in the final.
   ``The Journal is no more, but its spirted love of this community
has not ceased to be,'' he added.
   The final edition featured a picture of workmen removing the word
``Journal'' from atop the building.
   The photo was taken by the Pulitizer Prize-winning photographer
Rocco Morabito, who retired in 1983 after 45 years with the Journal.
   The final page one also included a story about Morabito's 1968
winning photo, ``Kiss of Life.'' The picture shows a power-company
worker giving mouth-to-mouth resuscitation to another worker atop a
utility pole.
   The joint newsroom for editors and reporters for the Journal and
the morning paper, The Florida Times-Union, was quiet as the final
edition was put to bed. Several editors and reporters headed to the
pressroom to watch the final edition printed.
   ``It's like your pet has been ill for a long time and the day
comes when you have to put it sleep,'' said Henry Blumenthal, wire
editor, who was cleaning out his desk. Like all other Journal
newsroom employees, he will assume new duties at The Florida
Times-Union.
   Frederick Hartmann, executive editor, said there will be no
layoffs in the newsroom and any excess should be handled by
attrition.
   ``When you are a dinosaur, you don't want to die, but it is
inevitable,'' said Barbara White, the newspaper's religion editor.
   Morris had noted earlier the demise of afternoon dailies across
the country.
   ``More than 200 afternoon newspapers have ceased publication,
including 23 during the past year,'' Morris said.
   The Miami News, which began 93 years ago, has announced that it
will close if it is not sold by Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
