<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--PoliceBurp     10-28 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Police Burp,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detectives Transferred For Covering Up On-Air Belch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three police homicide detectives have been
reassigned and could face suspension because of a loud belch heard
over Miami police radio several weeks ago, an official said.
   The department's communications computer, which automatically
records all transmissions, identified detective Ron Lemke's
walkie-talkie as the instrument used in the offense.
   Lemke was working a drug murder at the time, with homicide
detectives John Buhrmaster and Al Moreno. When confronted later, all
three denied knowledge of the belch.
   ``They were evasive. They denied it. They were embarrassed,'' Lt.
Mike Gonzalez said. Finally, they talked.
   The offense was not that serious, but the cover-up was
unacceptable, Gonzalez said. The department bounced all three out of
homicide and recommended a week's suspension without pay.
   ``Occasionally guys let their hair down and do childish little
things, but they've got to pay the consequences,'' he said.
