<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlowingPermits     10-28 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plowing Permits,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Law Says All Denver Snow Plowers Need Permits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents with snow plows who are willing to help
clear their neighbors' streets for free will have to obtain some
pricey insurance and a city permit this year, or their good deed
could land them a fat fine.
   ``It's what the city attorney's office says we need to do to
protect the city,'' John Mrozek, director of the Denver Department
of Public Works, said Thursday.
   Mrozek unveiled city snow preparations this week, noting that the
city council hasn't financed plowing of residential streets despite
angry demands after a big storm last winter.
   What the city will do is let neighborhood groups chip in to hire
contractors for plowing, Mrozek said. But those contractors must
have permits and insurance.
   The new regulation is aimed at commercial plowing firms, but
Mrozek admitted that it covers anyone, even the neighbor down the
block with a plow blade on his Jeep who clears the road as a favor.
   ``We can't limit it to one certain segment; we have to open it to
anybody,'' Mrozek said. ``I have no idea whether it will discourage
somebody or not.''
   Mike Musgrave, an aide to Mrozek, said the city would exercise
some judgment about plowing permits, but it won't send squads of
inspectors out to nab people who give neighbors a hand.
   The rule may be clarified, said City Attorney Steve Kaplan.
   Insurance agents gave prices ranging from $350 to $1,260 a year
for the required liability, injury and property damage coverage of
up to $1 million per incident.
   It's a case of legality casting too long a shadow, said
Councilman Bob Crider.
   ``What happens, when you put something into the law and get the
city attorneys involved, they write all that stuff and it takes away
all the fun of life,'' Crider said.
   ``I don't want to say somebody should break the law. But if
somebody wants to clear the road in front of my house, I'd sure give
him a cup of coffee.''
</TEXT>
