<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Bhopal,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing on Bhopal Gas Disaster is Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Court officials today postponed a hearing on
the government's $3 billion lawsuit seeking compensation from Union
Carbide Corp. for victims of the 1984 Bhopal gas disaster.
   Lawyers for the U.S.-based company and the Indian government
appeared in the court of District Judge M.W. Deo to take up
pre-trial matters, but the court clerk said the judge was on leave.
   The attorneys agreed to meet again Nov. 26.
   At least 3,135 people died and 20,000 others were injured when
toxic methyl isocyanate leaked from the pesticide plant operated by
the company's Indian subsidiary. It was the world's worst industrial
accident.
   A high court has ruled that Union Carbide should pay $190 million
in interim relief to victims of the disaster on Dec. 3, 1984 at
Bhopal. However, both the company and government are appealing that
decision in Supreme Court.
