<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CaponeLandmark     10-28 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Capone Landmark,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commission Rejects Bid to Make Capone's Home a Landmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bid to give landmark status to the home of
infamous Prohibition Era gangster Al Capone has been rejected by a
local review panel after pleas from Italian-American organizations.
   The 3-0 vote by the National Register Review Committee of the
Commission on Chicago Landmarks on Thursday is expected to be
appealed by groups seeking to place Capone's home on the National
Register of Historic Places.
   ``Memorialize Al and you stereotype all Italians,'' Carl DeMoon,
president of the Joint Civic Committee of Italian Americans, told
the committee.
   Giving landmark status to Capone's house would honor ``an image
we have tried to bury with him in his grave at Mount Carmel
Cemetery,'' DeMoon said.
   But Tim Samuelson, a program specialist for the landmarks
commission who nominated the mobster's South Side home, argued,
``History is the best weapon we have for putting Capone away once
and for all.
   ``His ghost continues to haunt the city. Chicago has vainly tried
to close its eyes and run away from Capone's ghost, but he has
remained in close pursuit, breathing down the city's neck and
tugging at its coattails,'' Samuelson said.
   DeMoon said the city's Italian community ``is both insulted and
enraged by this attempt to resurrect the fading memory of Al Capone,
Chicago's most infamous Italian-American.''
   An advisory committee of the Illinois Historic Preservation
Agency is expected to consider the issue Dec. 9.
</TEXT>
