<1ST_LINE>u i PM-AbortionPill 4thLd-Writethru a0573 10-28 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Pill, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0573,0698</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Orders Company to Resume Distribution Of Abortion Pill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs with company complying with order. Pickup
4th graf pvs, `The ministry...' DELETES outdated grafs 8-9, `It
was...of anonymity.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health Minister Claude Evin today ordered a
pharmaceutical company to resume distribution of an abortion pill in
the interest of public health, and the company said it will comply.
   The firm, Roussel Uclaf, said it had no choice but to obey Evin's
order. It said it will resume distributing the drug to approved
abortion clinics.
   Roussel Uclaf announced Wednesday it was pulling the drug off the
market in response to an ``outcry of public opinion at home and
aboard'' from abortion foes and a threatened boycott of its products.
   The Health Ministry order was issued after Evin met with
executives of the company, which manufactures the RU 486 pill, also
known as Mifepristone. Roussel Uclaf is part of the giant West
German chemical group Hoescht, which has the majority share. The
French government has a 36 percent share.
   Roussel Uclaf said a ``debate on public morality'' which it was
not qualified to arbitrate led to the decision to withdraw the pill.
   The ministry said Evin summoned Perre Joly, a Roussel Uclaf vice
president, to his office to express displeasure with the company's
decision. It said Evin reminded him that while the company could
make its own decisions, Evin was responsible for public health.
   It said the 1975 law legalizing abortion in France must be
applied and that voluntary abortions ``constituted a right for women
in this country.''
   ``RU 486 is an advance because it does not involve use of an
anesthetic. The precautions for supply of this drug, solely in
specified (abortion) clinics, provides for all the required
indispensible guarantees of security,'' the communique said.
   ``With the interest of the public's health involved, Claude Evin
called on the Roussel Uclaf laboratory to resume distribution of RU
486 and the laboratory said it would do so,'' the statement said.
   Abortion foes, including the Roman Cathlic church, had welcomed
the company's decision to suspend distribution, while social
leaders, physicians from around the world and some politicians
opposed it.
   The drug's inventor, Etienne Emile Baulieu, said the pill has
been used in France on 4,000 women with a 95.5 percent rate of
effectiveness.
   On Thursday, thousands of doctors attending a convention in Rio
de Janeiro called on Roussel Uclaf to continue making an abortion
pill or pass the patent onto another manufacturer. The physicians
are attending the weeklong World Congress of Gynecology and
Obstetrics.
   Officials at the Health Ministry maintained the company acted in
order to protect its image abroad. Company officials said they had
been inundated with mail from France and abroard, especially the
United States.
   They said many letters threatened to boycott the company's
products.
   Andre Ulmann, a Rousse Uclaf official who helped develop the
pill, told a news conference at the Rio conference that the
threatened boycott would have cost the company substantial sums of
money, ``So we decided to stop making the drug.''
   He did not specify the costs involved.
   The pill blocks the action of progesterone, a hormone essential
in all phases of pregnancy. Researchers say it is effective in the
first seven weeks of pregnancy, particularly when used in
conjunction with a second product called Sulprotone, or
prostaglandin E.
   They said the drug was not a do-it-yourself, morning-after pill
that could be purchased at a supermarket and taken home. Its use
requires medical supervision. The government announced authorization
of the drug Sept. 23. It has also been tested for use in China and
India.
   Baulieu, also at the Rio meeting, said Roussel Uclaf had decided
to withdraw the drug for moral reasons.
   ``There is absolutely no medical basis for the suspension, which
comes despite the approval of the drug by both the French and
Chinese governments in terms of safety and efficiency, Baulieu said.
   ``The company is bowing to pressure from church groups and
conservative sectors of society, '' he said.
</TEXT>
