<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--FemaleClub     10-28 0124</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Female Club,0126</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chilton Club Opens Doors to Men</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the 78-year-old, all-woman Chilton Club
have voted to make men eligible for membership.
   Without the change Thursday, the club could have lost its food
and liquor licenses under a Boston Licensing Board regulation
banning discrimination on the basis of sex, race or religion in
accepting members.
   Earlier, the Chilton had notified the board that it would seek an
exemption to the rule on the basis that it was organized for purely
social reasons, not for business purposes. The club has 900 members.
   On Tuesday, the all-male Tavern Club, which also had said it
planned to seek an exemption from the rule, announced it would begin
accepting women as members.
</TEXT>
