<DOCNO> AP881028-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Mood Bjt   10-28 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Mood, Bjt,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Optimism, Helplessness in the Dukakis Camp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the clock runs down on Michael Dukakis'
presidential hopes, a mixture of determined optimism and
helplessness envelopes the campaign staff jetting back and forth
across the country with him.
   Poll findings suggest his chances of victory over George Bush on
Nov. 8 are small.
   But the candidate's group of aides and advisers generally avoids
negative talk or fingerpointing over what went wrong in a campaign
that once held a double-digit lead in polls.
   ``Outside the fact we're all tired, the mood is excellent,'' said
Francis O'Brien, a senior adviser traveling with the candidate. ``We
wake up and say, `we're going to win.' That's what I believe.''
   Yet he adds: ``Now is it going to be hard? Are we behind? Yes.''
   Dukakis himself has seemed uplifted on occasion by his crowds,
which sometimes are quite large. He spoke with what seemed to be
fresh resolve in invoking Harry Truman's come-from-behind memory
this week.
   And his staff was positively euphoric, for the moment, after what
they considered a good interview Thursday night with Dan Rather on
CBS.
   But other times he has seemed startlingly emotionless and
reserved _ such as in his live interview on ``Nightline'' Tuesday
night.
   ``Dukakis is Dukakis,'' said campaign senior adviser Kirk
O'Donnell, ``He's as cool as they come.''
   O'Donnell was trying to persuade reporters that Dukakis'
colorless performance in that 90-minute network opportunity was not
the disappointment many observers believed it was.
   Dukakis has seemed a bit wan at other times, too. In an interview
on CNN, host Larry King asked: ``Do you think you've got a good
shot?''
   Dukakis replied simply: ``I think we've got a shot.''
   In the ABC interview, he said, ``I found it very difficult to
give people in this country a real sense of who the real Mike
Dukakis is.''
   ``You know, people have said I'm kind of cool and don't have
enough passion. ... It's very difficult to convey that.''
   Privately, some campaign staffers have revealed feelings and
frustrations _ and a hint of exasperation. One staffer, musing about
needing a vacation, said he would have plenty of opportunities in
another two weeks.
   Although open sniping hasn't broken out, there are private
suggestions that Dukakis himself has been unwilling sometimes to go
along with advisers ready to arm him with sharp, attention-getting
lines.
   A perception took hold that Dukakis had booted away a last
opportunity by a bloodless performance in his second debate with
George Bush in Los Angeles. The mood was reinforced after his
Nightline performance.
   Standing the next day in a room set up with telephones for
reporters to file their stories, O'Brien, the good-humored adviser,
felt the sting of a reporter's wit.
   ``Don't worry Francis,'' he was told playfully. ``Bob Beckel made
a lot of money after running a losing campaign.''
   It was a reference to Walter Mondale's 1984 campaign manager, who
has gone on to become a widely quoted analyst on television
commentary programs.
   Reporters constantly search for a metaphor for the Dukakis
campaign.
   Some saw one at a rally at Diablo Valley College in the suburbs
east of Oakland. Half a dozen buzzards circled lazily overhead
before Dukakis spoke.
   Others found it in Pueblo, Colo., where a brilliantly colored
hot-air balloon stood by the platform at a rally _ and fell to the
ground, deflating, after he spoke.
   On the campaign plane, aides point to polls showing single-digit
deficits as signs of encouragement.
   O'Donnell tried selling the line that the Nightline show was a
great success and represented a ``crescendo.''
   But the campaign took on an aimless quality the next day. Dukakis
stuck with his same stump speech, adding very little. As a
consequence, reporters had little new to write their stories about _
so many wrote about the campaign's dismal outlook.
   Aides insisted that the plan was to stick with the us-versus-the
rich economic theme, along with his continuing complaints about
nasty campaign tactics from the other side.
   ``What do you expect us to say at this point?'' said Steve
Engelberg, a traveling aide.
</TEXT>
