<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CarolinaFugitive     10-28 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carolina Fugitive,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Task Force Arrests Man Who Fled 13 Years Ago From Carolina Road
Gang</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ORANGE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who escaped from a prison chain
gang in South Carolina 13 years ago was back in custody today after
his arrest by a special task force for federal fugitives, police
said.
   Kenneth Lee Davis told agents after his arrest Thursday that he
had expected to be arrested shortly after his August 1975 escape,
but became more comfortable about remaining free as time passed,
said Jeff Fortier, special agent with the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement.
   Davis, 43, along with brothers Joe and Bobby, owns Davis Brothers
Painting Inc., a paint-contracting company in nearby Daytona Beach.
   Davis was serving 20 years for armed robbery, burglary, larceny,
forgery and two previous escapes. The 1975 escape was the third for
Davis in less than four years, agents said.
   For the past 10 years, Davis has lived in a mobile home park
surrounded by retirees and families with children, Fortier said.
   He will remain in the Volusia County jail until he is returned to
South Carolina, Fortier added.
   The arrest was part of Operation Intercept, a program that
established a task force of federal, state and local police agencies
devoting their time exclusively to federal fugitive cases in several
Southern states.
</TEXT>
