<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarveyGoof     10-28 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvey Goof,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broadcaster Gives Listeners Snow Job on Buffalo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syndicated news commentator Paul Harvey
buried Buffalo with nonexistent snow and then got snowed in himself
with complaints from angry residents.
   Harvey opened his 8:30 a.m. broadcast Thursday with an erroneous
report that the city at the eastern end of Lake Erie had received a
foot of snow. Although rural hamlets in the hills south of Buffalo
got several inches of snow overnight, the city's streets were clear.
The sky was sunny Thursday morning and temperatures were in the 40s,
in fact.
   ``We want a retraction,'' said Robert Carr, vice president of the
Buffalo Chamber of Commerce. ``It just furthers the inaccurate
perception that we're snowbound from Oct. 1 to April 1.''
   Mayor James Griffin also was angered by the broadcast and called
Harvey.
   ``I guess you take your weather pretty seriously,'' said John
Talmage, a researcher for Harvey.
   Harvey's office said the information came from a story by United
Press International. The UPI story, however, did not say there had
been snow in the city, only in an area several miles south of
Buffalo.
   The veteran broadcaster offered a correction on his 12:05 p.m.
broadcast.
   ``Well ... my usually reliable sources were not quite right,''
Harvey said, adding that now Buffalonians won't believe him when he
says two whales are trapped by ice in Lake Erie.
</TEXT>
