<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Prisoners     10-28 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Prisoners,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Editor Vows to Press For News on Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of a Soviet magazine has
promised to give the Soviet attorney general a list of 223 political
prisoners to be published in a respected emigre publication.
   Vitaly Korotich, editor of Ogonyok magazine, told delegates at a
seminar in Barcelona that he ``promised to take the (prisoners) list
to prosecutors'' to get information. Korotich was referring to a
list of 223 names that Soviet exile editor Kronid Lubarski that his
respected Munich-based magazine Country and World was to publish
Sunday.
   Korotich's statement on Thursday, reported in the daily newspaper
El Pais, came one day after West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said
in Moscow the Soviet Union had agreed to release all people regarded
in the West as political prisoners by the end of the year.
   Lubarski told the seminar there was some doubt about 56 of the
names on his magazine's list of political prisoners in the Soviet
Union, but assured them that the other 167 ``are in jail for their
political beliefs.''
   Both men were in Barcelona to attend a seminar on perestroika,
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of economic and political
restructuring.
   Korotich, whose Ogonyok magazine has been prominent in battling
for greater public debate on important questions in the Soviet Union
under Gorbachev's policy of glasnost or openness, harshly criticized
the Soviet system of justice.
   Saying the matter of political prisoners in the Soviet Union was
being handled in a questionable manner, Korotich said: ``It is not
known in which way they (the prisoners) were arrested and some have
been released in an unknown fashion.
   ``If they were arrested illegally, then those who did the
arresting should be tried for it under the law,'' Korotich said.
``If they (the political prisoners) were released although they were
guilty, why was that done?
   ``If it is thought that the prisoners have committed some crime,
then let them be publicly tried for it so we can know what they are
accused of and (watch) with the penal code in our hand,'' Korotich
said.
   Korotich at one point compared the Soviet justice system to that
of the Spanish Inquisition.
   Lubarski told the seminar he was disappointed with the statement
by Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov in which he
indicated the Soviet Union only held two dozen political prisoners.
   ``There are at least 10 times that many political prisoners,''
Lubarski said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
