<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ChambersTrial     10-28 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chambers Trial,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Brothers Convicted of Running Cocaine Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four brothers accused of running a cocaine
operation that controlled half of Detroit's crack houses were
convicted today on drug and related charges.
   Larry, Billy Joe, Otis and Willie Chambers were among eight
people convicted by a U.S. District Court jury that had spent 13
hours over three days reviewing weeks of testimony.
   Prosecutors said the Chambers reigned over Detroit's largest
crack cocaine operation, supplying up to half the city's 1,000 crack
houses with the drug.
   ``They controlled the cocaine, they controlled the houses, they
controlled the workers who handled cocaine,'' Assistant U.S.
Attorney Lawrence Bunting said in closing arguments.
   No sentencing date was set by U.S. District Judge Richard
Suhrheinrich, who revoked bond for all the defendants.
   ``The court finds that this conspiracy is a threat, a serious
one, to this community,'' he said.
   Several former gang members testified during the trial the
Chambers used promises of excitement and big money to lure people _
many from the Chambers' hometown of Marianna, Ark. _ to Detroit.
Gang members said they were paid up to $1,500 a week, but also said
they were kept in line with threats of physical punishment and even
death.
   Defense attorneys throughout the trial had criticized prosecution
witnesses, saying they had been paid and promised immunity in return
for testifying against the gang.
   Larry and Billy Joe Chambers could face up to life in prison for
their convictions on operating a continuing criminal enterprise.
Larry Chambers also was convicted of illegal firearm possession,
cocaine possession and conspiracy. Billy Joe Chambers also was
convicted of cocaine possession and conspiracy. Both pleaded guilty
earlier to income tax evasion.
   Willie Chambers, whose case was heard by Suhrheinrich instead of
the jury, was convicted of conspiracy and tax evasion.
   Otis Chambers, Belinda Lumpkin, Jerry Lee Gant, Marshall Glenn
and Eric Lamar Wilkins were convicted of conspiracy. Elaine Coleman
Lucas was convicted of cocaine possession. They could face up to 20
years each in prison.
   Paul Lamont Young, identified in the trail as the recruiter for
Detroit-area gang members, was acquitted.
</TEXT>
