<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusAttack     10-28 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Attack,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Teen Assaulted By Blacks On City Bus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white teen-ager was tied up, assaulted and
robbed by a group of 20 blacks aboard a bus in an attack police say
was racial in nature.
   The victim, whose name was not given because he is a juvenile,
was on his way home from school Thursday when he boarded a Transit
Authority bus in the borough of Queens.
   A group of about 20 blacks were already on the bus when the
15-year-old got on, said Detective James Coleman, a police spokesman.
   ``They passed a rubber exit cord (on the bus) and one of them
ripped it off,'' Coleman said. ``One suspect was heard to say,
`Let's tie someone up.'''
   The teen-ager moved to the front of the bus near the driver but
the gang of blacks moved in on him, Coleman said.
   Several restrained him while he was tied up with the cord and
carried to the back of the bus ``where he was kicked in the head and
body, and ethnic comments were made,'' Coleman said. He said he did
not know exactly what was said.
   The suspects also allegedly stole $5 from the teen-ager.
   It was not immediately known what the bus driver did during the
assault or if there were any other passengers on the bus.
   The group of black youths got off the bus and fled, Coleman said.
The teen-ager, whose father is a retired police sergeant, was taken
to North Shore Hospital where he was treated for cuts and bruises
and released.
   The teen-ager reported the incident to police Thursday. The case
was given to the Bias Investigative Unit early Friday.
   Transit Authority spokesman Jared Lebow said the agency was
trying to locate the bus driver, who had not reported the incident.
   The assault is the second racial incident reported this month.
   On Staten Island, a group of black youths and several white men
exchanged racial slurs outside a bar Oct. 7. About a half-hour
later, Derrick Antonio Tyus, 17, was struck and killed by a car.
   Police are investigating to see if the racial incident and the
accident are linked. Black youths involved in that incident told
police they were being chased by several whites when Tyus was
accidentally struck by a car.
</TEXT>
