<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VanderbiltSlaying     10-28 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vanderbilt Slaying,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Suspect in Slaying of Vanderbilt Kin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Friday they have no suspects and had
found no signs of forced entry into the oceanfront mansion where
Cornelius Vanderbilt III, distantly related to the 19th-century rail
baron, was found stabbed to death.
   Vanderbilt, 72, had been dead a short time when his body was
discovered in a first-floor hall Thursday morning by James Brunton,
37, who has shared Vanderbilt's home on Staten Island for five
years, police Lt. William Quinn said.
   Quinn said Brunton had been asleep upstairs and came down to
investigate noises.
   Vanderbilt headed Vanbro Construction Co., which he inherited
half a century ago.
   Vanderbilt's relationship to ``Commodore'' Vanderbilt, who left
Staten Island to make a fortune in shipping and railroads, was
through his grandfather, Cornelius Sr., who was described by the
Staten Island Historical Society as a distant cousin.
   The slain man's father, Cornelius G. Vanderbilt Jr., died in
April of 1941 at age 53, hours before he was to have appeared before
a grand jury investigating corruption in the paving industry. The
father was found in Richmond Creek, but an autopsy established heart
attack as the cause of death and police listed it as an accident.
</TEXT>
