<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietJewry     10-28 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Jewry,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Agree To Jewish Cultural Center In Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has agreed to a ``joint
venture'' with American Jews for the opening of a Jewish cultural
center in Moscow, Jewish sources said Friday.
   Details of the project will be discussed next week in Moscow
between Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze and Edgar
Bronfman, president of the World Jewish Congress, the sources said.
   The decision, which contrasts sharply with decades of official
repression of Jewish cultural and religious life, reflects the
widesweeping changes undertaken by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev in
the Soviet society and economy.
   Until recently, the teaching of Hebrew and practice of Jewish
culture often resulted in jail terms on trumped-up charges ranging
from anti-Soviet propaganda to drug possession.
   An understanding in principle on the cultural center was reached
last May in talks Bronfman held with Soviet officials, including
Shevardnadze and Konstantin Kharchev, chairman of the state
committee on religious affairs, said the sources.
   ``The Soviets have given the green light for this joint
venture,'' said one source, who declined to be further identified.
What remains to be discussed are the funding and exact location of
the center, he said.
   The center will include a library, museum and rooms for
celebration of weddings, bar mitzvahs and other religious
ceremonies, the sources said.
   If the Moscow project is successful, similar centers will be
opened in Kiev and other Soviet cities, they said.
   The center will be run by Soviet, American and European Jewish
groups in a building supplied by the government, the sources said.
   The handful of synagogues allowed to operate in the Soviet Union
are run by the state under close supervision.
   The agreement is the latest in a series of changes affecting the
lives of the estimated 2.5 million Jews living in the Soviet Union.
Authorities allowed some 12,000 Jews to emigrate this year, up from
the 8,700 allowed to leave last year and a significant increase over
the estimated 900 exit visas granted in 1986.
   The easing of restrictions also has affected other ethnic and
religious minorities, who are enjoying greater freedom under
Gorbachev.
   The changes also have extended to Soviet relations with Israel,
which Moscow cut off in 1967. An official Soviet delegation went to
Israel last year and an Israeli consular team is in Moscow now.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-VirginiaSenate Bjt   10-28 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Virginia Senate, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robb's All-American Image Bruised By Battle For Senate In Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles S. Robb _ Marine, LBJ's son-in-law,
two-term governor _ is still expected to run away with the U.S.
Senate election in Virginia, but his all-American image has been
battered by attacks from his Republican opponent.
   Maurice A. Dawkins, a 67-year-old black lobbyist and retired
minister, has bruised Robb with questions about associating with
alleged cocaine-users and about a state gambling investigation.
   ``For the governor of Virginia to permit cocaine dealers and
cocaine users to carry on under his nose, well, it's not wisdom,
it's arrogance,'' Dawkins said at a campaign debate.
   Robb, often mentioned as a future presidential candidate, accused
Dawkins of using ``character assassination of the basest sort.''
   The level of nastiness in the campaign is unprecedented in
Virginia, where political high spirits usually are leavened by
patrician gentility.
   ``Both candidates have been diminished, even the likely landslide
winner,'' said Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia political
scientist.
   But Robb's problems do not end with Dawkins' attacks from the
right. On the other side, Jesse Jackson forces were angry at him for
not backing Jackson's presidential bid and for suggesting that the
civil rights leader play a limited role in the presidential
campaign. Jackson won the state's presidential primary in March.
   Robb's nomination was likened to a coronation. A handsome former
Marine Corps officer, he was known only as former President Lyndon
Johnson's son-in-law when he ran for lieutenant governor in 1977,
but four years later he led a sweep of Democrats into the state's
top three offices, ending 12 years of GOP rule. He would be
Virginia's first Democratic senator since 1972.
   Dawkins, meanwhile, has raised a relatively tiny amount to
finance his campaign, has laid off all but one staff member and
blames his troubles on racism and the news media.
   Dawkins was the last of four Republicans to seek the nomination,
and his victory at the state GOP convention in June was seen by some
party leaders as a token gesture to steal the thunder of Virginia
Democrats, who are expected to nominate Lt. Gov. L. Douglas Wilder,
another black, for governor next year.
   Dawkins' only other political race was an unsuccessful bid for
the GOP nomination for lieutenant governor in 1985.
   Robb has a strong record of fiscal soundness to please
conservatives. He appeals to moderates for opening positions of
power in state government to blacks and women.
   He has used his big lead in the polls to take some potentially
unpopular stands, including possible support for a tax increase to
control the deficit.
   ``Don't expect me to do everything that you are going to think is
in your short-term interest,'' Robb said. ``Assume I'm serious
enough about solving some of the problems that whatever your
favorite program is, I don't care what it is, think of that as being
in peril.''
   At the start of the Senate campaign, Robb was the target of a
noisy demonstration staged by Jackson supporters at the state
Democratic convention.
   More troubles followed. By Labor Day, Robb was fielding questions
about published reports that, while governor, he attended parties in
Virginia Beach where cocaine was used.
   A subsequent story said Robb's social ties to people who were
targets in a police investigation of illegal gambling hampered
investigators, who allegedly were told not to mention Robb in their
official reports.
   Robb has denied seeing anyone use cocaine and said he did not
interfere in the gambling investigation. But the allegations gave
Dawkins ammunition to question Robb's judgment.
   Dawkins also has accused Robb of having a plantation mentality
toward blacks and has urged black voters to try the GOP for a change.
   While Robb's image has suffered, campaign polls this fall show
his support ranging from 56 percent to 66 percent. Dawkins,
meantime, has drawn from 12 percent to 19 percent.
   Robb, with $2.7 million in fund-raising, has continued to
campaign as if the election were tight. Dawkins has raised less than
$200,000 and stopped campaigning for almost two weeks this fall to
devote more time to seeking money.
   At a news conference last week, Dawkins blamed the press and, to
some extent, racism for his troubles. He then walked out, refusing
to answer questions.
   Dawkins' campaign ``has redefined what a political disaster is,''
said Sabato.
   But the cocaine party and gambling probe stories have tarnished
Robb's squeaky-clean image and could affect any ambitions he has for
higher office, Sabato said.
   ``You never say never, but I think he's certainly been damaged,''
Sabato said. ``I think he's been hurt.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
