<DOCNO> AP881028-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CollisionAlert     10-28 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Collision Alert,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Airline Collision Avoidance System Mistakes Ships for Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airliners testing new collision avoidance
systems sometimes have been unable to tell the difference between an
oncoming plane and a Navy ship sitting in the water below, a Federal
Aviation Administration official said Friday.
   The problem is with electronic signals being sent out by Navy
ships, said Joe Fee, manager of the FAA's airborne collision
avoidance and data systems branch.
   Despite the testing difficulties, however, Fee said the problem
can be corrected before mandatory Traffic Alert and Collision
Avoidance Systems are installed on all larger U.S. passenger
aircraft beginning late next year.
   The systems, which are designed to automatically alert pilots
when another plane is near, will be required on all planes carrying
more than 30 passengers in the United States by the end of 1991. The
system reads signals from transponders aboard other aircraft and is
designed to supplement, not replace, air traffic control systems on
the ground.
   The problem with ship signals was first reported in the current
issue of the electronics industry newsletter Military Avionics.
   The Times Union & Journal of Jacksonville, Fla., reported Friday
that a Piedmont airliner testing the equipment last year found that
the system went haywire as the plane was landing at Jacksonville
International Airport, warning the pilot that he was in close
proximity to five other aircraft.
   It was picking up signals from ships at the nearby Mayport Naval
Station, the report said.
   Fee, in a telephone interview, said the problem probably can best
be corrected by having Navy ships emit a signal that gives their
altitude _ sea level _ which currently is not a part of the signal
emitted by the Navy's IFF, for ``identification, friend or foe,''
system.
   Most airplanes emit signals that give their altitude, but some
smaller ones do not, so their signals would be identical to those of
Navy ships. The problem would be most obvious at airports that are
near Navy installations, such as Jacksonville and Norfolk
International Airport in Virginia.
   ``It's kind of a nuisance thing that we think can easily be
fixed,'' Fee said, adding that some other minor improvements still
need to be made in the system before regular installations begin.
   The FAA already has set standards for the collision alert system,
and has been trying them out on a handful of aircraft flown by
Piedmont, United and Northwest airlines. The Northwest test is still
under way.
   Three companies manufacture the collision alert systems, which
are expected to cost in excess of $100,000 each to install on more
than 3,000 aircraft: Bendix-King of Ft. Lauderdale, Fla.; Honeywell
of Phoenix, Ariz.; and North American Rockwell's Collins Division in
Cedar Rapids, Iowa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-DeManio     10-28 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-De Manio,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BBC Radio Broadcaster Jack de Manio Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack de Manio, a British Broadcasting Corp. radio
broadcaster for 34 years who was renowned for his rich, husky voice
on a breakfast-time news show, died Friday at the age of 74.
   De Manio died in St. Stephen's Hospital after a long illness,
said his wife, Loveday.
   He began his career as an announcer on the BBC's worldwide radio
service, and won fame during 13 years with the ``Today'' news and
current affairs program. He left the show in 1971 because, he said,
``I am tired of getting up so early in the morning.''
   De Manio was the first journalist to get a radio interview with
heir to the throne Prince Charles in 1969, and was notorious for
frequently giving incorrect time checks.
   He moved from ``Today'' to his own afternoon show, ``Jack de
Manio Precisely,'' which was replaced after seven years by a program
on the day's proceedings in Parliament. He retired from radio in
1979.
   De Manio wrote two books, ``To Auntie with Love'' in 1967 and
``Life Begins Too Early'' in 1970, and contributed to the satirical
magazine Punch and other periodicals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
