<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Israel     10-28 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Israel,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Travel Agents Pull out of Jerusalem Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 British travel agents have pulled
out of a tourism convention in Jerusalem after receiving protests
and a boycott threat from Palestine Liberation Organization, a
spokesman said Friday.
   About 3,000 delegates had been expected at the four-day
convention of the Association of British Travel Agents opening
Monday, but just under 1,700 have registered, said association
spokesman Martin Symington.
   The PLO's London office sent letters to all prospective delegates
appealing to them to stay away, and threatened to mobilize 2 million
Moslems in Britain into boycotting travel companies that attended.
   ``We do not take lightly attempts to belittle or ignore the
sufferings of our people,'' the PLO letter said, referring to the
11-month-old Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
   Jerusalem consists of a Jewish sector and an Arab sector annexed
after Israel captured it in the 1967 Mideast war. Most Western
governments do not recognize it as the capital.
   The convention was to have been held in Torremolinos, but the
venue was switched because a new convention center in the Spanish
resort had not been completed, Symington said.
   ``It's obviously disappointing that there are fewer people
attending this year,'' Symington said.
   ``We understood the reasons for delegates not going as there have
been problems of a political nature,'' he said. ``But Jerusalem was
the only place which met our convention requirements when we had to
change venues.
   ``To have pulled out would have been a political gesture and we
are an apolitical body.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1509EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PhobiaConvention Bjt   10-28 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phobia Convention, Bjt,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conquering Fear of Fear Itself Is Subject of Phobia Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If flying in an airplane makes you unbearably
dizzy, David Barlow will spin you in a chair until the room dances.
If a subway ride makes your heart race, he'll give you coffee to
simulate the sensation of panic until you overcome it.
   Barlow, a psychologist who teaches at the State University of New
York at Albany, was among the 420 experts and phobics gathered
Friday for a weekend convention on the fear of fear itself, also
known as anxiety attacks.
   The objective of the ninth National Conference and Training
Institute on Phobias and Related Anxiety Disorders is to find a
salve for discomfort widely suffered but not entirely understood.
   Barlow knows of what he speaks. About 10 years ago, he was under
the stress of a new job when he panicked at giving a speech. He
cured himself by jogging and orating at the same time to simulate
and overcome the breathlessness of sudden anxiety.
   He developed this technique into a treatment in which the
physical sensations of anxiety and panic are recreated, based on the
theory that people who suffer anxiety attacks are hypersensitive to
their bodily reactions. As a consequence, these people monitor
themselves, vigilantly waiting for another panic attack. When
attacks occur, an interior dialogue rages: Is this pounding heart
just a healthy muscle or is it the irrational foreboding of some
unknown disaster?
   Patients at Barlow's clinic are taught to reinforce rational
thoughts over the irrational fears.
   Estimates of how many Americans suffer from crippling anxiety and
phobias range from 2 million to 12 million, according to the
National Institute of Mental Health.
   Anxiety attacks were believed for a long time to be a heart
condition. Now, psychologists recognize that these experiences can
lead to phobias _ irrational, excessive and persistent fears.
   Phobias focus on specific situations that cause anxiety, such as
flying, subways, crowds or driving. There is the dizzying panic of
vertigo that can strike on a mountainside or an escalator, or the
loss of voice at having to speak in public, the No. 1 fear,
according to Jerilyn Ross, president of the Rockville, Md.-based
Phobia Society of America.
   Her organization is sponsoring the convention with Massachusetts
General Hospital and Harvard Medical School.
   The most devastating phobia is agoraphobia _ a fear of being in
public. Seeking to avoid the panic attacks that come when they are
among others, agoraphobics shun society, sometimes keeping to their
homes for decades. Only since the 1970s has serious attention been
paid to finding ways to relieve it.
   Treatments for anxiety and severe phobia include gradually
exposing the patient to the experience they fear, teaching them
breathing exercises to reduce the hyperventilation related to panic
attacks and sedatives.
   Women suffering from anxiety often retreat into depression. For
men, alcohol often is a way to cope. Studies show that 50 percent to
60 percent of alcoholic men began drinking to soothe anxiety, Barlow
said.
   One of the convention participants is Lisa D., a 33-year-old
lawyer who once felt the only secure place in the world was her
bedroom. It began when she was 17 and her stepfather abandoned the
family. One day the industrious, gregarious student panicked on a
ride to the beach.
   ``It was just the most uncomfortable, frightening feeling, a
feeling like you're short of breath, shaking all over. A sense that
you're just going to lose control. Time freezes and speeds up at the
same time and you just want to get to a safe place,'' recalled Lisa.
   Soon it became difficult to drive a car or even walk down the
street.
   She fought back and got herself to the University of Maryland,
where a full life there distracted her. But three years ago, with
her career under way, Lisa began panicking again. By then she had
read about agoraphobia and knew what was wrong. Lisa called a hot
line and was referred to a clinic for phobics.
   Although the attacks have ceased, Lisa is not entirely free, she
said. ``I don't think I'll ever be 100 percent comfortable about it,
but I'm able to say I'm not avoiding life because of it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1510EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Reagan-ForeignPolicy     10-28 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Foreign Policy,580</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 3:45 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Calls for Strong Defense, Contra Support, Pursuit of SDI</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This will stand instead of the promised lead
^By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan outlined his unfinished
foreign policy agenda today, saying his successor should maintain a
strong defense, support the Contra rebels and pursue the Strategic
Defense Initiative.
   In remarks prepared for delivery to the World Affairs Council, a
non-partisan foreign study group, Reagan said those steps were
essential to safeguard America, and Western civilization, from the
worlds' ``archvillians.''
   But Reagan also predicted that if his course of ``peace through
strength'' is maintained, a new strategic arms accord with the
Soviet Union is attainable ``in the next few years.''
   The president, while boasting of the improvement in U.S.-Soviet
relations that brought forth a treaty banning an entire class of
nuclear weapons during his administration, said much work will be
left to his successor.
   Responsibililty, he said, also falls on the voters, who on Nov. 8
will ``make decisions that will affect the world and our foreign
policy consensus for a great long time to come.''
   Reagan did not mention Vice President George Bush, the GOP
candidate, or his rival, Democrat Michael Dukakis, by name.
   ``Whatever the future may hold, it is safe to say: we have come a
long way and this is a portentous time,'' Reagan said.
   ``Let us remember that great steps have been taken in the last
few years, steps to safeguard against archvillains _ not to mention
the blowing up of the world. Of course, let us not be satisfied, and
certainly not smug. But let us be appreciative of what has happend
and determined to build on that progress,'' Reagan said.
   ``Change, indeed, is inevitable,'' Reagan said. ``No one should
doubt the instability of the present situation in Eastern Europe, in
which an artificial economic and political system, long imposed on
these people against their will, is more and more exposed as
bankrupt and discredited.''
   Calling the ``new degree'' of tolerance and experimentation under
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev welcome, Reagan also said that
``Moscow's handling of the growing drive for self-determination
within its European empire will be a vital test for us, of how deep
is the transformation of Soviet foreign policy in a new era.''
   He said the United States should hold to a strategy that ``means
not only maintaining our defenses and vigorous diplomatic
engagement, but also candor about and to our adversaries, support
for freedom fighters around the globe, and encouragement of human
rights and democratic reforms within the Eastern bloc.''
   The president called on Congress to ``give up the double
standard'' of supporting freedom fighters in one part of the globe
and not another. ``We must support the Contras'' in Nicaragua, he
said.
   On his space-based nuclear missile defense plan, known as SDI,
Reagan said, ``We must aggressively pursue the research, development
and testing.''
   ``Now is the time to redouble our efforts, not cut them back,''
he said, Congress, in the current fiscal budget, has mandated cuts
in the president's requests for the program.
   On the nation's defenses, Reagan said, ``We must keep our entire
defense structure strong,'' arguing that the ``enormous sacrifices''
that have been made to rebuild the military have only begun to ``pay
handsome dividends in peace initiatives across the globe.''
   Reagan's foreign policy speech came as he made his last
pre-election swing through his home state, where he was attempting
to enlist California and its bounty of 47 electoral votes for
Republican presidential nominee George Bush.
</TEXT>
