<DOCNO> AP881028-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO     10-28 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Ministers Urge New Short-range Arms, Belgium Balks at Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense ministers ended talks
Friday with a call for modernizing short-range nuclear weapons, but
Belgium refused to endorse a report laying out proposals for the
program.
   ``I see no hesitation,'' said U.S. Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci. ``We are going ahead on a step-by-step basis toward
modernization.''
   However, Belgian Defense Minister Guy Coeme told reporters that
his nation's center-left coalition government abstained from
endorsing the ministers' report on short-range weapons.
   ``Assuming any commitment now would be premature,'' he said.
   The issue is controversial in Europe, where the front-line
weapons would likely be targeted in a conflict.
   Despite Belgium's abstention on the report, Carlucci and the
other defense chiefs of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization said
Friday in their final statement that the alliance needed the
short-range nuclear arms in its arsenal. Their statement made no
mention of Belgium's hesitation.
   The short-range weapons have received new attention since the
United States and Soviet Union signed a treaty in December to
eliminate all intermediate-range land-based nuclear missiles.
   Most NATO nations want to extend the range of short-range, or
tactical, weapons up to the treaty limit of 300 miles.
   ``For the foreseeable future, NATO requires diversified,
survivable and operationally flexible nuclear forces in Europe
across the entire spectrum of ranges,'' the ministers said at the
end of their two-day talks at the Hague.
   NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner said the ministers made no
decisions on specific weapons systems this week.
   British Defense Minister George Younger said such decisions will
be taken as early as next year.
   The ministers' secret report, prepared earlier by their staffs,
calls for a new, longer range air-to-surface missile that could be
fired at Soviet air defenses from a NATO warplane. It also backs
U.S. work on replacing the Lance surface-to-surface missile, which
military analysts say will be obsolete in 1995.
   Details of the report became known when the London-based Campaign
for Nuclear Disarmament released a summary prepared by the Belgian
Defense Ministry.
   The defense chiefs meet twice a year to plan nuclear strategy.
Fourteen of NATO's 16 members take part, with Iceland attending as
an observer. France operates outside NATO's military command.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
