<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada     10-28 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Has Turner Winning Debates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poll published Friday said Liberal Party leader
John Turner won the two campaign debates, in which he and Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney had angry exchanges about the new
U.S.-Canadian trade agreement.
   The agreement, scheduled to take effect Jan. 1, has become the
dominant issue in the Nov. 21 general election. It would phase out
all remaining tariffs over a 10-year period, and Turner said it
``will reduce us ... to a colony of the United States.''
   Ed Broadbent of the socialist New Democratic Party joined Turner
and the Conservative prime minister in the six hours of televised
debates, the first half in French on Monday and the second in
English the next evening.
   Broadbent also opposes the trade agreement.
   According to the poll, conducted by Environics and published by
the independent Globe and Mail of Toronto, 46 percent of those
familiar with the debates said Turner won, 19 percent chose Mulroney
and 10 percent favored Broadbent.
   Free trade was judged the most important election issue by 76
percent of those surveyed. Environics said the poll was based on 811
interviews and the margin of error was 3.4 percent.
   A Gallup poll that covered only Tuesday night's debate, published
by the Toronto Star, had 72 percent favoring Turner, 17 percent for
Mulroney and 11 deciding Broadbent won.
   The last Gallup poll before the debates found 40 percent for the
conservatives, the New Democrats in second with 29 percent and the
Liberals with 28 percent.
   That outcome probably would give Mulroney a parliamentary
majority.
   On Thursday, Mulroney said his rivals were being ``shameful and
dishonest'' in their attacks on the trade agreement.
   Turner, whose party has been a dominant force in Canadian
government through much of this century, said in the debate the
agreement reverses 120 years Canadian of resistance to U.S. pressure.
</TEXT>
