<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionPill-Explainer 1stLd-Writethru a0639 10-28 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Pill-Explainer, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abortion Pill Blocks Hormone Action In Uterus
^Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 7th, `The prostaglandin...' to include
description of how drug is taken.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion Pill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The French drug RU 486 blocks pregnancy after
conception by interfering with a hormone that is essential to the
maintenance of pregnancy.
   The hormone, progesterone, is secreted normally during the latter
half of the menstrual period, said Dr. Irving Spitz, the director of
clinical research at the Population Council in New York, who is
studying the drug.
   ``One of the major effects of progesterone is to mature the
lining of the uterus so the egg can be implanted,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   Researchers had been searching for such a drug for more than two
decades, Spitz said. ``This is the first drug to be found that could
actually block the action of progesterone,'' he said.
   When progesterone's action is blocked, the uterus sheds its
lining. Any egg that might have been fertilized and implanted in
that lining is shed along with the uterine lining.
   RU 486 itself terminates pregnancy in about 75 percent of women
who use it during the first six weeks of pregnancy, Spitz said. To
boost the drug's effectiveness, doctors also prescribe a
prostaglandin, one of a group of hormone and hormone-like chemicals
in the body.
   The prostaglandin causes uterine contractions. The combination of
RU 486 and the prostaglandin is effective in about 95 percent of
women during the first six weeks of pregnancy, Spitz said.
   The drug's manufacturer recommends that it be taken in one dose,
followed three days later by a dose of prostaglandin, Spitz said. In
France, the drug is given only at abortion clinics, so that doctors
can monitor its effectiveness. The drug is not available over the
counter.
   Doctors will want to counsel the 5 percent of women in whom the
drug is not effective, he said. And some women who take it will
bleed excessively.
   The entire process of terminating pregnancy is usually complete
in seven to 14 days, Spitz said.
   Spitz said he is not aware that anyone in the United States has
taken steps to market the drug. To do so, a company would be
required to file a new drug application with the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration.
   It would likely take at least several years before such an
application would be approved, Spitz said.
   Hoechst Roussel Pharmaceuticals in Somerville, N.J., which is
affiliated with the drug's French manufacturer, Roussel Uclaf, said
Friday it had no plans to study or market the drug.
   Gynopharma Inc., also of Somerville, had been rumored to be
negotiating to market the drug in the United States. It has since
denied that it has plans to do so.
   Laura Giles, spokeswoman for Gynopharma, said Friday that the
company has not negotiated with Roussel Uclaf and is not petitioning
the FDA to allow marketing of the drug.
   Spitz said that RU 486 blocks progesterone by interfering with
progesterone ``receptors'' on cells in the uterus.
   ``It works very similar to a lock and key,'' he explained. ``All
hormones work on receptors. The receptor is the lock; the hormone is
the key.''
   The drug causes nausea and vomiting in 13 percent or 14 percent
of women who use it, he said. It sometimes causes bleeding and pain
as well, but those are ``normal accompaniments of the abortion
process,'' Spitz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Brigades     10-28 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Brigades,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brigades Vets Honored on 50th Anniversary of Departure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DELMONICO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For most of the 45 Americans present,
Friday's ceremony marking the 50th anniversary of the departure of
the International Brigades from the battlefields of the Spanish
Civil War was the last hurrah.
   ``It's probably the last watershed when such a gathering could be
held,'' said Steve W. Nelson of Truro, Mass., the 85-year-old
commander of the Abraham Lincoln Brigade of U.S. volunteers who
fought on the side of the Spanish Republic in the 1936-39 Civil War.
   The unveiling of a bronze sculpture of David looking down at
Goliath by New York artist Roy Shifrin was the centerpiece of a
ceremony presided by Barcelona's Socialist Mayor Pasqual Maragall in
honor of the Oct. 28, 1938, departure of International Brigades
veterans from the conflict that many saw as a prelude to World War
II.
   About 300 former Brigades members from 20 countries attended the
ceremony.
   The monument and the cost of the ceremony were underwritten by
contributions from, among others, Pete Seeger, Ed Asner, Allen
Ginsberg, Leonard Bernstein, Greogory Peck, Woody Allen, Harry
Belafonte, Studs Terkel, Kurt Vonnegut and Gloria Steinem. The city
of Barcelona provided the land.
   As the Barcelona city band played, Nelson said the sculpture was
``a symbol for the people to recall the great struggle of the
International Brigades who helped to delay a major part of the
Second World War.''
   The brigades were the idea of the Comintern or Third Communist
International to provide support for the Second Spanish Republic
following the nationalist rebellion of Gen. Francisco Franco in July
1936.
   Franco's troops received men and materiel from Nazi Germany and
Italy.
   Historians estimate 35,000 to 50,000 volunteers, many with no
formal connections to the Comintern, fought on the losing side,
defending the Second Republic in the war that ended with a victory
by the Franco forces in April 1939 and a subsequent 36-year
dictatorship.
   Nelson said of the 3,000 Americans who fought on Spanish
battlefields, some 300 are alive today in the United States. Another
800 died in the war.
   Bob Reed, 73, of Seattle marched in the Oct. 28 farewell parade
50 years ago in Barcelona.
   ``That was really a magnificent display of feelings,'' he said.
``The people were giving us flowers, the kids were riding on the
shoulders of the brigade members. It gave us a feeling of not losing
the war but of coming out with renewed determination.''
   Civil War historian Hugh Thomas says Soviet dictator Josef Stalin
decided to withdraw the Brigades from Spain when he ``despaired of
being unable to form an alliance with France and Britain against
Hitler'' following British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain's trip
to Munich in September 1938.
   The withdrawal of the Brigades was a gesture of goodwill toward
Nazi Germany that led to the signing of a non-agression pact between
the two nations a year later.
   Gabriel Jackson, professor emeritus of history at the University
of California at San Diego, told the U.S. veterans veterans that for
the surviving members of the International Brigades, the restoration
of democracy in Spain after Franco's death in 1975 was ``like a
victory 40 years later.''
   ``None of us would have believed there could have been a change
to democracy without another bloody revolution in Spain,'' said
Mosess Fishman, 75, of New York.
   Oct. 28 is also the sixth anniversary of the 1982 landslide
victory that swept the Socialists to power in Spain in general
elections for the first time since the outbreak of the Civil War.
   Steve Nelson said much of the 1950s McCarthy-era backlash against
the Lincoln Battalion veterans _ 60 percent of whom were either
members of the Communist Party or sympathizers, he said _ had
subsided.
   ``Young people are fascinated by the subject. There isn't a day
goes by at our New York office that we don't get calls or letters
from students or other people writing books about the subject,'' he
said.
   Bob Reed took advantage of the visit to continue his trip into
the past, to the fishing village of Malgrat de Mar on the
Mediterranean coast where the troop ship carrying him to Spain in
1937 was sunk a mile offshore by an Italian submarine.
   ``We went there cold,'' Reed said, ``but a young lady at the
tourist office was delighted to meet people she had read about in
history books.''
   Reed and several other survivors met with the mayor and
discovered that the bodies of six victims of the wreck, including
possibly an American, were buried in the Malgrat de Mar cemetery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1527EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     10-28 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush Hiding ``In His Little Cocoon''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis derided George Bush
as hiding ``in his little cocoon'' on Friday and defended his own
ridiculed ride in an Army tank, saying the Reagan administration was
trying to cut tank production.
   Dukakis has been interviewed on a series of network television
programs recently as he tries to make up ground in the polls, and he
accused his Republican rival of avoiding such encounters as the
election nears.
   ``Mr. Bush is out there in his little cocoon. They won't let him
out,'' Dukakis said. ``We're taking our case directly to the
American people.''
   Dukakis displayed a battling-back demeanor at a large and raucus
rally at a college outside Detroit, just a few miles from his Sept.
13 ride in an Abrams M-1 tank. That ride has been mocked in
television commercials by Bush.
   ``Let me tell you why I was in that tank factory,'' Dukakis said
at the rally in the crowded fieldhouse at Macomb Community College.
   ``I care about those people. I care about what they're making,''
the Democratic presidential nominee said. ``I'm deeply concerned
about this administration's plans to cut back on tank production
while spending billions and trillions on Star Wars.
   Dukakis also jabbed at Bush for a remark the vice president made
while watching Soviet tank maneuvers in Europe.
   ``I am very concerned,'' Dukaks said, ``when a vice president of
the United States who wants to be president comes back from Europe
and says to the American people, `I'd like to bring some of those
Soviet mechanics over here to tell American workers what to do.'''
   His paraphrase of Bush's words brought boos from the crowd in the
town where tanks are manufactured.
   ``I don't think we need any Soviet mechanics telling American
workers how to produce,'' Dukakis said.
   He also pointed to a series of problems and accidents at nuclear
facilities at Savannah River in South Carolina, Rocky Flats in
Colorado and Fernald, Ohio. He pledged to ensure nuclear production
facilities are not a threat to workers or communities.
   Dukakis appeared in Michigan with Gov. Jim Blanchard, who said he
thought Dukakis was improving everywhere. Dukakis claimed the same,
saying: ``It's tightening up here in Michigan _ it's tighting up all
over the country. You can know it, feel it and sense it.''
   Top campaign official John Sasso told reporters that polls taken
by the campaign showed Dukakis gaining nationally this week and
drawing close in the important state of California.
   Independent polls have shown national Bush leads of eight to 15
points, but Sasso said ``there is measurable movement this week'' in
Dukakis' direction. He declined to give exact numbers.
   Sasso contended that Dukakis is getting across his argument that
Bush has run a harshly negative campaign to avoid addressing major
issues.
   Dukakis was continuing his 11th hour strategy of television
interviews, and in Michigan he sat for an NBC-TV session to be aired
next week.
   He also has purchased several blocks of 5-minute network prime
time.
   Dukakis began his day in Kansas City, Mo., where he spoke to a
small crowd in the basement of the predominantly black Metropolitan
Missionary Baptist Church, pledging strong action _ by backing
international sanctions _ against apartheid in South Africa.
</TEXT>
