<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having problems with the hands on your
grandfather clock? Afraid you'll be an hour early for everything
this Sunday?
   Fear not. There's help for the time-impaired on the eve of the
annual switch from daylight-saving time back to standard time _
provided you can get to Manhattan in time.
   An upscale watch retailer said Friday it would turn back the
hands of timepieces free of charge this weekend, on anything from
wristwatches to alarm clocks to grandfather clocks.
   ``Anything. Whatever you want turned back, we'll do it for you,''
promised Kristen Hoppmann, spokeswoman for the Tourneau watch
company.
   The service is available at Tourneau's four Manhattan locations _
where the company sells watches that run from $150 to $150,000 _
even if your favorite timepiece came from your local discount house.
   ``It doesn't have to be one of ours. We'll take care of it
anyway,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on the business wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Martino had a short career at AT&T. So
short, in fact, that the company was still announcing his arrival
the day after he quit.
   Martino set a new standard for revolving-door employment this
week when he became the vice president in charge of AT&T's
1,000-member computer sales force, and then returned to his old
employer, IBM.
   ``He started working Monday morning and he left Tuesday
afternoon,'' Dick Muldoon, a spokesman for American Telephone &
Telegraph Co., said Friday. ``We are absolutely assured that his
decision was personal and it was not because he was dissatisfied
with business plans or directions.''
   AT&T executives were still telling securities analysts about the
high-level appointment as late as Wednesday, the Wall Street Journal
reported Friday.
   International Business Machines Corp. said Martino, 38, was on
special assignment to David M. Thomas, president of the National
Distribution Division in Montvale, N.J. He worked previously in
IBM's Applications Systems Division in Valhalla, N.Y., overseeing
software development.
   ``All I know is he left and after one day he decided to return.
He does not want to be interviewed,'' IBM spokesman Douglas DeLay
said.
   Muldoon added: ``He was very well respected _ at both companies.''
</TEXT>
