<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan has been honored for her
efforts urging women to take early steps to battle breast cancer.
   Mrs. Reagan, who recovered last year, received the 1988 Betty
Ford Award on Thursday.
   ``I know how hearing the word `cancer' or `malignancy' can just
absolutely freeze you with fear,'' Mrs. Reagan told an audience of
more than 2,000 people. ``But that fear should never keep you from
facing up to the need for mammograms'' for detection.
   Former first lady Betty Ford, who also recovered from breast
cancer, presented the award.
   Jill Eikenberry, a star of the NBC-TV series ``L.A. Law,'' also
was honored by the Susan G. Komen Foundation, the event's sponsor.
Mrs. Eikenberry, who had breast cancer two years ago, was recognized
for ``Destined to Live,'' a television special on the subject
broadcast earlier this month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles, who's made a habit lately of
roasting London's skyline, found a new way to have a go against
post-World War II architecture.
   The heir to the throne wrote and starred in a 75-minute
documentary in which he dons a hardhat, takes the controls of a
crane and gleefully wields a wreckers' ball against a condemned
multistory parking lot.
   Charles stirred controversy earlier by saying builders have done
more damage to London than Hitler's air force. He returned to that
theme in the British Broadcasting Corporation film intended for
broadcast Friday night.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired actress Helen Hayes gave
mixed reviews of her latest performances on a lecture tour.
   Miss Hayes, 88, told an audience at Purdue University ``I cannot
do without you,'' but said earlier Thursday at a news conference
that her stand-up gig made her a little nervous and she wanted to
stay home and tend her roses.
   ``Old age is not something I've staved off, it's something I've
achieved,'' she told the crowd of 3,000. ``I'm having a ball.''
   ``I cannot bear to be parted from a live audience. You've been my
very best friends for 80 years and I cannot do without you.''
   The actress said earlier: ``I haven't got used to it, the
nervousness. This is my fourth lecture and I have another next week
and then I'll not do any more. I'm also lazy. I don't like the
travel part. I want to tend my roses and stay home.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial must go on for actor Paul
Newman, whose appeal for dismissal of a lawsuit against him was
turned down in state Appellate Court.
   The legal battle, which ended in mistrial June 23, is with a
delicatessen owner over profits from Newman's Own salad dressing. A
second trial is scheduled next week in Bridgeport.
   The appellate court refused Thursday to dismiss Julius Gold's
lawsuit against Newman, writer A.E. Hotchner and food broker David
Kalman.
   Gold says he helped develop and market the dressing and was
promised 8 percent ownership. Newman contends he developed the
dressing in his Westport home.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first American woman to climb Mount
Everest said Friday she left a Susan B. Anthony dollar on the summit.
   ``When I reached the top, I did not think of being the first
American woman as I happened to achieve my personal goal,'' said
Stacy Allison, 30, of Portland, Ore.
   Allison, a carpenter, reached Everest's 29,028-foot summit on
Sept. 29 after a 10-hour climb. Last year storms forced her to turn
back at 27,224 feet. ``There was really no difficulty,'' she said.
``Women are equally strong like men. They are good decision makers,
too. Really I did not see any difference between men and women.''
   Asked why others had failed, she said: ``The cause was not
because of anything else except that the teams (which included
women) had not been in a position due to unfavorable weather on the
mountain.''
   On Oct. 2, Allison's teammate, Peggy Luce of Seattle reached the
top.
   ``This was my first expedition. I feel incredibly fortunate ...
(and) very lucky,'' Luce said.
   A Japanese housewife, Junko Tabei, was the first woman ever to
climb Everest in 1975.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marc Buoniconti and his family have
dropped their bid for a new trial in their failed lawsuit against
The Citadel's football team doctor.
   ``After some soul searching (the Buonicontis) decided not to go
forward with the appeal,'' said attorney William H. Grimball.
   A jury decided July 14 after a five-week trial that Dr. E.K.
Wallace Jr. was not negligent in his advice and treatment of
Buoniconti before the football player suffered a paralyzing injury
in a 1985 game.
   The 21-year-old son of former Miami Dolphins linebacker Nick
Buoniconti sought $23 million in punitive and actual damages.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the singing DeBarge brothers was
sent to the Kalamazoo County Jail pending sentencing Jan. 19 on a
cocaine conviction.
   U.S. District Judge Richard A. Enslen refused Thursday to release
Robert ``Bobby'' DeBarge, 32, of Los Angeles on bond, saying he
might flee.
   Enslen set $25,000 bond for Jonathon ``Chico'' DeBarge, 22. He
had not posted bond and remained in custody Friday.
   The brothers were convicted Tuesday with two other men of
conspiring to bring cocaine from Los Angeles for distribution in
Michigan.
   Jonathon DeBarge faces a maximum of 45 years in prison and Robert
faces 89 years.
   Jonathon recorded solo album ``Chico DeBarge'' in 1986. Robert
was a member of the singing group Switch.
</TEXT>
