<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1549EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CadetsSticken Bjt   10-28 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Sticken, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AG Says Officials Should Have Known Of Problems In Police Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hospitalization of police cadets from a state
academy exposed a brutal training regimen hidden from public
scrutiny despite many warning signs, but no one will be prosecuted,
the state attorney general said Friday.
   Attorney General James Shannon said his investigation found a
``top-to-bottom'' failure by the state to protect the cadets, most
of them from small-town police departments.
   He said he could find no statute under which to press charges,
that there was no evidence of intent by State Police trainers to
harm the cadets and that the ``diffusion of responsibility'' made it
unfair to prosecute individuals.
   But Shannon said the chief of the agency responsible for the boot
camp-like training should resign or be dismissed.
   ``The failure began with a bureaucracy that paid little or no
attention to the end product of its paper-shuffling: the care and
training of human beings,'' Shannon concluded.
   ``Instead, like the three monkeys of the legend, and despite the
existence of cause for alarm, the training bureaucracy saw no evil,
heard no evil and spoke no evil.''
   The investigation was limited to one class of the police training
academy in Agawam in western Massachusetts, one of 11 operated by
the state Criminal Justice Training Council. The class, which began
Sept. 19, included 50 cadets from local police forces seeking
certification as full-fledged police officers.
   The academy and its methods came under scrutiny when cadet
Timothy Shepard collapsed, slipped into a coma and had to undergo a
liver transplant at a Pittsburgh hospital, where he has regained
consciousness but remains unable to speak.
   At least 10 other cadets were hospitalized for ills stemming from
intense exercise and dehydration, the report said. One cadet was
quoted by the attorney general as saying his urine was ``as brown as
Hershey's syrup.''
   According to a Springfield doctor who coordinated the medical
response, at least 16 cadets were admitted to hospitals.
   Shannon's report documents a grueling regimen of ``modified
stress training'' and unrelenting exercise, defended by academy
officials as necessary to prepare for the rigors of police work.
When a cadet failed to keep up, the entire class would be punished
with extra push-ups or other exercises.
   ``I expressly reject the contention that exercising cadets ...
until they drop can meaningfully be termed `training,''' Shannon
wrote.
   Shannon said at a news conference that the officials involved
should have known there were problems at the academy.
   According to the report, Agawam Fire Department records show 12
ambulance runs to the academy from 1984 to this year to assist
trainees. Eleven calls required taking a cadet to a hospital. ``That
should have indicated a problem,'' Shannon said.
   He said responsibility belonged with the state troopers who
conducted the class, the directors of the academy and the 23-member
Criminal Justice Training Council, of which he is a member.
   Shannon told reporters that he did not believe Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis, who appoints the council, bore any blame.
   He said Gary Egan, the council's executive director, who took a
paid leave of absence starting Wednesday, should ``either resign or
be removed immediately.'' Egan's phone number in Wellesley is
unlisted.
   Shannon did not spell out how he thinks training should be
conducted, saying he hoped that issue would be addressed by separate
investigations being conducted by the Legislature and the governor's
office.
   His report detailed the physical training that took up most of
the first day of a class in February as an example. A videotape made
that day documents 2{ hours of morning training, showing that the
group performed 188 push-ups and that some cadets did more as
punishment.
   Investigators noted that most cadets had just two water breaks
during the day, taking a single 3-ounce cup of water.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1554EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CadetsStricken Bjt   10-28 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken, Bjt,0668</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0667 to fix typo in keyword.</NOTE>
<HEAD>AG Says Officials Should Have Known Of Problems In Police Training</HEAD>
