<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 2023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zambia     10-28 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zambia,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zambians Give President New Five-Year Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER HEARING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zambians voted overwhelmingly to give
President Kenneth Kaunda, the nation's founding father, another
five-year term in office, according to results released Friday.
   While the final outcome of Wednesday's presidential and
parliamentary elections are not expected until late Saturday, Kaunda
captured 93.6 percent of the ballots counted so far, officials said.
   The results were from 90 of the 125 constituencies.
   Kaunda, 64, who led the former British colony of Northern
Rhodesia to independence as Zambia Oct. 24, 1964 was the only
presidential candidate. Voters marked an eagle if they supported
Kaunda and a frog if they opposed him.
   Also up for election were the 125 seats in the National Assembly.
There were 609 candidates for the seats.
   Despite Zambia's severe economic problems, Kaunda has remained
popular and has served five terms. Most Zambians believe he has done
well in keeping their country free of civil strife that plagues
other African nations.
   One of the first tasks confronting him is the nation's $5 billion
foreign debt, which saps 40 percent of export income.
   The massive ``yes'' vote arms him with a mandate to carry out
economic reforms needed to check inflation, record unemployment and
rising urban crime.
   Key ministers were re-elected, strengthening Kaunda's hand in
seeking badly needed economic reforms.
   Prime Minister Kebby Musokotwane held on to his constituency and
is expected to remain premier in the new Cabinet.
   Kaunda is unlikely to make any statement on the polling trend
until after the final results are announced Saturday, aides said.
   He needed a simple majority of the ballots cast to remain in
power, or two-thirds of the total registered voters' support. Zambia
has 2.6 million registered voters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
