<DOCNO> AP881028-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 2024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Grain-China     10-28 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grain-China,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Subsidized Wheat Sold to China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exporters have sold China an additional 550,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices for shipment in
January, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   The sales, equal to about 20.2 million bushels, were handled by
six companies: Cargill Inc., 70,000 tons; Continental Grain Co.,
160,000; Richco Grain Ltd., 40,000; Louis Dreyfus Corp., 120,000;
Ferruzzi USA Inc., 130,000; and Nichimen America Inc., 30,000.
   Christopher E. Goldthwait, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said the sales were part
of an authorized 2 million tons of wheat announced on Aug. 18 under
the Export Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Goldthwait said the latest sale all but used up the Aug. 18
authorization, leaving only 10,000 tons still available to China.
   Although no selling prices or other details were announced,
recent prices of wheat at farm points have averaged around $3.80 per
bushel, indicating a U.S. farm value of about $77 million.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   The program enables exporters to sell wheat and other designated
commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in order to
meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Goldthwait said the bonuses due the six exporters for the latest
deal averaged $19.12 per ton of wheat, or about 52 cents per bushel.
</TEXT>
