<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 2025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DetroitNewspapers     10-28 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Detroit Newspapers,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foes Of Detroit JOA Argue Against Partial Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foes of the planned partial merger of Detroit's
two daily newspapers argued in court Friday that neither the papers'
circulation nor advertising revenues were in the classic ``downward
spiral'' that warrants merging business and production operations.
   At issue before a three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals was whether then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III properly
gave the Detroit Free Press and The Detroit News permission to form
a joint operating agreement.
   The decision Meese made before leaving office last summer has
been stayed while under court challenge by a group of readers and
advertisers.
   The Michigan group contends neither daily is a failing newspaper
deserving of an antitrust exemption under the 1970 Newspaper
Preservation Act.
   The Free Press, owned by Knight-Ridder, Inc., and the News,
purchased in 1986 by Gannett Co., Inc., sought the joint operating
agreement as a way to stem continuing losses by both newspapers
since 1980. Both have weekday circulations of more than 600,000.
   Opponents' attorney William B. Schultz said the only reason the
two newspapers have lost money is their eight-year battle to put
each other out of business by drastically cutting advertising and
circulation rates.
   ``On the day that they announced they were going to apply for the
JOA, both papers stated that they had fought this competition to a
virtual draw,'' Schultz said.
   ``There was ample support for the operation of two newspapers''
in Detroit, he said.
   ``It was true that the Free Press was losing money,'' Schultz
said. ``But it's true that the News was losing almost as much.''
   Knight-Ridder's attorney, Clark Clifford, argued that ``the Free
Press is not a strong paper. It is only what it is because in the
last eight years or so Knight-Ridder has pumped in $176 million _
that's what kept it alive.''
   Locked into this money-losing competition, ``There is nothing
that the newspaper can do without violating the antitrust laws by
calling up the News and say `let's have a price increase,''' said
Justice Department attorney Douglas Letter.
   Meese accepted the administrative law judge's factual findings
but not the recommendation that he reject the partial merger. Meese
concluded that if he denied the JOA, Knight-Ridder would carry out
its threat to close the Free Press, which has lost $100 million
since 1980.
   Schultz said Meese irrationally ignored the administrative law
judge's scenario that a rejection of the joint operating agreement
would prompt the News, and in turn, the Free Press, to raise their
prices.
   The administrative law judge predicted that both papers would
then make money.
   Schultz said Meese never explained why he ignored the
administrative law judge's rejection of testimony from Gannett
Chairman Allen H. Neuharth, who vowed that the News would never
raise its prices.
   Judge Laurence Silberman questioned whether the court could
second-guess Meese's ``reasonable prediction that if the JOA is
denied that the News will not raise its prices.''
   Silberman said the administrative law judge essentially concluded
that ``the Free Press is not quite on its knees'' while Meese found
that ``they haven't waved a white flag yet but it looks like they
are shot full of holes.''
   A lower-court judge upheld Meese's decision under which the two
dailies would publish separate morning and evening newspapers but
combine their advertising, business and production facilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TrappedWhales 2ndLd-Writethru a0636 10-28 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trapped Whales, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0636,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rescuers To Give Troubled Whales Another Chance To Reach Sea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to update with whales apparently swimming
to freedom, picking up at the 13th graf previous, beginning ``The
mammals' plight.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARROW, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two whales trapped for more than two weeks
by encircling Arctic ice apparently swam to freedom before daylight
today, after days of effort by Eskimos and icebreakers, an official
said.
   ``They were last seen at 8:45 a.m. They were looking good,''
North Slope Borough Mayor George Ahmaogak said after talking by
radio to Eskimos who had gone to open breathing holes for the
whales. The last sighting was about an hour before sunrise.
   ``I feel great. I feel like I got no more burden,'' said Arnold
Brower, the senior whaling captin who directed the Eskimo rescue
efforts of cutting breathing holes in the ice with chain saws.
   Asked if he was confident the two California gray whales swam to
freedom, actually open channels in the ice leading to ice-free water
200 miles away, rather than died, Brower replied: ``Yes.'' A third
whale disappeared a week ago and was presumed dead.
   As night fell Thursday in sub-zero temperatures, rescuers had
left the whales in a breathing hole just 330 yards from open water,
a distance that federal whale biologist David Withrow called
``essentially one long dive.''
   Twice Wednesday, the giant mammals traveled more than 300 yards
under the ice to reach new breathing holes, he said. But they
appeared reluctant to traverse the distance Thursday.
   The Eskimos crews had gone out early today to cut additional
holes to coax the animals toward the open water, said Ahmaogak.
   The whales' condition appeared worse after they struggled through
the slush and ice left in the icebreakers' wake Wednesday night and
Thursday. Both bled from multiple but superficial cuts.
   The Soviet icebreaker Vladimir Arseniev and its companion ship,
the Admiral Makarov, had remained nearby and offered to lend further
assistance by cutting a second path through the ice off the northern
Alaska coast. The ships then planned to depart for their home port
of Vladivostok.
   Rear Adm. Sigmund Petersen of the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration said the Soviet crews were ``ready to go
home.'' Their ships had been at sea for nearly six months and were
diverted for the last three days to assist the whale-rescue effort.
   ``We're here until those whales depart from the area,'' Ron
Morris, the rescue coordinator, said before the whales disappeared
early today. He said that if it was evident the whales had reached
open water, then ``that's all we're going to do ... the whales are
on their own.''
   The whales were caught in the arctic ice for nearly three weeks
by an early freeze, halting their annual migration to their winter
home off Baja California.
   The mammals' plight triggered a massive rescue effort involving
chain saw-wielding Eskimos and the Soviet icebreakers that captured
worldwide attention. The effort has cost an estimated $1.3 million.
   Rescuers thought that after the icebreakers broke a channel to
open water Wednesday the whales would resume their migration. But
the pair lingered and parts of the channel refroze.
   The eventual fate of the creatures may never be known because
scientists turned down the option of attaching radio transmitters to
them. Some rescuers said they'd rather not know what happens to them.
   The temperature hovered at minus 15 degrees Fahrenheit Thursday
night, quickly refreezing escape channels cut by the Arseniev. The
plunging temperatures also were beginning to put a glaze of ice on
the open water to which rescuers were trying to lead the whales.
   National Weather Service ice analyst Gary Hufford said the whales
had shown an ability to break newly formed ice, so he remained
optimistic they could survive if they got beyond the remnants of the
pressure ridge crushed earlier in the week by the Soviet icebreakers.
   When rescuers found the whales early Thursday, they were
maintaining a small breathing hole about 1{ miles from where they
were last seen Wednesday night.
   Concerned with the whales' inability to negotiate the partially
refrozen channel, Eskimo laborers cut more than three dozen new
breathing holes in a path toward open water. The whales followed
dutifully, and were resting in the last breathing hole when darkness
fell.
   The Eskimos were prevented from moving further because the ice
was unstable as a result of the icebreakers' earlier efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
