<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ConsumerSafety-Darts     10-28 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Consumer Safety-Darts,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Struck By Lawn Dart Remains in Coma</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Consumer Safety, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old girl who was injured when
a metal and plastic lawn dart stuck 2 inches into her head remained
in coma Friday, and doctors said she probably suffered brain damage.
   Also Friday, the Consumer Product Safety Commission voted to ban
the sale of lawn darts. Opponents say the darts have severely
injured an estimated 150 to 200 youngsters in the last 10 years.
   Amy Herrin of McMinnville and some of her friends were playing
with a neighbor's lawn dart set Tuesday when the girl was struck by
a 1 pound dart, said Sue Tucker, Amy's mother.
   The child was admitted to the pediatric intensive care unit of
Vanderbilt University Medical Center, where doctors induced the
coma, said spokesman Wayne Wood.
   ``She could conceivably be in a coma for several more days or
even two or three more weeks,'' he said.
   ``It's completely dependent on the needed treatment. She's in a
coma to prevent swelling of the brain and the damage that can
cause,'' Wood said. ``If at some point the doctors feel she no
longer needs to be in a coma, they will bring her out.''
   There has been some swelling of the girl's brain and she probably
suffered brain damage, he said.
   Mrs. Tucker said Thursday night she supports the ban on lawn dart.
   ``I'm glad that they are going to do something, and I know they
will,'' she said. ``It is not a toy that you play with.''
</TEXT>
