<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland     10-28 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rakowski Tells Nation He's Not Worrying About Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski told
the nation Friday night he is not worried about prospects for talks
with the opposition, and he instead is concentrating on the ailing
economy.
   ``I would be a poor premier dealing only with the round table and
making light of problems of millions of my fellow countrymen,''
Rakowski said in a 10-minute nationwide television address that he
said would be the first of several.
   The appearance, broadcast immediately after the evening news, was
to report on the results of his first month in office.
   In an earlier meeting with Western reporters, Rakowski said the
talks promised by Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak in August
are at the moment blocked, but ``I think that the round table will
take place.''
   The government has demanded that Solidarity drop from its
delegation to the proposed talks two opposition activists, and
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa has refused a meeting to discuss the
matter, throwing the future of the talks in doubt.
   In both his TV address and in the meeting with reporters,
Rakowski struck a note of unconcern at the impasse.
   ``There is no compromise at the given moment,'' he told
reporters. ``But I treat this moment as a moment only. I must admit
that I have not thought about who should make the first step now.''
   He continued, ``Improving living conditions for the Polish people
are the most important thing for me. ... The most important thing is
that we can buy a piece of ham in a store and not on the black
market.''
   Rakowski, who met the reporters in connection with a scheduled
visit to Poland next week of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, said
some Western politicians are beginning to recognize the reforms
taking place in Poland.
   ``Do you really think that all Western politicians condemn us?''
he said. ``Do you think that the Western politicians don't know that
it's the most liberal country in Eastern Europe and that the reforms
are the deepest here?''
   The talks were agreed to in August during Poland's worst wave of
strikes in seven years. Walesa halted the strikes after being
promised that the talks could include the topics of relegalizing
Solidarity as well as broad questions of political and economic
reform.
   Earlier Friday, a U.S. government spokeswoman said the United
States was concerned by reports of the impasse in progress towards
the talks with Walesa and the opposition.
   ``We had welcomed the commitment by the government of Poland to
hold meaningful round-table talks with representatives of Polish
society,'' said State Department spokeswoman Philly Oakley in
Washington.
   ``If conducted in good faith, such negotiations have the
potential to put Poland on the path of recovery and enhanced
international economic standing.''
   But Rakowski told the reportes he doubted that legalizing
Solidarity, banned after the 1981 martial law crackdown, would
create ``fantastic growth'' and said he was ``against the myth that
everything in Poland depends on Solidarity.''
   ``I already notice a certain progress in the economy and it was
done without Solidarity,'' he said. ``There is no Solidarity in the
countryside and production is growing every year by four percent.''
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban had announced Tuesday that the
government insisted on a preliminary meeting with Walesa to discuss
objections to the participation at the round table of two prominent
Solidarity advisers, Jacek Kuron and Adam Michnik.
   Saying it would set a bad ``precedent'' for him to allow the
government to interfere in an internal union decision, Walesa
rejected such a preliminary meeting and asked that the talks begin
immediately.
   Referring to Kuron and Michnik, Rakowski said: ``We don't want at
the table two men who openly express and have been expressing for
some years now their wish to overthrow the system, the government.
We are willing to talk to other people.''
   But he told the reporters that he did not think the impasse would
be permanent. ``Poles are known for their capacity to compromise and
there will always be a way out.''
   Andrzej Stelmachowski, a church mediator acting for Walesa in
organizing the talks, said in an interview that, ``The ball is on
the other side now.''
   In the TV address, Rakowski said his newly appointed government
ministers were getting familiar with their new jobs but have already
taken some steps ``with full energy.''
   He listed the creation of committees to deal with economic and
social political problems; a raise in retirees' pensions; plans to
streamline government bureaucracy; and the introduction of
free-market practices in the distribution of some foodstuffs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
