<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ramesses Protest,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charlotte Preacher Says Ramesses Exhibit Promotes Paganism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister said Friday he would not take
classes from his Christian school to see an Egyptian art exhibit at
the Mint Museum because its opening was used to promote paganism.
   An exhibit of more than 70 artifacts from the time of the pharaoh
Rameses II opened Oct. 1 at the art museum. Some 600,000 people are
expected to see the show through January.
   The Rev. Joseph Chambers, chairman of Concerned Charlotteans and
head of the Paw Creek Christian Academy, said he felt the promoters
of an opening ceremony for the exhibit showed ``insensitivity'' when
they invited people to join in a ceremony in which ancient gods were
asked to appear and bless the exhibition.
   Chambers stressed he was not opposed to the exhibit.
   Museum director Milton Bloch said that while he respected
Chambers' concerns, there was no need for an apology.
   ``The Mint's pre-exhibition procession and promotion used some
flowery phrases and theatrical fiction which it has turned out has
offended some people in our community,'' he said. ``This result is
entirely unintended.''
