<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Soviet-Space-Glance     10-28 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviet-Space-Glance,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recent Highlights of Soviet Space Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent highlights of the Soviet space program:
   Dec. 23, 1987 _ Cosmonauts Vladimir Titov and Musa Manarov begin
their long mission aboard the Mir, an orbiting space station
launched in February 1986 as a permanently manned fixture in space.
   Dec. 29, 1987 _ Cosmonaut Yuri Romanenko arrives back on Earth
after spending 326 days in space, a space endurance record.
   Jan. 23, 1988 _ Unmanned Progress 34 cargo craft docks with
orbital platform Mir. Re-supply ferries carrying food, fuel, mail
and hardware are periodically sent, and jettisoned after being
unloaded.
   Feb. 26 _ Titov and Manarov work outside Mir for 4 hours, 25
minutes to successfuly replace a solar battery.
   March 17 _ Soviets launch their first payload for a paying
customer when they lift a satellite for India into orbit.
   May 15 _ Soviets successfully launch a military intelligence
craft the size of a school bus into a 530-mile circular orbit.
   June 7-17 _ A joint Soviet-Bulgarian mission, the first manned
mission of 1988, docks with Mir as part of a 10-day mission.
   June 30 _ Titov and Manarov work for five hours outside Mir in an
unsuccessful attempt to repair a faulty component on a telescope.
   July 7 and 12 _ In the most complex planetary mission attempted
by the Soviets, two robot craft are launched to explore Mars and the
Martian moon Phobos. They include instruments for exploration
provided by eight countries.
   Aug. 29-Sept. 7 _ A joint Soviet-Afghan mission docks with Mir.
Cosmonaut Dr. Valery Polyakov joins Titov and Manarov for the
duration of their flight. Cosmonauts Abdul Ahad Mohmand of
Afghanistan and Vladimir Lyakhov, attempting to return to Earth, are
stranded in orbit due to equipment problems and human error on their
Soyuz TM-5 capsule. After 26 hours and two unsuccessful attempts to
re-enter the atmosphere, and with food and oxygen running
dangerously low, the capsule lands safely.
   Sept. 9 _ Roald Z. Sagdeyev, head of the Soviet space program,
reveals that one of the two probes bound for Mars has been rendered
useless after a ground controller sent it an incorrect message.
   Oct. 20 _ Titov and Manarov spend 4 hours and 12 minutes outside
Mir, successfully replacing a faulty component on a telescope, the
repair that eluded them in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
