<2ND_LINE>AM-Stolen Guardrails,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$77,000 Worth Of Aluminum Railings Taken From State Highways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rise in aluminum prices has been
followed by thefts of highway guardrails and signs, and state police
are checking with scrap metal dealers in an attempt to track the
thieves.
   State highway officials say 1,557 feet of metal railing worth an
estimated $77,000 have been stolen since July from six highway
overpasses in eastern Connecticut. State police spokeswoman Marcy
Stamm said Friday that several signs also have been stolen.
   ``The spot price of aluminum went up and all of a sudden it
became a hot item,'' said Andrew Throwe, a maintenance manager with
the state Department of Transportation.
   Aluminum prices have tripled since 1986 and thefts of aluminum
have been reported around the country.
   Stanley H. Ostrinsky, a Manchester scrap dealer, said he pays 50
cents a pound for usable aluminum, up from 40 cents a year ago.
   State auditors Henry J. Becker Jr. and Leo V. Donohue detailed
the aluminum loss in a report to Gov. William A. O'Neill. The
auditors said Thursday that 1,557 feet of aluminum guardrail, which
they say would cost $77,825 to replace, have been taken since July.
   Department officials said all the stolen guardrails have been
replaced.
   Police refused to say if they have any leads in the thefts.
