<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle     10-28 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Campaigns In Pennsylvania Dutch Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Pa., (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle compared Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis to a ``Mr. Pretzel man''
because of his ``twists and turns on the issues'' as the Indiana
senator stumped Friday in Pennsylvania Dutch country.
   On a bus tour that included stops to talk to school children and
attend rallies, Quayle noted that the Berks County region was
renowned for making great pretzels.
   ``That's pretty appropriate,'' the Republican vice presidential
candidate told a rally at the Roman Catholic campus of Alvernia
College.
   ``Mr. Dukakis has made more twists and turns on the issues than
any one of your pretzels,'' he said. ``Maybe that ought to be the
symbol of their campaign _ the pretzel.''
   Quayle worked the pretzel idea into a litany he often uses in his
stump speech to characterize Dukakis.
   ``You could call him Mr. Tax Increase, Mr. Polluter, Mr. Furlough
Man, Mr. Weak-On-National Defense, Mr. Pretzel Man.'' But, added
Quayle, one thing voters should never call Dukakis is ``Mr.
President.''
   In what an aide said was a bid to ``beef up voter turnout,''
Quayle took toured central Pennsylvania Republican strongholds as
well as Democratic areas where President Reagan pulled a majority of
votes in his 1984 presidential campaign.
   ``We're not taking anything for granted,'' Quayle told reporters
before leaving Friday morning for Pennsylvania from Syracuse, N.Y.
   Quayle's mission, according to aides, was to encourage voter
turnout and ward off complacency in Pennsylvanhia, a state where
Bush is polling a bit ahead but the race is still considered close.
   Republican Sens. John Heinz and Arlen Specter, as well as state
party chairman Earl Baker campaiged with Quayle, urged voters not to
assume tht because Bush is ahead in national polls that they don't
have to vote.
   The race said Baker, ``is neck and neck'' in Pennsylvania.
   In Lancaster County, Quayle adviser Jim Cicconi said, ``This area
is clearly a good Republican area and we're trying to beef up
turnout here.''
   At a drizzling outdoor rally outside the historic Lancaster
market, Quayle kept up a drumbeat of ridicule against Dukakis,
calling the rainy day ``Dukakis weather.''
   Quayle quoted from a Boston Herald endorsement of Bush, which
criticized Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor.
   The editorial cautioned those outside the state: ``Don't make our
mistake. We too wanted a leader and what we got was a man all too
willing to sacrifice taxpayers of this state to his own quest for
higher office.''
   The bus trip included roadside stops to greet schoolchildren who
were let out of class to see the candidate.
   And there were some quirky sights along the way _ a woman in a
witch outfit, two people dressed up like clowns, a drive-in called
Hoosier hamburgers _ as well as scenes typifying the agricultural
region. Amish residents walked the streets, and people in colonial
dress and a fife-and-drum band greeted Quayle in downtown Lancaster.
</TEXT>
