<HEAD>Woman Finds $5,000 In Used Jacket She Bought For $1.05</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STATHAM, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noveane Jackson thought she was $5,000 richer
when a wad of cash turned up in the pocket of a used jacket she
bought for $1.05.
   But the store owner convinced police the money was his, and Mrs.
Jackson is ready to do battle.
   Mrs. Jackson, who bought the jacket Oct. 22 at The Attic in
Athens, has hired an attorney to see if she can fight the decision
and regain the 50 $100 bills from store owner Randy Jackson. The two
are not related.
   ``I think the fairest thing to say is she just wants justice to
be done,'' her attorney, George Peters of Athens, said Thursday.
``Obviously, she wasn't certain of her legal rights at the time this
occurred.''
   Peters said the coat apparently had been hanging on a rack in the
store for some time when Mrs. Jackson decided to buy it.
   ``She'd already paid for it and it was being folded when (the
money) was found,'' he said.
   Police officer Inez McElhannon took the coat and the money after
a dispute arose over their ownership.
   Then the store owner contacted police Sunday night to claim the
money.
   ``He said it was his coat and that he didn't know his wife had
gotten it (to sell),'' Ms. McElhannon said, adding that he told
police he had not realized he had left the money in the jacket.
   McElhannon said Jackson told her he thought the money had been
taken in a burglary last year. She said he had reported to police
after the burglary that a watch was taken.
