<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 2026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SeaLionRescue     10-28 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sea Lion Rescue,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sea Lion In Fishing Line Noose Thwarting Rescue Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trapped Whales, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sea lion that got fishing line
tangled around its neck has evaded rescuers for six weeks and could
die if it isn't captured soon, marine mammal experts said Friday.
   The injured sea lion keeps to a buoy about 500 yards off Newport
Harbor, said Judi Jones, a director of Friends of the Sea
Lion-Marine Mammal Center in Laguna Beach.
   ``Its chances for survival are not good'' if not treated, said
Bill Ford, an officer of the organization, which rescues and
rehabilitates injured and sick seals.
   The animal is believed to be between 2 and 4 years old. Sea lions
reach maturity about 8.
   ``As the animal grows, the monofilament line does not expand, and
the line will eventually cut off the organs in its neck,'' Ford said.
   ``The minute we come near, their instinct is to jump off the
buoy,'' Ms. Jones said. ``If they come up to us, it's their choice.
But our approaching them is a threat. If they're injured, they're a
bit more wary.''
   Sedation is not a viable alternative.
   ``The minute the animal feels the stick or dart, it becomes
frightened,'' Ms. Jones said. ``Then it heads for the water, gets
drowsy and eventually drowns.''
</TEXT>
