<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Kids Poll,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weekly Reader Says Kids Like Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's schoolchildren say that for
only the second time in 200 years the United States will have a
president with the first name of George.
   The first, as every kid learns, was George Washington, and the
second will be Republican George Bush, acccording to a poll of
670,000 children ages 5 to 15 by Weekly Reader magazine.
   The students say Bush will beat Democrat Michael Dukakis 58
percent to 40 percent, according to the Weekly Reader presidential
poll, which has correctly called eight races since its inception in
1956.
   In the first year, students named Republican Dwight Eisenhower to
beat Democrat Adlai Stevenson by a 60.3 percent to 36.8 percent
margin. Eisenhower won with 57 percent of the vote.
   The magazine's executive editor Lynell Johnson said the reason
the poll has been so accurate is that the schoolchildren reflect the
opinions of their parents.
   ``Since Bush is doing well in all the national polls, I would be
surprised if he wasn't ahead in this poll as well,'' she said.
