<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Khashoggi     10-28 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Khashoggi,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrest Warrant Issued For Adnan Khashoggi In Marcos Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents have obtained an arrest warrant
for financier Adnan Khashoggi, who denies racketeering and fraud
charges filed against him and former Philippine President Ferdinand
Marcos, according to published reports here and abroad.
   An English-language newspaper in Saudi Arabia, Arab News of
Jiddah, reported Khashoggi's denial Thursday under a Riyadh
dateline. Arab News editors said the denial was ``remitted'' to
their office, but declined to say how or by whom.
   The Los Angeles Times, quoting unidentified sources, reported in
Friday editions that U.S. officials sought the arrest warrant out of
fear that Khashoggi would relocate to a country without any formal
extradition treaty with the United States.
   The U.S. government is accusing Khashoggi, once reported to be
the world's richest man, of acting as a front for Marcos to help
divert assets and hide Marcos' ownership of real estate and valuable
art.
   The Arab News said: ``He is disappointed that a technical legal
question involving the scope of an injunction in a civil case to
which he was not a party has been converted into a criminal
allegation in a totally unprecedented manner. He is confident that
when all of the facts are made public as the proceeding progresses,
his lack of culpability will become manifest.''
   Khashoggi was believed to be ``lying low'' in a European country
consulting with advisers on how he should respond to the charges
contained in a New York grand jury indictment, the Times said.
   The Times quoted sources close to Khashoggi as saying the
financier is considering returning to his native Saudi Arabia, which
has no extradition agreement with the United States.
   The United States has extradition agreements with France, Britain
and Spain, the countries where Khashoggi currently maintains his
primary residences.
   Although he believes he would ultimately be cleared of the
charges, the sources said, he is concerned about the possibility of
being arrested, jailed and extradited.
   Khashoggi's wealth once symbolized the rising economic power of
the oil-rich Arab world in the 1970s. But his financial empire began
to crumble amid a pile of debt in the early 1980s.
   Meanwhile, Marcos' arraignment in New York was delayed Thursday
until a court-appointed doctor can examine the 71-year-old former
Philippine leader in Hawaii, where he and his wife, Imelda, have
lived since leaving the Philippines in 1986.
   Marcos' attorneys argued he was too ill to travel to New York for
the arraignment. Mrs. Marcos, however, was ordered to appear at the
New York hearing on Monday.
</TEXT>
