Brothers envisions a movie that would serve as a pilot for a
situation comedy series, he said.
   When Alexander and his family moved out of the governor's mansion
in January 1987, they headed for six-months in Australia for what
his wife, Honey, called a learning experience.
   ``I hope they don't show me learning how to drive. For so long I
was driven around (when governor), and then I had to learn to drive
on the wrong side of the road,'' Alexander said referring to
Australia's left hand-drive roads.
   Alexander said it's up to Warner Brothers to decide what to do
with the book, and it could be 1990 before it's on television.
   He declined to say how much he was paid for the rights, but
acknowledged the deal would be a money-maker for him.
