<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-Radon 1stLd-Writethru a0659 10-28 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Radon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President OKs Bill for Radon Checks in Public Buildings</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: UPDATES throughout with Reagan also signing bill regarding
plastic six-pack rings; CORRECTS $15.5 million to $44.5 million, the
three-year total on the radon measure</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Friday signed bills
calling for a three-year, $44.5 million program to help states deal
with radon contamination and to reduce the threat to birds from
plastic six-pack rings.
   The radon bill authorizes $10 million a year for grants to state
and local governments to develop radon programs and another $3
million annually for technical assistance. The balance for other
activities includes $1.5 million for the Environmental Protection
Agency to study radon contamination in schools.
   Radon is a naturally occurring, radioactive gas found in soil
which has been blamed for as many as 20,000 lung cancer deaths
annually in the United States.
   The plastic bill gives the EPA two years to promulgate
regulations that would require use of degradable materials in
beverage six-pack ring carriers. Sixteen states already have laws
requiring those materials.
   Wildlife experts have said the plastic rings can remain intact
for decades and pose a growing threat to fish and waterfowl, which
can become snared in them.
</TEXT>
