<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Khatami     10-28 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Khatami,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Religious Leader Helped Khomeini Fight Shah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khatami, an Iranian
religious leader who helped overthrow the shah, has died at age 84,
the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported Friday.
   Khatami, father of Mohammed Khatami, the minister of culture and
Islamic guidance, died Thursday of an illness at a Tehran hospital,
the agency said. It did not specify the illness.
   Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini assigned Khatami the
task of distributing his communications starting in June 1963.
Khomeini's speeches, smuggled into Iran after his exile later the
same year, were instrumental in building opposition to Shah Mohammed
Reza Pahlavi, who was overthrown in 1979.
   Khomeini appointed Khatami his personal representative and prayer
leader in the central Iranian city of Yazd in July 1982, after the
previous prayer leader was assassinated.
   Khomeini canceled all his appointments Saturday to observe the
death of Khatami, the agency said. In a statement, Khomeini called
Khatami ``a prominent personality and an indefatigable struggler of
the recent decade,'' the news agency said.
