<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SecretClient     10-28 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Secret Client,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Might Change Ruling Protecting Attorney-Client Privilege</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who upheld an attorney's
right to shield the identity of a driver involved in a hit-and-run
fatality said he wants to review the lawyer's testimony on the
``small chance'' he might change his ruling before the case goes to
appeal.
   In a rare display of judicial uncertainty, Palm Beach County
Circuit Judge Timothy P. Poulton said Thursday that he may change or
revise his Oct. 13 decision after reviewing the testimony of
attorney Barry Krischer.
   Krischer was hired by a person claiming to be the driver of a car
that struck and killed Mark Baltes in Palm Beach on March 9, 1986.
The driver asked Krischer to keep his identity secret while
negotiating a plea bargain with prosecutors.
   The plea bargain fell through, however, and Krischer has guarded
the person's identity on the grounds of attorney-client privilege.
   Poulton uphold that privilege in his ruling against Baltes'
parents in their $6 million civil suit seeking to find the identity
of the driver.
   ``If we fail to rule as we do in this case, the result would be
the erection of a wall between the public and attorneys,'' Poulton
wrote in his eight-page order. ``Plaintiff's case has tremendous
emotional appeal. It is difficult to rule against the plaintiff's,
but I am convinced that the law requires it.''
   But a week later, Poulton sent a two-page letter to the attorneys
saying he realized the case would be appealed and that he wanted to
review the testimony.
</TEXT>
