<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Iran     10-28 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Iran,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Confuses Iran, Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan got Iran mixed up with
Afghanistan briefly Friday, going on to say that moves for a change
of some kind in the Iranian government are under way.
   The confusion came at an appearance before the Los Angeles World
Affairs Council when Reagan was asked if he would support efforts by
the son of the late shah of Iran to restore the monarchy.
   ``If that's what the people of Afghanistan, who have fought so
bravely and courageously to restore their freedom, if that's their
choice ...,'' the president began.
   A member of the council, who was reading written questions
submitted by members of the audience, interrupted and said, ``Mr.
President, we're talking about Iran.''
   ``Oh, what am I doing?'' Reagan said. ``I got into Afghanistan by
mistake, didn't I?''
   ``Do you want me to repeat the question,'' the council member
said.
   Reagan did not ask her to repeat the question, but he recalled
that he and his wife Nancy visited Iran shortly before the shah fell
and the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini came to power.
   ``It was amazing to see that country then,'' he said. ``As you
looked at the skyline, you saw derricks all over. These were
building low-cost housing apartments for the people. A land reform
was put into effect that gave land as we once did through
homesteading to the peasants, and maybe part of the reason for the
revolution was that most of that land belonged to the mullahs and
they didn't like having it taken away.''
   ``I know that there are moves on and there are factions that are
organizing right now with the expectation that come the end of the
ayatollah the country can be moved in one of several directions,''
Reagan said.
   ``I think that the United States would be very willing to be
supportive of a regime that wanted to restore democracy and freedom
to the people,'' he said.
</TEXT>
