<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1754EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet Bjt   10-28 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet, Bjt,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First `No' Votes Cast in Supreme Soviet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few legislators of the Supreme Soviet, that
traditional rubber stamp for the leadership, made history Friday
night by voting against decrees restricting street demonstrations.
   They lost by more than 1,300 votes because they were 31 at most
and the other members behaved in the customary manner.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who has encouraged debate in his
campaign for more democracy, watched from the dais with other
government and Communist Party leaders.
   Votes are taken by show of hands, usually all hands for whatever
measures the parliament's ruling Presidium adopts between
twice-yearly sessions. The Supreme Soviet chamber in the Grand
Kremlin Palace does not have electronic voting equipment.
   It appeared the leadership expected Friday's dissent because the
two laws were taken out of a Presidium package for separate votes.
   Despite overwhelming support for the laws by Supreme Soviet
deputies, hundreds of them laughed or smiled as Soviet photographers
rushed to record the spectacle of legislators voting no.
   Dissenters kept their hands up long enough for functionaries to
rush around and count.
   One of the 3-month-old decrees they opposed gives broad power to
control demonstrations to paramilitary police, whom protesters have
accused of beating them.
   On that measure, the vote was announced to the deputies as 1,348
in favor, 31 opposed and 24 abstentions. State television reported
one fewer yes vote, with four abstentions, and there was no
explanation for the discrepancy.
   On the second law, which requires advance permission for
demonstrations and has been used by local officials to ban a variety
of gatherings, the vote was announced to deputies as 1,368 for, 13
against and four abstaining.
   Television reported three fewer abstentions and did not mention
the rarity of negative votes in either case.
   The Supreme Soviet took its first step away from rubber-stamping
in closed committee meetings in May, amending a government proposal
on taxation of cooperatives. The new version passed unanimously in
the public session.
   Deputies could move farther toward democracy next month when they
consider a proposal for multiple-candidate elections of delegates to
a new national parliament.
   In introducing the measures, Presidium secretary Tengiz N.
Menteshashvili noted they had been criticized in the press and
letters to the leadership.
   Only one deputy spoke against them _ a factory worker from the
Baltic republic of Estonia, a new Soviet breeding ground of
independence. He said local government councils, not the Interior
Ministry, should decide when paramilitary police are needed to quell
demonstrations.
   ``Each republic has its own traditions,'' said Pavel P. Goryunov
from the city of Tartu. He particularly objected to a provision
allowing paramilitary police to enter homes in pursuit of suspects.
   After Goryunov's remarks, a Moscow subway worker and the chairman
of the Kiev city council spoke for the laws.
   ``We must regulate political freedoms for the good of all,'' said
Alexander S. Sukhanov, the subway worker. He said he did not
understand people who called the laws ``an encroachment on human
rights'' or ``a muzzle on democracy.''
   Colleagues applauded gave him much more applause than Goryunov.
   Menteshashvili, the Presidium secretary, cited ethnic rioting in
Sumgait, Azerbaijan, and problems in other cities as reasons for
strict control of demonstrations. Dozens of people were killed in
the Sumgait riots involving Azerbaijanis and ethnic Armenians.
   He held out the possibility of future amendments to the decrees.
   ``We still have to gain practical experience in democracy,''
Menteshashvili said. ``Then we can introduce amendments.''
   The Supreme Soviet unanimously approved a $795 billion budget for
1989 after trimming a projected deficit from $58 billion to $55
billion. Official reports said additional income was found during
committee sessions.
   Most new investment in the new budget is moved from heavy
industry to providing consumer goods.
   Finance Minister Boris Gostsev said Thursday the government has
run deficits for years because of huge losses by state-owned
businesses. This is the first year a deficit has been acknowledged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1759EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NgHearing     10-28 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ng Hearing,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documents: Ng Told Investigator He Helped Dispose Of Victim's Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Ng told a detective
investigating a California murder spree that he helped dispose of a
victim's body, according to court documents released during his
extradition hearing.
   The provincial court hearing is to determine if enough evidence
exists to extradite Ng, a 27-year-old former U.S. Marine, to
California. The hearing has been closed to the public in its second
week.
   Ng, whose name is pronounced Ing, is accused in the slayings of
12 people between June 1984 and January 1985. Most of the charges
involve sex-torture killings at a rural cabin in Calaveras County,
east of San Francisco.
   He faces 25 charges in California, including at least 10 of
murder.
   San Francisco police detective Edward Erdelatz said in an
affidavit released by the court on Thursday that he interviewed Ng
in Canada about the slaying of one of the victims, Paul Cosner, a
San Francisco car salesman.
   After being advised of his rights, Ng said he had a meeting in
Cosner's car with Leonard Lake, who was also suspected in the
slayings, Erdelatz said in a sworn statement.
   ``Ng stated that Lake said he (Lake) had just shot Cosner, whose
body was in the car,'' Erdelatz said. ``Ng stated he then helped
Lake dispose of Cosner's body.''
   Lake killed himself in custody in 1985. Ng came to Canada and is
serving a 4{-year sentence for an armed robbery in Calgary, Alberta.
   If extradited and convicted, Ng faces possible execution in
California.
   Canada has a policy against extraditing anyone facing the death
penalty. The final decision rests with Federal Justice Minister Ray
Hnatyshyn.
   Reporters have been told that the hearing, which was expected to
last five weeks, possibly could end sooner.
   Allegations of torture and mass murder in the California deaths
have raised questions about Canada's extradition procedure. As
recently as May, California Gov. George Deukmejian urged Canadian
Prime Minister Brian Mulroney to speed up the process.
   In a letter, Deukmejian said denying the extradition ``could have
the unfortunate consequence of making Canada a haven for death
penalty fugitives.''
   But Ng's Calgary-based lawyer, Don MacLeod, predicted it could be
a long time before Ng heads south. Regardless of the outcome of the
extradition hearings, McLeod said, an appeal is likely.
   The hearing has attracted widespread attention in Canada, where
the national news weekly Maclean's said the case ``will provide a
clear test of Canada's wilingness to return suspected criminals to
jurisdictions where they could be put to death.''
   Ng is being held at the maximum security Edmonton Institution
during the hearing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
