<DOCNO> AP881028-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1804EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Uruguay-Summit     10-28 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uruguay-Summit,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latin Economic Experts Will Meet To Plan Common Debt Strategy</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto PDE-1</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUNTA DEL ESTE, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic policy officials of seven
Latin American nations with collective foreign debts of nearly $340
billion will meet next month, Brazil's treasury minister said Friday.
   Mailson Ferreira da Nobrega said they would work on a common
strategy for negotiations on debt forgiveness by creditor banks and
governments.
   ``I believe we've got to do something to reduce the stock of
debt,'' he told reporters during a break in a meeting of presidents
of the Group of Eight nations.
   ``This (debt reduction) is the way to make it possible for us to
develop our economies and to avoid social unheavals and political
instability,'' he said.
   Finance ministers of the seven participating nations _ Argentina,
Brazil, Colombia, Mexico, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela _ could meet
before year's end, da Nobrega said.
   Panama is the eighth member of the Group of Eight but was
suspended last February following the ouster of President Eric
Delvalle by Panama's military strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Details of the proposed economic meeting, discussed by the
presidents in closed meetings, were expected to be announed Saturday
in a final communique.
   Da Nobrega said the seven countries intend to negotiate debt
reduction rather than taking unilateral action. ``The countries are
firmly convinced that confrontation does not pay,'' he said.
   He also said the group has no specific plan in mind and will
examine ``every solution that has been put forward.''
   Last month, the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development said
creditor banks and governments should forgive 30 percent of the debt
owed by 15 nations, including all seven active members of the Group
of Eight.
   The agenda for the second summit since the organization was
formed in 1986 included strife in Central America, production and
trafficking of illegal drugs and trade imbalances.
   It was clear from the speeches made by all seven presidents
Thursday, however, that their deteriorating economies were the main
concern.
   ``Since 1982 the region has transferred to the exterior about
$200 billion in interest payments; the ratio of debt stock to total
gross national products exceeds 57 percent. These are incredible
figures,'' said President Jose Sarney of Brazil. His country's $121
billion foreign debt is the highest of any developing country.
   Mexico owes about $104 billion, Argentina $56 billion, Venezuela
$20 billion, Peru $16 billion, Colombia $16 billion and Uruguay
about $6 billion.
   Sarney stopped interest payments on $70 billion of Brazil's debt
in February 1987. On taking office in July 1985, President Alan
Garcia of Peru suspended relations with the International Monetary
Fund and said his government would pay interest only up to a maximum
of 10 percent of Peru's annual export earnings.
   Argentina has renegotiated its foreign debt three times since
1983 and is negotiating again with commercial banks and the IMF.
   On Thursday, the presidents called for a ``new dialogue'' with
the United States and other industrial nations on narcotics
trafficking and the conflicts in Central America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
