<DOCNO> AP881028-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 2030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     10-28 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Aid Relief To Southern Sudan Waits Rebel Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudanese rebels will not let U.S. relief
supplies into a starving, besieged town under government control
unless food also is delivered to a town held by insurgents, a rebel
spokesman said Friday.
   ``The food should be shared,'' said Richard K. Mulla. ``Why
should people in the area we control go hungry?''
   Mulla is secretary of the Sudan Relief and Rehabilitation
Association, the relief arm of the Sudan People's Liberation Army.
The rebels began fighting five years ago for autonomy in southern
Sudan, which is largely Christian and animist, from the
predominantly Moslem north represented by the government in Khartoum.
   Rebels repeatedly have threatened to shoot down aircraft,
military or commercial, that fly over the south. They shot down two
commercial planes in 1986 and 1987, killing 73 people. and at least
two large cargo jets have been hit this year but landed safely.
   Mulla spoke to The Associated Press by telephone from his home in
a Nairobi suburb.
   He said officials of the U.S. Agency for International
Development (AID) in Khartoum wrote to rebel headquarters in Addis
Ababa, Ethiopia, seeking guarantees their aircraft flying to Aweil
would not be shot at.
   Aweil, site of a government garrison 600 miles southwest of
Khartoum, has been under rebel siege for months. Sudanese officials
say at least 6,000 people died of starvation there during the summer.
   Mulla said the rebels agreed to give relief flights safe conduct
guarantees if supplies also were flown to Aton. Available maps do
not show that town.
   A man who answered the telephone at rebel headquarters in Addis
Ababa confirmed AID sought guarantees, but would not give details.
He refused to say when the letter was written or when the reply was
sent to the U.S. Embassy in Addis Ababa.
   ``They (the Americans) were told to contact me,'' Mulla said. ``I
don't know what they are waiting for.''
   Telephone calls to the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi were not answered
and attempts to reach embassy officials were unsuccessful. The U.S.
Embassy in Khartoum was closed for the Moslem sabbath and its
officials were unavailable.
   An AID official, speaking in Nairobi on condition of anonymity,
said the agency still awaited guarantees from the rebels.
   Asked whether Sudanese authorities approved the agency's contact
with the rebels, he said: ``The negotiations were carried out from
Khartoum. I don't know the details.''
   The government of Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi has expelled
relief groups in the past for dealing with the rebels, who control
most of the countryside in southern Sudan. Army troops control the
cities.
   People are starving in southern Sudan because of food shortages
caused by droubht and aggravated by the war.
   The U.S.-financed airlift started carrying food and medical
supplies Oct. 13 to Mairam, Kadugli, Muglad and Abyei. Aweil is
southwest of Abyei and Mulla said Aton is southeast.
   Thousands of refugees from the fighting and drought have fled to
the towns.
</TEXT>
