<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JournalClosing     10-28 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Journal Closing,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jacksonville Journal Ceases Publication After 101 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 101-year-old Jacksonville Journal
ceased publication Friday, the victim of declining circulation among
afternoon dailies.
   ``So Long, Jacksonville,'' read the banner headline.
   A run of 44,467 copies was planned when the presses at the
Florida Publishing Co. began printing Friday morning, but the run
was increased to 50,000 copies in the afternoon because of heavy
demand for the final edition.
   A group of Journal editors and reporters gathered in the
pressroom as copies of the final edition started rolling.
   ``I feel like I'm attending a funeral,'' said Perry Gann, the
press superintendent.
   ``Everything has been so somber and quiet,'' added reporter Sandy
Strickland, an employee for 19 years.
   ``I feel like somebody kicked me in the stomach,'' said columnist
P.J. Tedrick, adding that she hadn't found the courage to open the
final edition.
   There were no ceremonies planned to mark the occasion.
   The front page and three other pages of the 116-page newspaper
were devoted to the newspaper's closing. Other features appeared
throughout the edition.
   ``The Journal has had a long and distinguished record of service,
commitment and leadership,'' wrote Publisher William S. Morris.
   The final edition also features a picture of crews removing the
Journal name from the building.
   The photo was taken by Pulitizer Prize winning photographer Rocco
Morabito, who retired in 1983 after 45 years with the newspaper.
   The Journal began publishing in 1887 as the The Metropolis. It
was renamed the Jacksonville Journal in 1922 when it was purchased
in by John Perry of New York and Richard Lloyd Jones of Tulsa, Okla.
   Perry and his son, John Holliday Perry Jr. owned and operated the
Journal until 1959 when it was sold to Florida Publishing Co.,
publiher of the The Florida Times-Union.
   Florida Publishing Co. was purchased Jan. 1, 1983 by Morris
Communications Corp. of Augusta, Ga.
   The closing leaves The Times-Union, a morning newspaper, as the
sole newspaper in the city.
</TEXT>
