<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AbortionPill 1stLd-Writethru a0672 10-28 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Pill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0672,0872</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Resumes Distribution of Abortion Pill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 13-14 bgng: Baulieu said... with 6 grafs to include
reaction at Rio conference. PICK up 15h pvs: In Washington... Edits
to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pharmaceutical company that manufactures abortion
pills reversed itself Friday and agreed to resume distribution of
the drug after the government demanded it do so.
   The company, Roussel Uclaf, announced its decision after Health
Minister Claude Evin said the pills should be made available in the
interest of public health.
   Roussel Uclaf, partly owned by the French government, said it had
no choice but to comply.
   The firm announced Wednesday it was pulling RU 486, also known as
Mifepristone, off the market because of an ``outcry of public
opinion at home and abroad,'' and a threatened boycott of its
products.
   Evin, after meeting with company executives, issued a statement
saying France's 1975 law legalizing abortions must be respected.
   ``The drug RU 486 is an advance because it does not involve use
of an anesthetic. The precautionary measures to be taken in
administering this drug, exclusively in approved health clinics,
provides indepensible safeguards to women's health,'' Evin's
statement said.
   Roussel Uclaf is part of the giant West German chemical group
Hoescht, which holds the majority share. The French government has a
36 percent share.
   The government certified the pill for use under medical
supervision Sept. 23.
   Since then, 4,000 women in France have used it with a success
rate of 95.5 percent, according to the drug's inventor, Etienne
Emile Baulieu.
   In a statement issued late Friday, the company said it ``accepted
the (government's) order and would rescind its earlier decision and
would resume distributing RU 486 in approved health centers.''
   Roussel Uclaf repeated that ``no medical reason'' had prompted
its decision to withdraw the drug from distribution.
   Baulieu, at a conference in Rio de Janeiro of the World Congress
of Gynecology and Obstetrics, issued a statement saying he was
``very pleased'' with the decision to resume distribution.
   He said the pill represented ``immense hope'' for Third World
countries.
   ``It is a question of human misery, of life and death. It was not
possible to keep such an important advance in the drawer just
because certain pressure groups were against its distribution,''
Balieu said.
   Dr. Malcolm Potts, the president of Family Health International,
a non-profit organization that specializes in developing
contraceptives, is attending the Rio conference. He said a vast
majority of the hundredes of participants at the meeting applauded
when the French decision was announced.
   Potts said that after the session dozens of gynecologists
celebrated the move by ordering champagne in the restaurant of the
hotel where the congress is being held.
   Dr. John Sciarra, chairman of obstetrics at Northwestern
University in Evanston, Ill., who was attending the Rio conference,
said ``the congress received the news of the French Health
Ministry's move with enthusiasm.
   ``The general reaction at the congress was that the withdrawal of
the pill from the market on emotional grounds after it had been
tested for effectiveness and safety, seemed to be a very erratic
response.''
   In Washington, Kate Michelman, executive director of the National
Abortion Rights Action League, applauded the government's action.
   ``The French government has taken a strong stand against
intolerance and in favor of the health of women. We support this
action and the message it sends to those who seek to impose their
will on all of us,'' she said.
   Anti-abortion groups, including the Roman Catholic church, had
welcomed the company's decision to suspend distribution.
   Cardinal Albert Decourtray, president of the French Bishops
Conference, said Friday he was ``astonished that the government
intervened in such an authoritarian manner.'' He denied that the
church had pressured the company to halt distribution.
   Thousands of doctors attending the Rio conference had called on
Roussel Uclaf to continue making the abortion pill or pass the
patent onto another manufacturer.
   Health Ministry officials maintained the company acted to protect
its image abroad when it halted distribution. Company officials said
they had been inundated with mail from opponents to the drug in
France and abroad, especially the United States.
   They said many letters threatened to boycott company products.
   Andre Ulmann, a Roussel Uclaf official who helped develop the
pill, told reporters at the Rio conference a boycott would have cost
the company substantial sums of money, ``So we decided to stop
making the drug.''
   The pill works by blocking the action of progesterone, a hormone
essential in all stages pregnancy. Researchers say it is effective
in the first seven weeks of pregnancy, particularly when used in
conjuction with a second product called Sulprotone, or prostaglandin
E.
   They said the drug was not a do-it-yourself pill that could be
purchased over the counter and taken at home. Its use requires
medical supervision.
   Evin, in a television newscast, said of the threatening letters
received by Roussel Uclaf.
   ``It seems it is the fundamentalist movements that have already
protested at other times, notably in 1975 when the abortion bill was
passed.''
</TEXT>
