<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Strike     10-28 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Strike,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Blow Up Power Towers; Black Out 20 Percent Of Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas blew up eight
electricity towers, leaving about 20 percent of the country without
power Friday, the government said.
   The bombs exploded during a one-day general strike Thursday and
early Friday morning, said the minister of mines and energy, Oscar
Mejia Vallejo. He said sabotage of generators also contributed to
the blackouts.
   Among the areas without electricity were the Caribbean coast
cities of Cartagena, Santa Marta, Barranquilla and Riohacha.
Cartagena and Santa Marta attract hundreds of thousands of U.S. and
Canadian tourists each year.
   Other northern cities affected were Valledupar and Sincelejo. In
north central Colombia, the damage blacked out Monteria, Ibague,
Armenia, Pereira, Manizales and 30 other towns.
   Not affected were Colombia's three largest cities _ Medellin,
Cali and the capital, Bogota _ where one-third of the 30 million
people live.
   Guerrillas also blew up four bridges Thursday in the northern
banana-growing region and near the central town of Barrancabermeja,
the Defense Ministry said.
   Juan Martin Caicedo, the labor minister, said the general strike
called by labor unions was a failure. In a news release, he
estimated 95 percent of workers went to their jobs.
   El Tiempo, a Bogota daily, quoted union leaders as acknowledging
the strike did not meet expectations, but claiming 60 percent of
workers joined it.
   The strike had little apparent affect in Bogota.
</TEXT>
