<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VonBulowAuction     10-28 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-VonBulow Auction,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Von Bulow Collection Goes on Auction Block</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil painting of two dogs sold for $180,000,
more than five times its original estimate, at an auction of art and
antiques widely reported to be from the collection of Claus and
Sunny von Bulow.
   ``Two King Charles Spaniels, a Landscape Beyond,'' an oil
painting by British artist Richard Ansdell, had a presale estimate
of $25,000 to $35,000. The 10 percent buyer's premium boosted the
total price for the work to $198,000.
   Sotheby's had promised to keep the seller's name a secret. But
curiosity seekers flocked to the presale exhibition last weekend
after The New York Times reported that the auction, entitled,
``Property from a Private Collection,'' would feature the Von Bulow
belongings.
   ``An 83-room mansion _ it's almost obscene. It's a world I don't
know of,'' said Evelyn Goldstein of Bayside, who attended the sale
with her daughter.
   The 509 lots featured English furniture and decorations, Old
Master paintings, silver and rugs, much of it very ornate.
   ``The silver is nice. But a lot of the things, I wouldn't like in
my house,'' Mrs. Goldstein said.
   Von Bulow has been living in Europe since he was acquitted in
1985 in a retrial of charges that he twice tried to murder his wife,
heiress Sunny von Bulow, with insulin injections.
   The offerings, which Sotheby's predicted would bring between $6
million and $7.5 million, were said to include furnishings from
Clarendon Court, the von Bulows' mansion in Newport, R.I., and
pieces from the couple's Manhattan apartment.
   Some sale items fizzled: Henri-Pierre Danloux's portrait of his
wife and infant son, which had a presale estimate of $300,000 to
$400,000, was yanked from the auction block when the top bid,
$210,000, failed to make the prearranged minimum.
   Other lots included a portrait by George Romney, which fetched
$396,000, below its estimate of $400,000 to $500,000; one by Sir
Joshua Reynolds, for $363,000, within its $350,000 to $450,000
estimate; and another by Reynolds for $220,000, topping the $120,000
to $160,00 estimate. All final prices included the premium.
   Diana Levitt, a spokeswoman for Sotheby's, said a big crowd was
expected Saturday, the final day of the auction.
</TEXT>
