<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Sears-LawnDarts     10-28 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sears-Lawn Darts,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Sanction Sears Store for Selling Lawn Darts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Consumer Safety Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has refused to sanction Sears,
Roebuck and Co. for selling lawn darts at a store in Puerto Rico in
violation of a consent decree with the Consumer Product Safety
Commission.
   U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green refused to cite the company
for civil contempt of court and impose sanctions sought by the CPSC.
She cited evidence that ``Sears has taken all possible steps to
eliminate the sale of lawn darts in its stores.''
   The judge's decision, dated Tuesday, was made public Friday.
   ``This decision is especially gratifying because it acknowledges
our commitment to the consumer and to safety,'' said Michael Bozic,
chairman and chief executive officer of the Sears Merchandise Group
in Chicago.
   ``Sears was the first major retailer to discontinue selling the
product,'' Bozic said. ``In spite of these steps, we were unfairly
singled out by the CPSC because one of our 800 stores inadvertently
failed to remove them from sale.''
   The commission had sought the contempt citation after a random
survey of 20 stores found that Sears was selling lawn darts at one
outlet in violation of a consent decree it had entered into with the
agency.
   The consent decree required Sears to properly label lawn darts,
post large warning signs and take other steps to ensure that
consumers were warned of the product's safety hazards.
   The judge noted that Sears went farther than the consent decree,
ordering all of its 800 stores to stop selling the product. ``Sears
has convincingly shown that it has achieved substantial compliance
with the obligations imposed by the consent decree,'' the judge
found.
   ``While the court does not condone even a few non-conforming
darts in a single store, the fact that some such darts were
discovered does not obviate the force of Sears' commendable efforts
and it does not provide a basis for entry of civil contempt in this
instance.''
</TEXT>
