<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shuttle-Glance     10-28 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Glance,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comparison Of Soviet And U.S. Shuttles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet and U.S. space shuttles look similar, but they are
built and operate differently. Here at a glance is a point-by-point
comparison:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Soviet Shuttle</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Height including launch vehicle: 198 feet
   Liftoff weight: 4.4 million pounds
   Maximum payload: 66,000 pounds
   Energiya launch vehicle has four liquid-fueled main engines in
base.
   Four liquid-fueled strap-on boosters
   Buran orbiter has jet engines in tail for maneuvering to landing
   Buran controlled automatically from ground
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S. Shuttle</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Height including launch vehicle: 185 feet
   Liftoff weight: 4.4 million pounds
   Maximum payload: 55,000 pounds
   Launch vehicle's external liquid-fuel tank has no engines;
engines in base of orbiter
   Two solid-fueled strap-on boosters
   Orbiter has no jet engines and glides to landing
   Astronauts and ground share control
</TEXT>
</DOC>
