<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     10-28 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Of Anti-Government Demonstrators Return From Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 people opposed to the
government have returned from border refuges to which they had fled,
and more are expected to reach reception camps by a Nov. 18
deadline, the government said Friday.
   Government spokesman Kyaw Sann told journalists the deadline
would not be extended but the government would ``make all efforts to
let the students know our intention to receive them back without
malice.''
   By Thursday, he said, 525 people had returned to their homes
after passing through 27 centers opened the government opened Oct.
14.
   They fled after a Sept. 18 military coup and brutal suppression
of a popular uprising against 26 years of authoritarian military
rule. Most went to areas controlled by various ethnic rebel groups
also fighting the Rangoon government.
   Rebel spokesmen say more than 8,000 students, professionals,
Buddhist monks and others sought refuge. About 5,200 of them are at
bases of the Karen National Union, which has provided some military
training, the spokesmen say.
   The government announced it would take no action against any of
those returning who had not committed specific criminal offenses.
   Karen sources on the Thai-Burma border cited unconfirmed reports,
however, that some people had been mistreated at the reception
centers. They said the alleged mistreatment includes forcing people
to run in circles until they drop from exhaustion and severely
restricting food and water.
   Kyaw Sann, the government spokesman, said 21 insurgents and 15
soldiers were killed in 37 clashes Oct. 22-27. He said the
skirmishes did not include those with the Karen National Union,
which is based along the Moei River between Thailand and Burma.
</TEXT>
