<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     10-28 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Analysts Say Botha May Soon Call General Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha may be
heartened enough by the overall results of this week's local
elections to call a general election in a few months, political
analysts said Friday.
   Botha's National Party lost about 90 communities Wednesday to
far-right candidates opposed to his ideas for limited desegregation
and power-sharing with blacks, but won in Johannesburg and Pretoria
and repelled Conservative Party challenges almost everywhere outside
Transvaal, the most populous province.
   ``There is enough positive news for the National Party in the
results to tempt them into a general election,'' said Richard
Humphries, a political scientist at Johannesburg's University of the
Witwatersrand.
   David Braun, political correspondent for The Star, the country's
largest daily newspaper, said support existed within Botha's Cabinet
for a general election in March or April, a year earlier than
required.
   Braun and other analysts suggested Botha may calculate that
despite its gains, the Conservative Party has shown itself incapable
of winning a national election.
   Experts interviewed by The Star said the Conservatives, who now
hold 23 of Parliament's 178 seats, could add 11 to 23 more if a
general election were held soon.
   Botha signaled his interest in wooing right-wing voters by
forwarding to the President's Council on Friday a controversial bill
to tighten enforcement of the Group Areas Act, which mandates racial
segregation of residential areas.
   The council, controlled by the National Party, has the power to
implement deadlocked legislation, such as the group areas bill.
Parliament's white chamber approved the bill but its smaller
chambers for Asians and people of mixed race rejected it. The black
majority is excluded from Parliament.
   Party leader Andries Treurnicht said his Conservatives will
resegregate business districts in towns it now controls. Chris
Heunis, the constitutional development minister, said only
Parliament can do that.
   The Citizen, a pro-government Johannesburg newspaper, urged Botha
to dispel the impression that his party was uncertain how to deal
with black political demands.
   ``The Conservative Party capitalizes on this uncertainty by
simply suggesting that whatever the government does or plans to do
will put another nail in the white man's coffin,'' The Citizen said.
   ``Many moderate voters would give the National Party their
support if it got its act togther and spelled out where it is taking
South Africa.''
   The Star said the local elections gave Botha two reasons to
proceed with reform: ``First, the Conservative challenge has been
brought down to Earth, and second, the considerable stayaway in the
black, colored (mixed-race) and Indian elections highlights a
vehement rejection of the present system of government.''
   Noting that Conservative Party supporters are less than 4 percent
of the population, it said: ``Reform cannot afford to be halted by
such puny opposition.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
