<DOCNO> AP881028-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Palestinians     10-28 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palestinians,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Huge Arsenal Seized with Palestinians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police seized anti-tank rockets,
grenades, automatic weapons and explosives during raids that netted
14 people suspected of being Palestinian terrorists, prosecutors
said Friday.
   One security source said ``you could arm an army'' with such an
arsenal.
   Sources have said those arrested planned an attack in a foreign
country, not identified, but spokesman Alexander Prechtel of the
chief federal prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe said Friday the
target's nature was not clear.
   A senior State Department official in Washington said privately
that West German police suspect the Palestinians planned to hit
American or Israeli targets, but he added that information available
to the United States was sketchy.
   Prechtel said 10 of the 14 detained in the raids Wednesday and
Thursday had been released, but did not say why or whether they
might face charges later. He would not name the four still held but
said they were men, two born in Syria and two in Jordan, in the age
range 35 to 46.
   Earlier official reports had said 13 people were arrested in the
raids on 18 locations in West Berlin, Hamburg, Frankfurt and Neuss,
just outside Duesseldorf.
   According to Prechtel, one of the Jordanian-born men had been
sentenced to life imprisonment in Israel but was released in a 1979
prisoner swap. He had gone to Israel on a terrorist mission in 1968
and was arrested after the explosives he was carrying exploded
prematurely, wounding him, the spokesman said.
   He said man the arrived in West Germany from Damascus, capital of
Syria. Prechtel said the four men kept in custody were suspected of
establishing a terrorist cell of the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command in West Germany and storing
weapons.
   Ahmad Jibril, a former Syrian army captain, leads the
Syrian-controlled Palestinian group, which opposes Yasser Arafat,
chief of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Western and Middle East intelligence reports say Jibril's men
have been assigned temporarily to Syrian and Libyan secret services
in the past to carry out assasinations and bombings.
   The Washington official said Syria's role with the PFLP-General
Command was a major reason for continuing cool relations between the
United States and President Hafez Assad's government.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said: ``We commend
the German authorities for the outstanding police and intelligence
work. ... This demonstrates that international terrorism remains a
threat.''
   Chief federal prosecutor Kurt Rebmann has taken over the
investigation of the Palestinians, Prechtel said.
   About the possible targets, he said in a telephone interview:
   ``We can conclude that we are dealing with an organization. We
can conclude that they were planning the most serious crimes,
including murder, but where, when, against whom and with what
motives is still totally unclear.''
   Describing what was found in just one Frankfurt apartment,
Prechtel listed an anti-tank bazooka, 25 grenades, more than six
pounds of TNT, several pounds of other explosives, six machine guns,
and other weapons and ammunition.
   He said police found many detonating devices, including a
battery-powered delay-action detonator, at an apartment in Neuss,
and seized false papers that included forged passports of several
countries.
   Security sources said privately of the men in custody arrived in
West Germany in recent months and the fourth lived here. They said
all had been under surveillance and ``we had them under control.''
   West German authorities had expressed concern about possible
terrorist attacks linked to the trial in Frankfurt of confessed TWA
hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi, a Shiite Moslem from Lebanon.
   Chief Duesseldorf prosecutor Jochen Ruhland said Thursday,
however, that ``we have no clues'' of such a connection.
</TEXT>
