<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-IRA     10-28 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-IRA,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say IRA Has Enough Arms But a Shortage of Top Agents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army has enough
Libyan-supplied weapons but is facing a shortage of top agents
willing to risk their lives, senior British military sources serving
in Northern Ireland said Friday.
   The sources, from headquarters in Belfast, spoke with the
condition they not be identified.
   They said that despite the IRA's problems, its terrorist campaign
was expected to continue, especially against British soldiers on the
British mainland and in Western Europe.
   ``The assessment is that they (IRA guerrillas) have come to the
conclusion that killing English, Scottish and Welsh soldiers causes
more pain and grief than killing Irish soldiers,'' one source said.
   This year IRA guerrillas have killed 26 British military
personnel in attacks in England and Europe.
   The source said it was impossible to say if the IRA is now
stronger or weaker. It began its campaign nearly 20 years ago to
unite Northern Ireland, a British province where Protestants
outnumber Roman Catholics 3-2, with the predominantly Catholic Irish
Republic under a leftist government.
   The IRA is stronger because it is much better armed but it also
is weaker because its support in the Catholic community has
decreased and the number of people personally involved in its
terrorism has dropped, according to the source.
   He said six years ago the IRA would call off an attack if it
risked losing a ``prestige weapon'' such as a shoulder-fired,
rocket-propelled grenade, but an estimated 150 tons of weapons from
Libya have given the group a high-quality arsenal.
   The source said security forces in Northern Ireland have captured
about five tons of IRA weapons but it is believed most of the Libyan
shipments remain hidden in the Republic of Ireland with small
amounts smuggled across the border when needed.
   ``We believe that they've got the arms they need now to sustain a
campaign at the level which they've been running recently for a
matter of years,'' he added.
   The sources said the Libyan shipments have included heavy machine
guns, rocket-propelled grenades, quantities of commercial explosives
and Soviet-made SAM-7 surface-to-air missiles capable of downing
helicopters and other aircraft. No surface-to-air missiles have been
used in the Northern Ireland conflict.
   ``The critical factor at the moment is ... the people that
they've got with the bottle (courage) to really press home an attack
and risk their life,'' another source said.
   He suggested the IRA was short of such guerrillas because of
``war weariness'' and the possibilities of death or long prison
terms.
   ``Take the hardest of the hard core _ perhaps being the shooters
_ perhaps there are only 20 or 30,'' he said.
   There are others willing to plant bombs, store and transport
weapons and help the terrorists, but support for the IRA is
dwindling, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0214 </DOCNO>
