<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChambersTrial     10-28 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chambers Trial,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chambers Brothers, Five Others Convicted Of Running Drug Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine of 10 people accused of running what was once
the city's largest cocaine ring were convicted Friday and a judge
said their conspiracy had been ``a serious threat'' to the community.
   The Chambers brothers organization allegedly supplied cocaine to
about half the estimated 1,000 drug houses in the nation's
sixth-largest city, and imported youngsters from Arkansas to help.
   U.S. Attorney Roy C. Hayes said the convictions won't have an
immediate effect on cocaine trafficking in Detroit.
   ``We're not going to reduce the supply in a case ... from 1983 to
1987,'' he said. ``But I think the harsh message ... will begin to
send a lesson.''
   Some of the 10 defense attorneys said they planned to review a
transcript of the trial to determine if an appeal would be filed.
   ``I think it is very difficult in these times for a person
accused of trafficking narcotics to get a fair trial as, say, a
person accused of murder,'' said Charles Lusby, attorney for Billie
Joe Chambers. ``I'm not saying my client didn't get a fair trial,
but I believe there's a bias in our community and it is very
difficult for people to set aside that bias.''
   Convicted of conspiracy were Willie, Larry, Billie Joe and Otis
Chambers along with Eric L. Wilkins, Elaine Coleman Lucas, Belinda
Lumpkin, Jerry Gant and Marshall Glenn.
   U.S. District Richard Suhrheinrich revoked bonds for three of the
defendants who had been free during the six-week trial, declaring:
``The court finds that this conspiracy is a threat, a serious
threat, to this community.''
   Paul Young was acquitted of conspiracy for allegedly hiring
teen-agers to process crack cocaine. However, Young already is
serving a life sentence for first-degree murder.
   Larry and Billie Joe Chambers also were convicted of running a
continuing criminal enterprise, involving the recruitment of
youngsters from Marianna, Ark., where the brothers once lived. The
recruits were brought to Detroit to work in cocaine houses.
   Those two brothers and Lucas also were convicted of cocaine
possession with intent to distribute, Larry Chambers was convicted
of a firearms charge and Willie Chambers was convicted of tax
evasion.
   No sentencing date was set. Maximum penalties range from 20 years
to life in prison and $2 million in fines each.
</TEXT>
