<2ND_LINE>AM-Politics-Quotes,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quotes From the Presidential Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Friday from the
presidential campaign trail:
   
   DAN QUAYLE, hitting on Dukakis while touring Pennsylvania Dutch
country, renowned for its tasty pretzels: ``Mr. Dukakis has made
more twists and turns on the issues than any one of your pretzels.
Maybe that ought to be the symbol of their campaign _ the pretzel.''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, deriding his opponent for shunning network
television appearances: ``Mr. Bush is out there in his little
cocoon. They won't let him out. We're taking our case directly to
the American people.''
   
   GEORGE BUSH, saying Dukakis contends American families are better
off only because women have been forced into the work force:
``Frankly, that strikes me as sexist _ because it implies that women
wouldn't work unless they had to.''
   
   LLOYD BENTSEN, telling Oakland high school students to work hard,
shun drugs, and vote: ``When you come right down to it, in an urban
area like Oakland, the war on drugs in our schools will be won or
lost by a series of millions of personal decisions made by students
like you.''
   
   GEORGE BUSH, a day after pledging to end the campaign on a
kindler, gentler note: ``I ask you to consider: What kind of morning
would electing the liberal governor of Massachusetts bring? Will it
be gloomy. Will the dark clouds of pessimism and limited possibility
obscure our vision?''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, continuing to bank on a Harry Truman-like
comeback: ``In politics, as you all know, 11 days is an eternity.
There is time to do it.''
   
   CLIFTON DANIEL, Truman's son-in-law, saying President Reagan was
talking nonsense when he said the Democrat would be a Republican if
he were alive today: ``President Truman would shoot himself before
he became a Republican.''
</TEXT>
