<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Liar'sClub 2ndLd-Writethru a0690 10-28 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liar's Club, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0690,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Politicians, Only Amateurs, Allowed At Liar's Club</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with winning liar, Cavett's
comments; Picks up 5th graf, `Championship lies...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANNEBROG, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Liar's Hall of Fame issued
its annual Pinocchio Award on Friday to a farm columnist who said
the drought was so bad in Ohio that a Roman Catholic priest tried to
turn wine back into water.
   Politicians were ineligible for the grand prize won by Russell
Hoy, a columnist for the Ohio Farmer.
   ``We have a rule that politicians can't participate, only
amateurs,'' said Roger Welsch, the hall's founder and an expert in
Nebraska folklore.
   Even Vice President George Bush, who was to campaign Friday
evening in Omaha, was told to keep his distance from the competition
crowning the teller of this year's tallest tale.
   Well, actually, the liars just didn't bother to invite him.
   Entertainer Johnny Carson, who grew up in Nebraska, didn't show
up either, but he received special recognition for his
``contribution to the art of the tall tale'' during the induction
ceremony at Eric's Big Table Tavern.
   ``It's hard to sort out what's true and what's not in a Liar's
Club,'' said Linda Welsch, Roger's wife.
   Dick Cavett, another Nebraska native, was on hand for the
induction ceremony and received a ``public service'' award for his
comedy radio program.
   ``All my life I've dreamed of being here. Whoops!'' he said, to
the laughter of veteran liars.
   Hoy's winning lie said the 1988 drought was so dry that ``the
Baptists were sprinkling and the Presbyterians were using a damp
cloth'' for baptisms.
   He said, ``the Lutherans were passing out rain checks and at
least one Catholic priest was working at turning wine back into
water.''
   Championship lies honored the past two years were told by one
competitor who said he once met an honest fisherman, and another who
claimed he once saw a lawyer standing outside on a cold winter day
with his hands in his own pockets.
   Many of this year's yarns targeted the summer drought, including
an anonymous entry from nearby Central City that insisted
authorities had banned water skiing on the Platte River because it
was kicking up too much dust.
   ``Most people, deep down inside, like to stretch a story,'' said
Eric Nielsen, owner of the tiny tavern. ``I don't know why, but all
of us are guilty of it.''
   The 2-year-old Liar's Hall consists of three plaques on a wooden
wall near the men's room along with pictures of Presidents
Washington, Johnson, Nixon and Reagan.
   ``The pictures are there because of the old story that Washington
never told a lie, Johnson never told the truth and Nixon never knew
the difference,'' Nielsen said, adding that Reagan has been added
``because he forgot.''
   This year's event got a great deal of publicity, and organizers
worried about how to come up with an induction ceremony that would
satisfy the expectations of out-of-towners.
   ``The problem is, in the past the ceremony itself was all
fabricated,'' Mrs. Welsch said. ``It's really gotten out of hand.''
   A news release described the induction as the 37th annual event
and said it was attended by a crowd of 1,455 in white ties.
   Nielsen said he tried to discourage reporters from attending.
``We thought about telling them when they got here that it was
already over and we just lied about the time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0217 </DOCNO>
