<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HotelFire     10-28 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Fire,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Girl Released On Bail in Arson Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British tourist charged with setting a fatal Miami
Beach hotel fire was released on $100,000 bail Friday after spending
five weeks in jail.
   Tara Jane Terry, 19, of Camberley, England, is accused of arson
in the Sept. 17 fire at the Nassau Hotel that resulted in the deaths
of two elderly residents. A third person remains in a coma.
   Miss Terry faces a maximum of life in prison if convicted. No
trial date has been set.
   Her boyfriend, Mark Edward Richardson, 20, was briefly detained
as a material witness and has been free on $100,000 bond.
   According to an affidavit filed by a federal agent, Miss Terry
and Richardson were arguing when they arrived at the Nassau Hotel
the night of the fire. Federal agents and firefighters determined
the fire was set when she was in the room alone and Richardson was
downstairs talking to the manager.
   Miss Terry's lawyer, Richard Sharpstein, argued Friday before
Magistrate Linnea Johnson that a Miami minister and Miss Terry's
mother, Chrissy Terry, would be responsible for her if she were
released on bail.
   He said the minister has offered Miss Terry a job as a
fund-raising volunteer for the church and an apartment for the
mother and daughter.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Edward Nucci made no objection. Other
bail conditions included a 10 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew and frequent
reporting to court officials.
   Nucci said state prosecutors are conducting a separate
investigation in the case.
</TEXT>
