<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShipsReturn     10-28 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ships Return,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frigates Return From Gulf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four guided missile frigates that
escorted U.S.-flagged oil tankers in the Persian Gulf returned home
here Friday, six months to the day after they left.
   The USS Halyburton arrived first, docking at 8:30 a.m. at the
Charleston Naval Base. Sailors were greeted by several hundred
family members and friends and a rainbow.
   ``How did you arrange the rainbow?'' one homecoming sailor said
to a reporter.
   Crowds also greeted the USS Fahrion, USS Nicholas and USS Robert
G. Bradley when those ships arrived shortly after the Halyburton.
About 800 sailors were aboard the four Oliver Hazard Perry-class
frigates.
   The four ships left Charleston April 28 to join the Navy's Middle
East Task Force, escorting convoys of Kuwaiti tankers and other
neutral vessels.
   Cmdr. Louis J. Giannotti commanded the Halyburton. ``This cruise
was fabulous. It was probably the most rewarding of my career. I
felt like I was really practicing my profession,'' he said.
   The ships responded to attacks by Iranian forces against neutral
tankers, conducted search-and-rescue missions and rescued two downed
helicopter pilots.
   The Halyburton also interrupted what appeared to be an attack
that was being mounted by five Iranian patrol boats against a
tanker, Giannotti said.
   Between July 24, 1987 _ when the Kuwaiti supertanker Bridgeton
struck a mine while under U.S. escort _ and the Iraq-Iran cease-fire
on Aug. 20, 1988, Navy ships and aircraft engaged in more than a
dozen armed clashes with Iranian forces and encounters with Iraqi
warplanes.
   On July 3, the missile cruiser USS Vincennes mistook an Iranian
jetliner for a military attack plane and shot it down, killing all
290 aboard.
   In August, a U.S. nuclear-powered aircraft carrier and nine other
warships steamed into the Arabian Sea to replace other U.S. vessels
in helping to protect Persian Gulf oil shipments, the U.S. Navy said.
</TEXT>
