<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Teamsters     10-28 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Teamster Chief Addresses Members, Defends Bush Endorsement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters President William McCarthy on Friday
defended his union's backing of George Bush for president, while
telling over 1,500 members he's prepared to fight to keep the union
a strong, unified force.
   ``Bush, I know, will do a good job,'' McCarthy said after
delivering a state-of-the-union address to representatives of 750
locals from around the nation.
   ``Dukakis, there's no way he can run the country if he can't run
the state,'' McCarthy said of the Massachusetts governor.
   Vice President Bush, the Republican candidate, was favored by
50.2 percent of the Teamsters surveyed in a recent union poll.
Democrat Michael Dukakis was backed by 46.4 percent of the union
members.
   The union endorsed Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984. The AFL-CIO,
which the Teamsters rejoined last year, is supporting Dukakis.
   McCarthy, 61, of Boston, was elected head of the Teamsters after
the death of Jackie Presser in July. He is known to dislike Dukakis.
   Republican Gov. James R. Thompson, who briefly addressed the
meeting, sparked some boos from the audience when he said he was
there to deliver Bush's thanks for the endorsement.
   However, McCarthy defended throwing the union's support to the
GOP. ``The time has changed. No longer do you vote for the party,
you vote for the man,'' he said.
   McCarthy declined to say what tactic his union, the nation's
largest, would take should Bush, if elected, pursue the federal
government's lawsuit to force reforms on the Teamsters.
   The civil racketeering lawsuit, filed in New York in June, is
aimed at cleansing the union of alleged mob influence, federal
officials say.
   ``I'll cross that bridge when I come to it,'' McCarthy said. But
he added that he hopes Bush ``gives me what I want.''
   One of the delegates, Chuck Mack, president of Teamsters' Joint
Council No. 7 in San Francisco, predicted McCarthy is ``going to be
judged on the role he plays in contract negotiations'' and other,
more fundamental issues.
   McCarthy won points among the rank-and-file Friday for his vow to
play a hands-on role in bargaining and organizing.
   Evidence, members say, is the union's decision earlier this month
to abolish a decades-old practice requiring two-thirds ``no'' votes
to turn down tentative accords negotiated by its top leaders.
   The new policy requires only a simple majority _ any ``yes'' vote
greater than 50 percent _ to approve contracts covering the
international's membership.
   It is considered a major victory for the rank-and-file, said
Teamsters spokesman Chip Roth. ``They love it,'' McCarthy said in a
brief meeting with reporters after Friday's address.
   He declined to discuss what dissidents say led to the action _ a
lawsuit challenging a decision by top Teamster officials in May to
ignore a 63.5 percent membership rejection of a contract covering an
estimated 200,000 interstate truckers and warehouse workers.
   ``We don't have any problems,'' McCarthy said tersely. ``We all
love each other.''
</TEXT>
