<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Children'sHome     10-28 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rev. Herman Fountain Pleads Innocent to Assault Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who runs a home where 72 children
were removed amid abuse and neglect allegations pleaded innocent
Friday to charges of assaulting a police officer.
   ``I didn't feloniously hit them. I didn't double up my fist and
hit anyone,'' the Rev. Herman Fountain said before he was arraigned
in George County Circuit Court.
   Fountain and three assistants at the Bethel Children's Home were
indicted by a grand jury Tuesday on three counts of felonious
assault on law enforcement officers.
   The charges stem from a June incident in which the state took
temporary custody of 72 youngsters after a 14-year-old male runaway
testified that he and other young residents were physically abused
at the home.
   Most children have been returned to their parents. The state
retained custody of 17 who were ruled as abused and neglected.
   Fountain, 38, proprietor of the independent Baptist boarding
home, says he believes in strict discipline and the Biblical dictum
``spare the rod, spoil the child.''
   He maintains the state has no right to question his disciplinary
measures because he answers only to God. Church-run homes are exempt
from state regulation in Mississippi, but the state has the power to
investigate abuse cases.
   Fountain and his assistants were released on property bonds they
posted in June.
