<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WarsawPact     10-28 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Warsaw Pact,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Ministers Call for East-West Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers of the Soviet-led
Warsaw Pact on Friday proposed an East-West summit to review
reductions in military forces and conventional armaments in Europe,
the MTI news agency reported.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze and the top diplomats
of the six other pact members _ Hungary, Poland, Bulgaria, East
Germany, Romania and Czechoslovakia _ are attending a meeting that
opened Friday, MTI said.
   The official Hungarian agency said that in a statement issued
late Friday the ministers proposed a summit of all European
countries, plus the United States and Canaca, to review cuts in
conventional armed forces on the continent.
   The statement on ``confidence- and security-building measures and
disarmament in Europe'' also called for the banning of large
military maneuvers and reductions in the size, duration and
frequency of other maneuvers.
   MTI said the foreign ministers proposed:
   _Notification of independent activities by air and naval forces
and creation of zones of confidenece and security in Europe and the
adjoining seas and oceans
   _The freezing and reduction of military expenditures and the
establishment of a European information and contact-maintaining
center for the prevention of any surprise attack
   _Measures for the regular exchange of data about the armed forces
and their operations and for the exchange of information on the
structure and substance of military budgets.
   The statement said the proposals were meant ``to make the
military potentials of the participating states become strictly
defensive in nature.''
   Among topics to be discussed by the ministers is the conference
being held in Vienna to review compliance with the Helsinki accords
on European security that were signed in 1975 by virtually all
European countries and America and Canada.
   Earlier this month at the Vienna conference the Soviets removed a
major obstacle to proposed new talks on reducing conventional
weapons in Europe.
   Diplomats in Geneva said the Soviets reversed their stand and
agreed that tactical nuclear weapons would not be included in the
new talks between members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
and Warsaw Pact on conventional forces.
   The new negotiations would replace the Mutual and Balanced Force
Reduction talks that have dragged on in Vienna for 15 years.
</TEXT>
