<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0668 10-28 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0668,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Drops `Kinder, Gentler' Tone Day After Promising No More
Negative</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB final graf with five grafs to UPDATE with Omaha
appearance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush described
Michael Dukakis on Friday as a sexist who would torpedo prosperity
and bring gloom and malaise upon America.
   And that was just for openers the day after he resolved to wage a
gentler, kinder presidential campaign in its concluding days.
   ``Los Angeles is the movie capital of the world, and if my
opponent is elected the movie will be called `Malaise Two: The
Sequel,''' Bush said, recalling the word that figured in the
political downfall of President Carter.
   At a California town hall breakfast in Los Angeles, Bush stuck to
the economic theme he has stresse every day this week. One message
that didn't vary: his insistence that Americans are far better off
today than when President Reagan came to office in 1980.
   The vice president said Dukakis would scrap policies that work in
favor of new spending plans and probably new taxes. ``He wants to
torpedo the prosperity that we have worked so hard to achieve,''
Bush told about 600 people at the Los Angeles breakfast.
   He said the Democratic nominee contends American families are
better off because women have been forced into the work force.
``Frankly, that strikes me as sexist _ because it implies that women
wouldn't work unless they had to,'' Bush said.
   At the California Highway Patrol Academy in Sacramento, Bush was
received endorsements from two police organizations, the California
Correctional Peace Officers Association, claiming 18,000 members,
and the International Association aof Correctional Officers, which
says it represents 300,000 lawmen.
   Bush said that of all his differences with Dukakis, none is
``deeper and wider'' than on crimefighting, on such matters as the
death penalty, tough judges, prison furloughs.
   The GOP candidate said he believes that most of the policemen who
have endorsed his campaign consider themselves Democrats.
   ``A lot of mainstream Americans feel that the national Democratic
Party in 1988 just simply doesn't represent them any more,'' he said.
   ``You might almost say that the Democratic Party today suffers
from a split personality with a rank and file made up of some of the
best of America, the silent majority . . .'' he said. ``But the
leadership, much of it, is a remnant of the 60s, the new left, those
campus radicals grown old, the peace marchers and the nuclear freeze
activists.''
   Bush said he represents mainstream America.
   Any trend toward campaign kindness was marginal at most, despite
the resolution Bush offered in the euphoria of a Hollywood reception
Thursday night on the floodlit lawn at Bob Hope's giant estate.
   ``We're not going to be talking on the negative side any more,''
Bush said then. ``...It's going to be a kinder and gentler finish to
this campaign.''
   Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff, said Friday the comment did
not signal any change in campaign strategy or in GOP television
advertisements. ``He wants to talk positively, but that doesn't mean
he won't continue to draw contrasts to his opponent,'' Fuller said.
   The GOP nominee said voters should think of peace and prosperity
when they go to the polls Nov. 8. ``Peace means you can sleep at
night knowing that the world will still be there in the morning,''
Bush said. ``Prosperity means you can sleep at night knowing that
opportunity will still be there in the morning.
   ``But I ask you to consider what kind of morning would electing
the liberal governor of Massachusetts bring, would a Democratic
morning bring?
   ``Will it be gloomy? Will the dark clouds of pessimism and
limited opportunity obscure our vision?''
   In Omaha Friday night, Bush campaigned with Nebraska's appointed
Sen. David Karnes, struggling to hold a GOP seat against favored
former Gov. Bob Kerrey.
   He taunted Dukakis over farm policy,a recalling the grain embargo
imposed against the Soviet Union by President Carter. He said it
didn't work then and it wouldn't work now.
   ``I will never use food as a political embargo tool,'' he told a
rally at Omaha Civic Auditorium.
   On Saturday, Bush scheduled a six-stop bus tour in the Chicago
area, wrapping up the next to the last week of the campaign with
another push for the 24 electoral votes Illinois will award on Nov.
8.
   Bush said one of two men will be elected president that day.
``Only one of us is on the move and headed in the right direction
and that is me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
