<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Drops Attack, Tells Students to Vote, Shun Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, The Texas...,with two grafs to update with
Texas rally.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd
Bentsen put aside negative partisan rhetoric as he finished a
California swing Friday, telling high school students to work hard,
to shun drugs and to vote.
   Bentsen visited Oakland Tech, a mostly black school which has
raised its national test scores and community standing with the help
of special programs for youths interested in health care and
computers.
   ``The fact that you are attending Oakland Tech means you have a
bright future,'' he said. ``And the best way to destroy that future
for all time is to become involved with drugs.''
   Bentsen said he and Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential
nominee, would launch an effective fight against drugs, but he also
said that effort would not succeed unless students did their part.
   ``When you come right down to it, in an urban area like Oakland,
the war on drugs in our schools will be won or lost by a series of
millions of personal decisions made by students like you,'' he said.
   The Texas senator returned to his home state later Friday, and
attended a rally of about 500 supporters in Austin. Bentsen
defiantly held up a reprint of the 1948 Chicago Tribune that bore
the front-page headline, ``Dewey Defeats Truman'' and told the
supporters, ``That's the kind of comeback we're looking forward to
having.''
   Bentsen was introduced at the California school rally by Sen.
Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and actor Danny Glover, best known for his
part in the movie ``Lethal Weapon.''
   Glover, who is black, told the students packing the gymnasium
that his mother, now 93, was kept from voting by discriminatory
practicies until she was 60. Apathy was not acceptable, he said.
   ``Too much blood has been shed ... to bring us to this point,''
he said.
   Cranston turned to the presidential race, saying of the
Republicans, ``They think the campaign is over. They're back in the
locker room.''
   Bentsen, who planned to vote absentee in Texas this weekend to
push a get-out-the-vote drive, made no mention of George Bush or Dan
Quayle. He urged the students to vote Democratic _ if they are old
enough to vote _ and to get their parents and friends to the voting
booth.
   The gymnasium walls were papered with signs welcoming Bentsen,
including one picturing the school's bulldog mascot wearing a cowboy
hat.
   In the middle of his speech, Bentsen suddenly stopped, as he
noticed the scoreboard. It was set up with the Dukakis-Bentsen home
team having 47 points _ the number of electoral votes in California
_ and the Bush-Quayle team with zero.
   ``I just saw the score up there,'' he said. ``That's great. It
convinces me even more the best America is yet to come.''
</TEXT>
