<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HumanHeads     10-28 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Human Heads,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spector Gets Probation In Heads Shipment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 72-year-old doctor who shipped human heads
and other body parts from Pennsylvania was placed on two years'
probation Friday, fined $35,200 and ordered to perform 1,600 hours
service in the city's prisons.
   Dr. Martin Spector had pleaded no contest to charges that
included theft of the body parts he received from morgue employees
at the University of Pennsylvania and Jefferson hospitals.
   Spector, an ear, nose and throat specialist, faced a maximum
sentence of 8{ to 17 years in prison.
   Spector's lawyer, Joel Slomsky told Common Pleas Judge Mark
Bernstein his client was a dedicated doctor for nearly half a
century and his motivation was continued medical research.
   It was brought out that Spector, over the years, had made about
$10,000 sending ear bones and heads to research centers in Colorado
and elsewhere.
   Slomsky, however, while acknowledging that while Spector violated
the laws of Pennsylvania, said his client didn't realize what he was
doing was illegal and what he received was minuscule.
   The investigation began more than two years ago when United
Parcel Service workers in Louisville, Ky., noticed something leaking
from a foul-smelling package. When they opened the box to repackage
it, they found human heads inside. The box bore Spector's return
address.
   Spector was one of five people charged in the case. Three of four
morgue workers have pleaded guilty and are on probation. Charges
against the fourth worker were dismissed.
   Before imposing the sentence, the judge told Spector that ``your
crime is the result of poor judgement. A donated body should be
respectfully treated and then properly interred. No one can trample
on the rights of those people in the name of science.''
   Under Pennsylvania law, bodies can be donated to medical schools
through a state affiliate knowns as the Humanities Gift Registry.
   Spector refused to talk to reporters after leaving court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
