<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadetsStricken-Reax     10-28 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken-Reax,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family of Sick Cadet Hints at Lawsuit Concerning Training Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Cadets Stricken, Bjt
^By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of a cadet who needed a liver
transplant after his first day of state police academy training said
Friday they were satisfied by a probe that faulted the program, but
hinted that a lawsuit was in the offing.
   ``I'm pleased on the one hand, but not at all on the other,''
said Bruce Mendel, father-in-law of Cadet Timothy Shepard, who
remains in serious condition. ``We can show that there was intent to
harm the cadets.''
   Methods at the training academy in Agawam in western
Massachusetts came under scrutiny when Shepard collapsed, slipped
into a coma and had to undergo a liver transplant operation.
   He has since regained consciousness but remains unable to speak.
   Attorney General James Shannon said Friday an investigation found
a ``top-to-bottom'' failure by the state to protect the cadets. The
academy's physical training program was found to be brutally
vigorous.
   At least 10 other cadets from Shepard's class were hospitalized
for ills stemming from intense exercise and dehydration.
   Shannon said he planned no prosecution of trainers but called for
the chief of the agency to either resign or be dismissed.
   Gary Egan, the council's executive director, took a paid leave of
absence starting Wednesday.
   Mendel said he has learned that two state troopers who supervised
instruction at the academy called an ambulance before class began to
stand by during the first day of training.
   ``Doesn't that tell you something about their intent?'' he said.
   Mendel also said he would like to see other officials removed as
a result of the Agawam injuries.
   ``There were people to blame from the top down, yet they're all
still working and the one guy who is gone is still getting paid,''
he said. ``I hope he doesn't go too far because we're going to see
him in court and we don't want to go all over the United States
looking for him.''
   Egan's telephone number at his Wellesley home was unlisted. His
replacement, Acting Director James Canty, did not return a telephone
call to his office.
</TEXT>
