<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AbortionProtests 1stLd-Writethru a0726 10-28 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,0826</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 120 Arrested As Weekend Of Anti-Abortion Protests Begins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with arrests in Florida; picks
up
4th graf: `In Indianapolis ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 120 demonstrators were arrested in three states Friday
as anti-abortion activists kicked off a weekend of protests calling
for pickets or blockades at abortion clinics in 32 cities.
   Operation Rescue founder Randall Terry, whose group organized the
protests, was among at least 50 demonstrators who were arrested
Friday morning as they picketed an abortion clinic in Vestal, N.Y.
   Vestal Police Chief Frank J. Croom said those arrested will be
charged with resisting arrest and trespassing. Terry could face
additional charges, including conspiracy to commit a crime, he said.
   In Mary Esther, Fla., sheriff's deputies arrested 34
anti-abortion demonstrators who had blocked the doors of a clinic
operated by Family Planning of Fort Walton Beach. Those arrested
were among about 120 protesters who converged upon the clinic in the
Florida Panhandle suburb.
   Okaloosa County Sheriff Larry Gilbert said he sympathized with
the protesters' views, but not their demonstrations.
   ``I do feel we're being used. That's for sure. They do use us and
the media and they're certainly doing it now,'' he said.
   In Indianapolis, 40 protesters were arrested after they blocked
entrances to two women's clinics. Police said they were charged with
criminal trespass.
   ``It was very peaceful,'' said Wendy Snitko, a spokeswoman for
the Indianapolis Police Department. ``There were no problems with
any of the protesters, whatsoever.''
   The demonstrations marked a continuation of the anti-abortion
campaign that has resulted in some 7,000 arrests across the country
in the past five months. The campaign began in Atlanta in July, and
more than 1,200 people have been arrested in 20 demonstrations in
the Georgia capital since then.
   Bob Nolte, a spokesman for Operation Rescue, said the
demonstrations Saturday will be conducted ``Atlanta-style.'' The
demonstrators in Atlanta, most of whom came from outside the city,
refused to move from entrances to women's clinics, forcing police to
carry or drag them to police buses.
   Once jailed, hundreds declined to give their names or refused to
sign bail bonds, clogging the jail and court systems and costing the
city in excess of $500,000 in police overtime, jail and court costs.
   ``A lot of these people will be first-timers,'' said Nolte, who
runs a campus ministry at the University of Florida in Gainesville.
   He said Operation Rescue cannot control the tactics used in the
various cities but estimated there may be 4,000 to 5,000 arrests
across the nation this weekend.
   Jesse Lee, pastor of the Neighborhood Church in Manhattan, told a
news conference Friday that protest groups will hit 32 cities
Saturday and will range in size from three to 1,000 people.
   Among the cities Lee identified as targets were Jackson, Miss.;
New York; San Francisco; Dallas; Buffalo, N.Y.; Binghamton, N.Y.,
and Pittsburgh. The New York protest would violate a federal judge's
injunction against the group.
   ``This is not just a bunch of radical gypsies traveling around
the country, from place to place, getting arrested,'' Lee said.
``This is Smalltown, U.S.A., rising up against abortion.''
   In Phoenix, Operation Rescue director John Salvatore said about
80 people will ``intervene'' Saturday at abortion clinics when women
try to enter. He would not define what he meant by ``intervene.''
   ``It will be peaceful, but all of us are going to risk arrest,''
he said.
   In Wyoming, which has no abortion clinics, activists will mark
the day with a prayer vigil in Evanston, Nolte said.
   In New Jersey, about 100 people gathered Thursday at a church for
a rally and instructions on Operation Rescue tactics. Bill Koehler,
an organizer of the New Jersey protests, said he expects about 300
people to participate in a demonstration Saturday at a single
targeted clinic.
   In South Carolina, Sharon Pfost of the Pro Life Action Network
said 80 to 100 members of her group plan to picket all five clinics
in Columbia that offer abortions.
   In New Orleans, the Rev. Rod Aguillard said he expects at least
200 anti-abortion activists to risk arrest by blocking access to
five clinics. Another 600 protesters are expected to participate in
street demonstrations, he said.
   In Texas, protesters will go to clinics in Austin, San Antonio,
Houston and Dallas on Saturday ``to express our love for the
children who are scheduled to be killed that day,'' said Rex Moses
of Operation Rescue in Austin.
   The Texas Abortion Rights Action League, a group supporting
women's rights to choose whether or not to have an abortion, also
plans a rally Saturday in Austin. Phyllis Dunham, executive director
of the league, said the rally ``is meant to show just how much
community support there is for choice, and how little community
support there is for Operation Rescue.''
</TEXT>
