<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 2230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Trade     10-28 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Trade,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Mulling Increase in Foreign Share in Joint Ventures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is considering almost doubling the
share foreign companies can hold in joint ventures with Soviet
businesses in a major proposal to aid the ailing economy, a Western
diplomat said Friday.
   Under a Jan. 13, 1987, decree of the Council of Ministers,
foreign partners now are limited to owning 49 percent of a joint
venture, and the Soviet side 51 percent.
   Western businessmen said the restriction made it unprofitable for
them to form joint ventures, and they have been complaining to
Soviet officials for months.
   A senior Western diplomat involved in East-West trade said the
Soviets are considering a ``firm proposal'' to allow the foreign
partner to own 80 percent of the joint venture.
   The diplomat, spekaing on condition of anonymity, said some
Soviet officials indicate the foreign partner may even be allowed to
own more than 80 percent of the business.
   He praised the Soviets for acting on Westerners' complaints, but
said the principal problem with joint ventures remains restrictions
on how profits can be taken out of the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet ruble cannot be converted into other currencies on
world markets, so foreign companies must devise ways of either
earning convertible, or ``hard'' currencies, or taking out their
share of the proceeds in Soviet commodities.
   The Communist Party's ruling Politburo decided this month to make
the ruble convertible gradually, but no details have been released
and it is believed such steps will take years.
   Increasing their share will give foreign partners more control
over managing joint ventures and allow more Westerners to be brought
in as employees for the operations, the diplomat said.
   The proposed changes will have to be approved by the Council of
Ministers and the Supreme Soviet, the nominal parliament.
   So far, the Soviet Union has signed 108 joint ventures with
foreign partners, most with Finnish and West German companies. In
addition, American companies have signed six joint venture contracts
with the Soviets. Soviet officials have said 300-400 joint ventures
are under negotiation.
   The Soviets have been actively seeking joint business projects
with capialist countries to help improve the quantity and quality of
consumer goods and to earn convertible foreign currencies to pay for
grain and other imports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
