<DOCNO> AP881028-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 2241EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Navy-Cannibalism     10-28 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy-Cannibalism,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Captain's Attorney Says Language Barrier Led to Tragedy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boatload of Vietnamese refugees that
reportedly turned to cannibalism after being left adrift by a U.S.
Navy ship weren't able to tell of their desperate plight due to a
language barrier, an attorney said Friday.
   The Vietnamese junk, which originally carried 110 people, had
been at sea for 18 days when it met the Navy ship. When the boat was
rescued 19 days later off the coast of the Philippines, it had only
52 survivors, officials said.
   The commander of the USS Dubuque, Capt. Alexander G. Balian, 48,
has been relieved of duty in connection with the June 9 incident and
the Navy is reviewing an investigation to decide whether he should
be court-martialed.
   Dan Donato Jr., civilian attorney for Balian, said the captain
told the Navy that the refugees were misled by an unidentified
Dubuque sailor's inaccurate assertion that help was on the way.
   ``In an effort to provide these people with some hope, he told
them that they would be picked up in a couple of days because the
Navy had contacted another ship to do that,'' Denato said.
   ``He was of Vietnamese extraction and, perhaps, spoke better
Vietnamese than English. I think that was, perhaps, one of the
problems,'' Donato said.
   Donato's comments at a news conference Friday echoed statements
in documents obtained by The Los Angeles Times, including Balian's
account of the incident and Navy charges against the captain.
   Crew members of the Dubuque, an amphibious ship, gave water,
several hundred pounds of food and navigating equipment to the
refugees aboard the junk after determining that the vessel appeared
seaworthy, Donato said.
   However, that and other information was wrong, he said.
   ``The refugees told me that there were people below decks in bad
need of food and, perhaps, near starvation,'' said Donato, who spoke
to a dozen survivors.
   ``But their understanding of sick or injured didn't include
starvation,'' he added, saying that crew was not advised of any
starving refugees.
   The crew and captain also thought the flat-bottomed boat had been
at sea for seven days, when it actually had been out 18 days, Donato
said.
   Survivors said a 12-year-old boy and a 15-year-old boy were
murdered and eaten, unidentified sources told the Times. A
12-year-old girl who died also was eaten by some of the refugees,
the paper said.
   Balian is charged with violating a general Navy regulation of
``wrongfully failing to render assistance'' to the refugees.
   The Navy also alleges that Balian was derelict in his duty and
negligently failed to investigate sufficiently and give appropriate
assistance.
   A recommendation on whether charges will be brought in a
court-martial is expected within a week, Donato said. An Article 32
hearing, the equivalent of a grand jury proceeding, was completed
earlier this week, he added.
   Donato said Balian sought vital information about the refugees'
condition and the state of the ship and acted properly based upon
the information he received from his crew.
   ``He did make these determinations, but unfortunately in the
press of things and because of the chaotic situation, he didn't get
exactly the right information,'' he said.
   The Dubuque was en route to the Persian Gulf and facing time
constraints, he said.
   ``He had to make a decision as to what was required under the
operational orders. You also have to remember he was anxious, he had
to make 18 knots in order to get to the gulf'' by the assigned time,
Donato said.
   But he said Balian's decision wasn't influenced by scheduling.
   Balian's Navy attorney, Lt. Cmdr. Ron Petronio, said Balian is
currently in Japan awaiting the Navy's recommendation.
   Donato said he expects some charges will be upheld, but the
decision for court-martial is up to Rear Admiral Geoffrey Chesbrough
at the Subic Bay Naval Base in the Philippines.
</TEXT>
