<HEAD>Three Mental Health Center Officials Indicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former top officials of a Provo
mental health center were charged Friday with theft and misuse of
nearly $3.5 million in public funds.
   Glen R. Brown, former executive director of Timpanogos Community
Mental Health Center; Carl V. Smith, former director of specialty
programs; and Craig W. Stephens, former director of administrative
services, were named in indictments filed by the state attorney
general's office.
   Brown, reached at his Provo home, said he had no comment. Smith's
Highland telephone number is unlisted. There was no answer to calls
made to Stephens' Orem residence.
   Attorney General David Wilkinson said the charges follow a
six-month investigation into allegations of financial improprieties
at the the center. Prosecutors charge that from January 1984 to
April 1988 the defendants transferred public money to themselves for
``alleged'' contract services without the knowledge or authorization
of the center's board or the state Division of Mental Health.
   The state charges that Smith averaged $31,243 per month in
unauthorized payments, Stephens $25,540 per month and Brown $9,990.
   The defendants also are accused of using the center's credit card
account to finance personal vacations and buy thousands of dollars
worth of jewelry, furs and clothing.
   The three defendants resigned last April after the legislative
auditor's office unveiled allegations of misappropriation of funds
at the center. Three staff members also were fired after the
revelations.
</TEXT>
