<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CrimeDuo     10-28 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crime Duo,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crime Pair Steal Yachts, Dodge Danger In Fugitive Escapades</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GELSENKIRCHEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two West Germans cruised the
Mediterranean on hot yachts, financed a madcap business venture with
stolen money and tangled up Tangier harbor before justice caught up
with them, police said Friday.
   The pair's wild adventures were detailed by police spokesman
Juergen Matthes in Gelsenkirchen, where both men had been sought for
nearly a year on charges that included theft and flight to avoid
prosecution. The suspects' identities were not disclosed.
   Police said the men's eight-month spree began early this year,
when they stole a vehicle to elude police in West Germany.
   This is the account Matthes gave:
   The two went to Majorca, in the western Mediterranean, where they
stole a yacht worth more than $1.5 million, but the engine promptly
burned up.
   Undaunted, they stole another yacht a short time later, this time
in Portugal. But first they broke into a store and stole a copying
machine and a typewriter to forge the ship's registration papers.
   They found they could have saved themselves the effort. When they
cracked the ship's safe, they found all documents needed plus more
than $5,000 cash in British pounds.
   The two fugitives generously handed out hundreds of bottles of
expensive whiskey found on board to police officials and harbor
authorities as they sailed around the region.
   But they ran into trouble in Tangier, on the northernmost coast
of Morocco, when the yacht's propeller became entangled in mooring
lines.
   One of the men donned stolen underwater gear and freed the
propeller, then swam in front of the yacht to keep it clear, cutting
all mooring lines in his path through the harbor channel.
   ``The result was total chaos in the harbor,'' Matthes said. ``The
fishermen were standing with knives at ready along the breaker
walls.''
   The fugitives eluded the infuriated fishermen, however, and
reached the open sea.
   On Spain's Grand Canary island, they decided to set up an aerial
sightseeing business, although neither had ever flown a plane. They
bought a rusting crop duster with money stolen from a currency
exchange.
   ``Neither of them has a pilot's license, although I think one of
them once sat next to his uncle in a cockpit when he was a child,''
Matthes said.
   The test flight ended in a crash-landing, but an experienced
pilot congratulated them even on that, saying: ``I couldn't have
landed here myself.''
   The yacht-voyaging ended when they ran into a storm while bound
from Tangier to the Canary Islands.
   One man paddled to land on a life raft, but he came ashore in a
restricted military area, was arrested and deported to West Germany
in August.
   His companion managed to steer the yacht into the harbor and
fled. He turned up broke in West Germany two months later and was
arrested by police.
</TEXT>
