<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--UtahQuake     10-28 0123</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Utah Quake,0125</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mild Earthquake In Western Salt Lake Valley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST VALLEY CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake registering magnitude
2 on the Richter Scale bumped the western Salt Lake Valley on
Friday, the University of Utah Seismograph Stations said.
   The temblor at 4:10 p.m. prompted a number of telephone calls
from residents who reported feeling it, said research seismic
analyst Linda Hall.
   Hall said the quake's epicenter was located about two miles north
of the suburb of Granger and seismologists were continuing to study
the event.
   The Richter Scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. A quake of magnitude 2 is the smallest normally felt by
humans.
