<HEAD>Precede MEXICO CITY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Army Troops Seize 11,000 Pounds of Cocaine</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with colonel saying army
confiscated cocaine, location of seizure, details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHIHUAHUA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army troops on a training mission
discovered nearly 11,000 pounds of cocaine stashed in a cave in the
rugged Sierra Madre mountains, a military official said Friday.
   Mexican army Col. Salvador Bejaralo Gomez said the troops came
across the cocaine Thursday afternoon near the town of Buenaventura,
about 120 miles north of Chihuahua, capital of the northern state by
the same name.
   Earlier Friday, the Excelsior news service quoted a federal
police commander as saying that police had discovered the cocaine.
Excelsior said the drug was worth an estimated $3 billion.
   Bejaralo said he could not provide an estimate of the value of
the cocaine, which was stuffed in large canvas bags. The drug was
taken to an army base in Chihuahua and will be destroyed next week,
Bejaralo said by telephone from Chihuahua.
   Military officials did not know who hid the cocaine inside the
cave and no one was arrested, Bejaralo said.
   The Excelsior report came from Acapulco, where law enforcement
officials from 21 Latin American countries were meeting.
   The report called the seizure the largest ever in Mexico.
   The largest cocaine haul ever is 22,000 pounds authorities seized
in Colombia on March 10, 1984.
