<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OrganizedCrime     10-28 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Organized Crime,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indictment Charges Mob Controlled Edgewater Condo Project, Bribed
Ex-Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bosses and associates of the Genovese
organized crime family held hidden interests in a condominium
project in northeastern New Jersey and paid the borough's mayor $500
a week to help build it, according to an indictment unsealed Friday.
   The defendants set up at least seven companies, some controlled
by their wives, to obscure the investors behind the 60-unit Shelter
Bay project in Edgewater.
   Thomas Tansey, Edgewater's mayor from 1980 to 1987 and now
borough clerk, was paid more than $70,000 for two years to push for
the project, smooth its way and quash rivals, the indictment said.
   The organized crime figures also paid off Tansey's gambling
debts, financed his home and vacations and paid for an Atlantic City
hotel room, according to the charges. Tansey denied the allegations.
   The indictment returned Thursday said defendant Donald Ivaldi of
Englewood controlled the Shelter Bay plot despite declaring
bankruptcy in the late 1970s. Defendant Milton Parness, a convicted
swindler from Edgewater, offered to help in developing the property
in exchange for a share of the business, it said.
   Past problems meant they could not obtain bank financing, so they
brought Genovese second-in-command Matthew ``Matty the Horse''
Ianniello into their venture, the court papers said.
   Ianniello ``shared his stake'' with now-retired and jailed
Genovese boss Anthony ``Fat Tony'' Salerno. Salerno was named but
not indicted.
   The defendants deceived Fidelity Union Bank _ now known as First
Fidelity Bank _ into granting loans totaling $21 million to finance
the project, the indictment said.
   Parness, Ivaldi, Ianniello, Tansey and California developer
Nathan Weissman were charged with racketeering and various counts of
extortion, mail fraud and bribery.
   The indictment also alleged schemes to kite checks and extort
kickbacks from subcontractors.
   Tansey and Weissman pleaded innocent at an appearance before U.S.
District Judge John Bissell and were released on $25,000 bond each.
Ivaldi's attorney, John Arseneault, denied the charges.
   The other defendants and their attorneys could not immediately be
reached for comment. An appearance for the other defendants was
scheduled for next Friday.
   The indictment grew out of a 4-year-old investigation into
Genovese activity in New Jersey that led to the conviction in May of
Salerno, the retired family boss, and Ianniello in a New York City
construction industry bid-rigging scheme.
   Ianniello, Ivaldi and Parness were accused with Salerno and
others last May in a Genovese scheme to take control of a Morris
County sand-pit business.
   That case, which is pending, also grew out of the Genovese
investigation, which included months of secretly taped conversations
of crime figures in a construction trailer at the Shelter Bay site.
</TEXT>
