<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OfficerSlainArrest     10-28 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Officer Slain Arrest,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Surrender to Reporter in Officer's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA WOLFSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed gang member suspected of gunning
down a policeman surrendered to a television reporter Thursday along
with a teen-age girl who allegedly drove the getaway car.
   The two were wanted in a Sept. 3 drive-by killing re-enacted
Sunday on TV's ``America's Most Wanted.''
   Kirkton Phenor Moore, 27, a reputed gang member, and his
girlfriend, Raylene Brooks, 17, were accompanied to the Hollywood
police station by KTLA-TV reporter Warren Wilson after surrendering
to him in Las Vegas, police said.
   ``He told me he wanted to turn himself in a long time ago'' but
feared he might be beaten by police, Wilson said.
   Wilson said Moore's mother called him about 10 days ago to see if
he would accept the surrender of her son. Wilson said he notified
police, and worked with them, but police would not say whether they
monitored the surrender.
   ``I felt confident this person was tired of running and wanted to
turn himself in,'' Wilson said.
   Moore proclaimed his innocence, but after watching the television
show, ``he was afraid if he didn't turn himself in, he wouldn't
survive,'' Wilson said.
   Officer Daniel Pratt, 30, was shot in the face while tailing a
car suspected in a drive-by shooting in which three people were
wounded, authorities said.
   Moore is charged with one count of murder with special
circumstances and four counts of attempted murder. The special
circumstances, murder of an officer, could result in the death
penalty. Moore's arraignment, originally set Thursday, was delayed
until Nov. 3, said Andy Reynolds, a spokesman for the district
attorney's office.
   Ms. Brooks pleaded innocent Thursday to one count of murder and
four counts of attempted murder in Compton Juvenile Court and
remained in custody.
   ``I feel a kinship with KTLA and Warren Wilson because they have
done something that we wanted to do but have been unable to do,''
said Police Chief Daryl Gates at a news conference. He said the
department also was indebted to ``America's Most Wanted,'' a Fox
Television production carried by 125 stations.
   The show has profiled 95 fugitives, and 48 are in custody, said
Jack Breslin, a Fox spokesman.
   The City Council and the Los Angeles Police Protective League
offered a $40,000 reward for the couple's capture, but a police
official said Thursday it has not yet been determined who will get
the money.
   Wilson, a Los Angeles reporter who has had three other murder
suspects surrender to him, said he wouldn't accept reward money.
   ``I don't think journalists should get involved with money like
this,'' he said. ``I consider it blood money; in this case, the
blood of a police officer.''
</TEXT>
