<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Nuclear     10-28 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Nuclear,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuclear Plant Leaks Radiation In Western Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear plant in western Japan leaked radiation
into the air, but not enough to contaminate the environment, a
company official said Thursday.
   The leak was in the Ohi No. 1 plant in Fukui region, about 200
miles west of Tokyo, an official of Kansai Electric Co. said on
condition of anonymity. The amount of radiation still was being
measured.
   He said the leak was detected when ``an above average amount'' of
radiation was measured in the 1.18 million-kilowatt plant during
testing of a valve in the steam generator.
   Radioactive water leaked into a separate circuit of water used to
condense the steam after it has driven the electricity-producing
turbines. The leak could have come from a tiny hole in the pipes,
but had nothing to do with the valve test, he said.
   Some radiation was released into the air, but should not reach a
level that will contaminate the environment, the official said.
   A radiation leak occurred at the plant in September 1981 when a
pipe was punctured, the official said.
   Japan's 35 nuclear reactors supply about 29 percent of the
nation's electricity, according to government figures. Fukui has 12
nuclear power plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
