<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     10-28 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim Soviets Bringing New Planes, Guns to Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Afghan rebel
alliance said Thursday that the Soviets are deploying new
high-altitude bombers and long-range artillery into Afghanistan
despite their declared plans to withdraw.
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, leader of the hardline Jamiat-i-Islami
faction and present chairman of the seven-party mujahedeen (holy
warrior) alliance, said he received the first reports of the new
weaponry Monday. He said additional reports confirmed them on
Thursday.
   The reports could not be immediately confirmed but Jamiat has
proved a relatively reliable source of war news in the past.
   ``This is a dangerous new political and military situation,''
Rabbani told reporters in the Pakistani capital.
   He said the bombers were identified as Tu-16s, known as Badgers
in the parlance of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization. They are
among the largest twin-engine bombers ever built.
   Rabbani said his anti-Marxist, Islamic guerrillas also reported
seeing new, high-altitude jet fighters but he could not identify the
type.
   He said the aircraft, bearing Soviet markings, were observed at
the big Soviet air base at Bagram in northeast Afghanistan and at
Shindand air base in the west.
   The rebel leader said there also were unconfirmed sightings of
the planes at Kabul airport, which doubles as an air force base.
   Rabbani said the only logical use of such aircraft was to conduct
saturation bombing from inside Afghanistan. Previously, the Soviets
have flown the planes from inside the Soviet Union to bomb guerrilla
positions in northern Afghanistan.
   He said he also received numerous reports of new BM-41 long-range
artillery and a new type of mine distribution device.
   ``The BM-41 cannot be used against mujahedeen positions in the
mountains because they cannot be aimed that high,'' Rabbani said.
``Their only use would be against civilian targets.''
   Moscow recently hinted it might alter its pullout timetable from
Afghanistan because of alleged interference by Pakistan and the
United States.
   The rebels, armed mainly by Washington, operate from bases inside
Pakistan.
   Under a U.N.-sponsored accord singed in Geneva last spring,
Moscow agreed to withdraw its more than 100,000 troops from
Afghanistan between May 15 and next Feb. 15. The rebels did not take
part in those negotiations, but were represented by Pakistan.
   United Nations observers said the Kremlin met its pledge to
complete the removal of half of the troops by Aug. 15, but no major
Soviet troop withdrawals have taken place since then.
   The rebels claim to have taken five of about 30 provincial
capitals since the pullout began, and have begun hammering Kabul,
the Afghan capital, with rockets almost daily.
   The government has claimed steady military victories over the
guerrillas.
   Rabbani reiterated the rebels' offer to negotiate peace directly
with Moscow. They refuse to discuss terms with the Afghan
government, which they see only as Soviet puppets.
   ``We do not wish to disturb the Soviet withdrawal from
Afghanistan. In fact, we wish to facilitate their speed,'' Rabbani
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
