<1ST_LINE>a i PM-France-Unions Adv31   10-28 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Unions, Adv 31,0838</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Oct. 31 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>French Labor Movement Low in Membership But High in Profile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France's labor unions _ feeble in membership,
splintered in politics _ have kept a knack for grabbing attention
and embarrassing governments.
   A ``Day of Action'' Oct. 20 by public employees dominated the
news and put pressure on the government of Premier Michel Rocard, a
socialist, to do something to restore what is known as ``social
peace.''
   Workers thronged Paris' wide boulevards, marching under angry
banners by the tens of thousands. Teachers closed their books,
postmen dropped their mailbags, and transit passengers were left
crowded on train and subway platforms waiting for the occasional
ride.
   Union leaders said they would consider stepping up the pressure
for pay raises with more strikes.
   The impression is of a powerful and united labor movement, but
the reality is five national federations split along political
lines, all suffering from falling membership and accused of losing
touch with the workers.
   ``It's a very complicated movement,'' said Rene Mouriaux, who
specializes in unions at the Paris-based Center for the Study of
French Political Life.
   ``It has the lowest rate of union membership in Europe, but the
ability to mobilize people is relatively great,'' he said in an
interview. ``They have an ability to make themselves heard that goes
beyond their ability to organize.''
   Reliable figures on membership are scarce. The claims by the
different union federations are widely believed to be overstated.
   Mouriaux said the best estimate he could offer, after extensive
study, was that 9 percent to 13 percent of France's 17.8 million
salaried workers have union cards.
   State-owned enterprises and the civil service are much more
heavily organized than private business, but any precise figures on
the breakdown are ``poetry,'' he said, rather than science.
   As membership dwindles, union leaders more frequently lose
control of angry workers. Many recent strikes, including one by
nurses, have been led by ad-hoc committees, bypassing the existing
unions who counseled patience.
   Roughly one-fourth of union members belong to the communist-led
General Confederation of Labor, known by its French initials CGT. It
claimed 1.6 million active and retired members in 1983, the last
time it disclosed a figure, but the independent newspaper Le Monde
estimated the CGT's real membership then at about 890,000.
   The second-biggest union is the French Democratic Confederation
of Labor (CFTD), close to the socialists; followed by Workers Force
(FO), which broke from the CGT when the latter became
communist-dominated in the late 1940s; the General Confederation of
Cadres (CGC), made up mostly of technicians, engineers and
middle-management; and the French Confederation of Christian Workers
(CFDC), no longer strictly religious.
   Most single-profession unions are affiliated with one of the big
federations, with the notable exception of the powerful National
Education Federation, which is dominant among public school teachers.
   The CGT has maintained its leadership, even while support for the
French Communist Party has dwindled to less than 10 percent of the
electorate, from its postwar position as the strongest party on the
left.
   The CGT's reputation as the toughest union, taking the hardest
line against the companies and the government, attracts workers who
would never vote communist.
   But even the CGT has suffered in the past 15 years, especially
from widespread layoffs in the hard-hit industries that used to be
its strongholds _ the mines, shipyards and steelworks.
   Although membership is low, unions have a secure place in French
law. Union representatives are involved in managing the social
security system, negotiating national contracts and in ``enterprise
committees'' that large businesses are required to establish.
   In the current standoff, the unions are demanding
across-the-board wage increases for public employees to keep up with
the cost of living, while the government says no money will be
available before next year.
   The situation is all the more uncomfortable for the socialists,
who took over the government in May from conservative Premier
Jacques Chirac. The union members overwhelmingly vote socialist, and
socialist leaders are more at ease supporting the union demands.
   ``The left in power finds itself on both sides of the
barricades,'' the leftist newspaper Liberation wrote recently. ``The
socialists are in a good position to understand the appeal of the
civil servants _ these constitute their natural sociological domain,
reservoir of voters but also of activists and leaders.''
   While there are sometimes long strikes in private industry,
French unions are better-known for work stoppages lasting one day at
a time _ or even less _ intended as a show of force during
negotiations, rather than as a final blow when talks have failed.
   Workers who provide essential services, such as nurses and
air-traffic controllers, are required to provide a minimum level of
service even when they strike.
   Rarely does business come completely to a halt.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs Oct. 31</NOTE>
