<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0544EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Chile-Exile Adv01   10-28 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Exile, Adv 01,0886</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs Nov. 1 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Labor Leaders' Internal Exile Upsets Chilean Business Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARRAL, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Within the limits of this sleepy,
conservative farming community, Chile's top labor leader resides in
court-ordered internal exile that has been criticized even by his
foes in big business.
   Manuel Bustos, president of the Workers' United Central, Chile's
main trade union confederation, was driven in a police car late on
the night of Sept. 15 from the capital city, Santiago, to Parral,
210 miles to the south. He hasn't stepped outside the town since and
legally cannot until February 1990.
   His confinement has been denounced by labor and human rights
organizations worldwide.
   Appeals for his release rose in number and volume after voters in
a yes-or-no referendum Oct. 5 rejected Gen. Augusto Pinochet's bid
to remain on as Chile's president until 1997.
   Bustos, a 42-year-old textile worker, harbors hopes that
Pinochet's ballot-box loss will bring him freedom soon.
   ``Maybe during the Christmas season, there will be an amnesty,''
he said in an interview. ``At least I can have my illusions, can't
I?''
   His sentence of 541 days' ``relegation'' to Parral was ordered by
the Supreme Court, which convicted him and other confederation
leaders of violating internal security laws by calling a general
strike that turned violent a little more than a year ago.
   The court ordered an identical sentence for the confederation's
vice president, Arturo Martinez, who is confined to Chanaral, a town
in northern Chile.
   Following Pinochet's defeat in the Oct. 5 referendum, a 16-party
opposition coalition called for the release of Bustos and Martinez.
Leading businessmen, including several who had supported Pinochet,
echoed the appeal.
   Manuel Feliu, president of the Production and Commerce
Federation, a national business organization, said an amnesty for
the two labor leaders ``would be a sign of grandeur and of
reconciliation, which is what the country needs now.''
   Bustos said Feliu's statement reflects the realization by
businessmen that elected rule will bring an end to what he described
as pro-business labor laws they enjoyed under Pinochet.
   Pinochet remains as president but must step down in 1990 after an
open presidential election.
   ``They now see that the time is getting close when things are
going to have to change some,'' Bustos said. ``They're a little
anxious to start some kind of dialogue.''
   He accused business leaders of being ``two-faced,'' calling for
reforms in a publicity bid for workers' sympathies while ``using and
abusing'' the current laws.
   ``Change is going to come, whether they like it or not,'' he
added.
   Upon seizing power in a bloody 1973 coup, Pinochet dismantled the
country's powerful, mostly leftist-led labor unions. Leaders were
imprisoned, expelled and, in several cases, tortured and killed.
Pinochet's military government drafted laws that prohibit
industrywide collective bargaining, limiting salary negotiations to
individual locals.
   Strikes are illegal in a wide range of industries considered
strategic, including copper mining, which provides up to half the
country's export income. In areas where strikes are permitted, law
requires that bargaining follow a strict timetable and be conluded
within 60 days. If not, the company's original contract goes back
into effect.
   Several international and foreign organizations have criticized
the laws as unfair, including the U.S. government, which last year
suspended Chile's special trade status because of restrictions
against organized labor.
   Bustos said businessmen also realize that a genuine dialogue with
labor cannot begin until his and Martinez' internal exile ends.
   ``These relegations are an obstacle to conversations'' and tend
to make the confederation more radical, he said.
   Bustos is a member of the Christian Democratic Party, the
country's largest political organization. Although he backs a
left-of-center faction of the party and has often taken a strongly
combative stance against the Pinochet government, he is considered
politically moderate in comparison with many other labor activists.
   ``I believe the only way you can reach an understanding with
people is through conversation,'' he said. ``I have always tried to
talk with business leaders.''
   Bustos does not rule out demonstrations or perhaps a general
strike by workers, however, if Pinochet fails to respond promptly to
opposition calls for democratic concessions.
   ``We have to think about an orderly mobilization ... to warn the
regime that indeed we have strength,'' he said.
   During his first weeks in internal exile, a regular stream of
visitors, including labor leaders and journalists, have called at
the working-class residence of a local Roman Catholic priest where
Bustos is staying. His wife, a journalist in Santiago, comes each
weekend with his 5-year-old son, he said. The couple also has two
teen-age daughters.
   He has become involved in protecting the rights of workers in the
Parral area, ``where there are some 7,000 workers and not one single
union,'' he said. He plans to open an office, with a secretary and a
lawyer, to represent workers in suits against employers.
   ``I've kept busy,'' he said. ``I brought a book with me, and in
all this time I still haven't finished it.''
   He said the book was about recent social reforms in the Soviet
Union.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Nov. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
