<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-DirtyDancing ADV28   10-28 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Dirty Dancing, ADV 28,0861</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, Oct. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Dirty Dancing' the Television Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The makers of the CBS version of the hit movie
``Dirty Dancing'' can at least brag that they have successfully
adapted a simplistic, cliche-ridden movie into a simplistic,
cliche-ridden television series.
   ``Dirty Dancing'' premieres Saturday with a one-hour episode,
then continues as a half-hour show.
   The movie, a variation on the worn
rich-girl-falls-for-sexy-boy-from-wrong-side-of-tracks plot, was a
hit thanks to hot dancing, great early '60s music and two charming
stars, Jennifer Grey and Patrick Swayze. The TV series has some good
music and dancing, and at least one charming star _ Melora Hardin in
the Grey role as Baby.
   In the movie, the plot was an excuse for loads of scenes of
sensuous dancers writhing to hits from the '60s. On TV, choreography
is money, so there's less dance, more talk.
   To allow for a continuing plotline, the series has the option of
going beyond summer vacation, since Baby (Hardin) is no longer the
daughter of a vacationing doctor but the daughter of the divorced
owner of the resort, Max Kellerman (McLean Stevenson).
   Hardin has a winning presence, but Patrick Cassidy has a long way
to go to live up to Patrick Swayze in the role of Johnny. Swayze
managed to give the guy some depth despite the movie's ankle-deep
plot.
   Cassidy's Johnny is a self-centered, humorless dunce who dances
around alone in his room rubbing his body. Granted, Cassidy didn't
write or direct such scenes, but Swayze didn't exactly have
``Macbeth'' to work with, either.
   In the opener, Baby arrives to spend the summer getting to know
Dad. Wandering about, she discovers Johnny's dancers rehearsing one
of their ``hot'' numbers. Johnny drops his partner and ogles Baby.
Dad stumbles in and gives Baby the job of talent coordinator _
Johnny's job _ for the resort's stage show. Johnny is miffed.
Conflict No. 1, with many more to come.
   Dad is suspicious about Johnny's secretive rehearsals. But Baby,
good sport that she is, persuades him to let the dancers continue,
pleading, ``Dad, you've got to give them a chance!'' There are a lot
of lines like, ``Dad, you've got to give them a chance!'' and ``All
I know is you can't give up!''
   After Dad departs, Baby brags that she has taken ballet, so
Johnny sets her up to make a fool of herself by insisting she join
the dancers. He eventually convinces her that her only purpose in
life is to defy her father and dance in the stage show, so they
sneak around at night to practice.
   Meanwhile, Penny (Constance Marie), Johnny's jealous Latin dance
partner, fumes, and Baby pretends interest in Neil (Charles
Stratton), the lifeguard her father approves of. Mandy Ingber
replaces the obnoxious sister of the movie as Baby's witless cousin,
Robin.
   Choreographer Kenny Ortega has done a good job with the dancing.
Too bad there isn't more of it. And too bad the writers and director
Tony Bill did not more effectively build the rudimentary suspense
that fuels the central cliche in the premiere _ the opening of the
big show and Baby's surprise appearance.
   By the end of the opener, everything seems to be tied up quite
nicely, but this is weekly television where concepts must be run
into the ground.
   Will Dad come to terms with Baby's new-found independence? Will
Baby and Johnny get it on before Penny gets Baby?
   Shut up and dance.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   REPLACING OVERRATED CAPISTRANO SWALLOWS AS TEST OF DEPENDABILITY
_ Judith Krantz' fifth novel, ``Till We Meet Again,'' is being
turned into a six-hour miniseries for CBS. All of Krantz' previous
books were also made into miniseries: ``Scruples,'' ``Princess
Daisy,'' ``Mistral's Daughter'' and ``I'll Take Manhattan.'' This
one, promises CBS, is ``the story of the romances, adventures and
family betrayal of three women, set against the sweeping events of
two World Wars.'' ...
   CRONKITE SIGNS _ Walter Cronkite, the CBS icon who set network
executives adither when he suggested his contract would allow him to
work for Another Network after next month, has signed a new,
five-year deal, according to the Los Angeles Times. Negotiations
began last spring. There had long been reports Cronkite felt
slighted during the network's 1984 convention coverage. This year,
he was in the anchor booth with Dan Rather as esteemed commentator.
Under the new contract, Cronkite can do outside work for public TV
or cable, but not for ABC or NBC. ...
   `SUNDAY MORNING' MEDIA CRITIC _ New York Magazine television
critic John Leonard has joined CBS' ``Sunday Morning'' as a
commentator on television, film and books. Leonard, a published
novelist, is former television reviewer for Life magazine _ under
the name ``cyclops'' _ and former editor of The New York Times Book
Review. He'll continue writing for New York and Newsday. Leonard
made his debut last week. He replaces Ron Powers who left to think
great thoughts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Oct. 28</NOTE>
