<DOCNO> AP881028-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:PortugueseTheater ADV01   10-28 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Portuguese Theater, ADV 01,0784</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, Nov 1 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Two Shows Look at a Small Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Starkly different productions of music
and dance by two Lisbon theater groups provide intriguing glimpses
into how the Portuguese see themselves nearly 15 years after the
return of democracy to Western Europe's poorest nation.
   The shows, one by a progressive theater cooperative and the other
by a more traditional music hall troupe, also illustrate how the
country's recent history still weighs heavily on the public
consciousness.
   The 48-year dictatorship established by Antonio de Salazar in
1926 and brought down by leftist military officers in April 1974 is
pivotal in both ``O Baile'' (``The Dance'') and ``A Prova dos
Novos'' (``The Test of the Newcomers'').
   ``O Baile,'' performed at a former nightclub called the Ritz by
the A Barraca (The Barracks) cooperative, was inspired by the French
film ``Le Bal'' (``The Dance''), directed by Ettore Scola.
   Helder Costa, director, author and leader of the cooperative,
said the Ritz production uses a dance hall setting to portray
Portugal's ``memory of itself confronted by outside influences.''
   ``A Prova dos Novos'' takes place at the Variedades Theater in
the downtown Parque Mayer where Lisboetas have been going for years
to eat grilled sardines and attend burlesque and vaudeville shows.
   The writers and many of the actors are children of music hall
veterans, an art that has kept three theaters going in the park
since the 1920s.
   In ``O Baile,'' the decline of Salazar's dictatorship is
portrayed as a carnival ball attended by dancers wearing huge paper
mache masks representing the traditional pillars of society _ the
Roman Catholic Church, the landowners, the police and the secret
service.
   In a splashy number in the Variedades show, actor Carlos Cunha
does a double takeoff on Portugal's leading young designer, Ana
Salazar, and long-time ruler Salazar as ``Manna Salazar, the
dictator of fashion,'' who is obsessed by boots.
   Salazar, who died in 1968 but whose regime carried over to 1974,
was popularly known as ``Boots.''
   The 14 actors in ``O Baile'' never utter a word, although they go
through numerous changes of costume designed to orient the audience
to the time in which their performance takes place: the Second World
War when neutral Lisbon was the center of international intrigue;
the '30s when the fascist Portuguese Legion tried to bully civilians
into submission; the late '60s when thousands of Portuguese youths
were drafted into colonial African wars.
   A beauty contest in the '50s judged by a ``fado'' singer dressed
in black is a biting satire on the music identified with Lisbon and
made famous outside Portugal by Amalia Rodrigues. The songs, often
about lost love, are accompanied by guitars or mandolins.
   ``Salazar turned fado into an official support for his regime,''
Costa said in an interview. ``People forgot fado can also be
lilting, not only sad. He almost succeeded in convincing the
Portuguese we were cut out to be morose, melancholy and ultimately
passive.''
   Soccer, Portugal's consuming national passion, is also central in
both productions.
   In ``A Prova dos Novos,'' contestants in a game show dressed to
represent the four major soccer clubs _ Benfica, Sporting, Os
Belenenses and Porto _ offer a hilarious and biting look at how
blatant game-fixing and cash deals have sullied the sport that keeps
much of the population of 10 million mesmerized two nights a week.
   In ``O Baile,'' dance hall patrons gather around to watch a
flickering black and white image of Mozambican-Portuguese soccer
great Eusebio on the field, in a scene marking the fateful
introduction of television into the country in the late '50s.
   With the exception of the music halls, Portuguese theater has
never been terribly robust. It suffers from a lack of funding and
overwhelming competition from television.
   But critic Carlos Porto calls the growing production of works
about Porutugal by Portuguse writers ``one of the most important
developments on our changing theatrical horizon.''
   Although given generally favorable reviews, ``A Prova dos
Novos,'' like the other music hall presentations in the Parque
Mayer, generally attracts a provincial audience.
   ``Most people who imagine themselves intellectuals or
professionals wouldn't set foot in a musical revue in a place like
this,'' said Gabriela Alvarez, a Lisbon video producer. ``Too bad,
because they're missing something.''
   The Ritz doesn't advertise its show, but Costa said word-of-mouth
publicity and rave reviews for the year-old ``O Baile'' have
resulted in weekend capacity houses of 200, including President
Mario Soares.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues Nov. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
