<2ND_LINE>BC-Skeleton Shop, ADV 29-30, AP Photo Pkg,0449</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29-30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 29-30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDS: Repeating to correct SID selector line.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Iowa Company Makes Bones, Skeletons</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Photo Package</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINFIELD, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of bones are heaped on the
tables. Skulls of all sizes stare from the shelves. Soon thigh bones
will be connected to hip bones, and neck bones to head bones, at the
H.T. Lensgraf Co.
   ``We can make your mother-in-law if you want,'' said Tom
Shelledy, general manager of Lensgraf, one of the few companies in
the world that creates hand-made replicas of entire skeletons and
individual bones.
   The finished products, made of urethane plastic, are sold to
clinics, medical schools, physical therapists, hospitals, medical
libraries and doctors nationwide and in 20 other countries.
   ``You mention Lensgraf products and just about any doctor knows
who you're talking about,'' Shelledy said.
   Having one of the world's leading makers of bone copies in this
southeastern Iowa village doesn't seem strange to the 897 residents.
Many of them don't even blink when Shelledy takes his pet baboon,
Babelle, for a stroll.
   From a cage in the middle of the Lensgraf factory, Babelle
watches two dozen employees work in somewhat of an assembly line
fashion.
   Parts _ a total of 180, not including small hardware such as
screws and wire for assembly _ are formed in molds that were made
from actual bones.
   ``Most of the bones have come out of India or Europe,'' Shelledy
said. ``A real, complete skeleton will run you a couple of thousand
dollars.''
   After the plastic parts harden, they are taken to another part of
the factory, where the excess bits called ``flesh'' are removed.
   The urethane plastic skeletons, each selling for $399, are
assembled at five separate stations.
   ``It takes a day to make a full skeletal replica,'' Shelledy
said. ``We can put out 14 a day.''
   The replicas are complete with arteries, discs and nerves, and
Lensgraf also manufactures dog heart replicas for veterinarians.
   For fun, Lensgraf makes such trinkets as 5-inch-long spinal cord
key chains, or key rings attached to miniature foot and hand
structures.
   Shelledy says it's not spooky being around bones and skulls all
day.
   ``I wouldn't say it's spooky ... it's quite different,'' he said.
``Your mind comes up with a lot of questions _ who they were, what
they were like. ... To know these structures once had feelings _
happy and sad _ and now they're all gone.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Eds: Photos by AP Photographer John Gaps.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend, Oct. 29-30</NOTE>
</DOC>
