<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 4-6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs b0755 of Oct. 25 to reflect network's new title for
miniseries.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Charles Haid Plays Australian Tunnel Digger in `Great Escape'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Haid's longtime hobby of doing accents
came in handy when he was cast as an Australian soldier in the NBC
miniseries ``The Great Escape II: The Untold Story.''
   He plays Sgt. Mac MacKenzie in the four-hour, two-part series
that is a sequel to the blockbuster 1963 movie about the true story
of a huge escape of Allied airmen from a German prisoner-of-war camp
in World War II.
   ``He's a combination of a couple of guys,'' said Haid. ``Mostly a
Scot, who's still alive but was conveniently changed to an Aussie
for television. My character was a tunnel digger. Moles, they called
them.
   ``We filmed in Yugoslavia with a lot of British actors. My
biggest challenge was fitting in with their dialects. My hobby is
doing accents. I've been fascinated by accents since I was a kid. I
have a kind of parrot ear. Mostly what I did was listen to tapes.
Then all of a sudden,'' slipping into an Australian accent, ``you're
talkin' like that.''
   ``The Great Escape'' sequel will be broadcast by NBC on Sunday
and Monday, Nov. 6-7.
   Besides Haid, who starred as Officer Andy Renko for seven years
on ``Hill Street Blues,'' the movie also features Christopher Reeve,
Judd Hirsch, Anthony Denison, Michael Nader and Donald Pleasence.
Pleasence, who was an actual POW in World War II, played an Allied
prisoner in the 1963 movie, which starred Steve McQueen, James
Garner, Charles Bronson and Richard Attenborough. In the miniseries
Pleasence plays a German SS officer.
   The miniseries picks up the story of the escape and its bloody
aftermath, in which 50 recaptured prisoners were murdered. The
second half takes on aspects of a police chase as some of the
escaped POWs return to Germany after the war to track down those
responsible for the killings.
   ``We were in Zagreb, Yugoslavia, which is in the middle of
nowhere,'' Haid said of filming. ``We'd get in a car every morning
and drive out into the woods. The POW camp was built in the woods.
We'd pass woodsmen with their horses and wagons and axes. It was
like something from another century.
   ``It's a beautiful country. So much of it's untouched. I liked
it, but a lot of people didn't. The roads are pretty bad. But you
could turn a corner and step back into another century.''
   Haid said he plays the lovable old cuss in the miniseries. ``You
see them in every English war movie,'' he said. ``I'm the guy who
says, `It's awright, mate. You'll make it.' It's like a Victor
McLaglen part.''
   Haid was is the Navy in the early 1960s and served aboard a
nuclear submarine. After that he got a degree in directing from
Carnegie Institute of Technology in 1968. He began his career as an
associate producer of the musical hit ``Godspell,'' and since then
has swung back and forth between acting and producing.
   The first feature film he produced was ``Square Dance,'' followed
by ``Flying Blind,'' which hasn't been released yet. Future projects
are ``Ask the Dust,'' about Los Angeles in the 1930s, and ``The
Nightman,'' a thriller. He and actress Melanie Mayron have written a
comedy about mistaken identity.
   He also has a role in ``Home Room News,'' currently being filmed
in Indiana. ``It's great to be in a picture that's not about life
and death,'' he said before starting. ``I play a doctor whose
daughter wants to be a journalist, and he wants her to go to medical
school.
   ``I'm just a character actor. I'm finding it's wonderful and
freeing to be away from `Hill Street Blues.' It's good to get away
from a character as strong as Renko. I was in danger of being
typecast. It's also nice to be working. I haven't hit the wall so
many actors do after a series. That's because of `Hill Street.' It
was such a special show. It rubbed off on all the actors. It was a
turning point for television.''
   Haid did a pilot after ``Hill Street Blues'' called ``Fort
Figueroa'' that was not picked up as a series.
   ``I'm hopefully headed toward directing,'' he said. ``I've been
attending the University of Bochco, meaning I've been observing on
the set of `L.A. Law.''' Steven Bochco is the executive producer of
``L.A. Law'' and before that ``Hill Street Blues.''
   ``If I direct something I want to know how to do it first,'' he
said. ``I need the technical knowledge. I embarrass easily. I don't
want to try to direct and do something that will make me cringe. I
think people measure you by what you're attached to.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 4-6</NOTE>
