<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--CampaignRecap ADV06-2Takes   10-28 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Campaign Recap, ADV 06-2 Takes,0835</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 6 b&w
photos, 1 cartoon.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ The candidates' revels now are ended. For many,
that came not a moment too soon; the campaign, as polls have shown,
was widely decried as negative and uninformative, short on charisma,
long on insults. In this lively review, a reporter who has observed
presidential politics over four decades distills the essence of what
handlers and principals wrought.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SAUL PETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the first presidential election in American
history, in 1789, there were no primaries, no nominating
conventions, no campaign, no debates, no speeches.
   Envious?
   Though heavy with hot air of zealots and rascals, most of the
elections since then also offered American voters some fun and
entertainment in the torchlight parades, the bands and songs, the
wit and spark of combat.
   Had any fun lately?
   As campaigns go, this one, more than most, seemed mirthless and
endless, a battle of consultants and computers, of goofs and gaffes,
a pingpong match with square balls.
   A campaign in which the smoke-filled room was replaced by a room
full of machines, and charisma was outlawed. Instinct surrendered to
statistics and spontaneity was scripted. A campaign nasty without
passion, an argument without compelling differences, a game of
trivia for high stakes.
   George Bush, the new John Wayne, spent more time on the flag than
Betsy Ross. Michael Dukakis, said one observer, came across like a
man making a condolence call. Dan Quayle? The metaphors were
non-stop. Try ``reluctant Rambo.''
   The rhetoric was a notch above James Garfield's in 1880: ``A
pound of pluck is worth a ton of luck.'' The campaigning was less
sharp than the Republican line of 1948, ``To err is Truman.'' And
less original than Theodore Roosevelt's phrase for Woodrow Wilson in
1916: ``a Byzantine logothete,'' (functionary.)
   The debates of 1988 fell short of Lincoln-Douglas. Some viewers
found themselves yearning for the Carter-Ford debate of 1976 when
the sound went off and the two candidates for President of the
United States of America stared at each other and said absolutely
nothing for 27 delicious minutes. You could look it up.
   Still, this year had its special moments, none likely to be
treasured by the principals. With all the what-if questions put to
Quayle, George Bush, his sponsor, could not have enjoyed the many
reminders that, if elected, he might die in office, lose his mind or
be forced out in disgrace.
   Michael Dukakis could not have cherished that picture of him
riding in an army tank and wearing, it seemed, his father's helmet.
Objective observers agreed he probably could not project a warrior
image even with two pearl-handled revolvers on his hips and a knife
in his teeth.
   It was a campaign of awkward challenges and doltish questions
from the media. Prove you're not a wimp. Show me you're not an
iceberg. Convince me you're not a pea brain. What would be the first
thing you'd do if suddenly you were President. Well, what? Go to
war? Count the silver? And then (as if this were the key question
that would unravel the witness): If your wife were raped and
murdered, would you still oppose the death penalty?
   It took a cast of thousands to make The Making of a President
1988. But all of them, the stars, the supporting players, ingenues,
character actors and animal acts, the director, stage managers,
coaches and makeup artists, none ignited the critics more than the
blond, blue-eyed juvenile lead.
   With the exception of Richard Nixon, who was almost dropped
because of a secret fund, and Geraldine Ferraro, the first woman to
be chosen, vice presidential nominees make the news the day they're
anointed and then they're gone, on the lesser circuits of political
vaudeville. It's considered good training for the job.
   Thus, history little noted the mighty labors of Lyndon Johnson on
the vice presidential stump in rural Virginia in 1960, soaring in
his peroration, pausing, descending and then, with that slit-eyed,
thin-lipped, high noon look, delivering the coup de grace. ``And so,
my friends, I ask you, what did Richard Nixon ever do for
Culpepper?''
   Dan Quayle was different. He couldn't fight his way off the front
page.
   First, a story that Dan Quayle, hawk, had nested in the National
Guard during the Vietnam War with family help. Then, boom-boom, a
story that Dan Quayle, student, was first rejected by his law school
for poor grades but finally was admitted. How? He insisted he got in
``fair and square'' and not, as reported, under a program to help
minorities and the poor, of which he was neither.
   And now came smiling, handsome, Dan Quayle, candidate for Vice
President, enriching man's search for enlightenment in diverse ways.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
