<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-28 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0564</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal incomes rose a moderate 0.5
percent in September while consumer spending turned in its weakest
performance in almost a year, the government has said in reports
that offered fresh evidence that economic growth is slowing.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that personal consumption
spending, which accounts for two-thirds of overall economic
activity, was unchanged in September following a 0.6 percent August
rise.
   It was the first time spending had failed to advance since a 0.2
percent drop in October 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prices Americans pay for imported goods
fell 1.1 percent from July through September, the first decline in
more than two years, the government has reported.
   The Labor Department attributed the quarterly drop reported
Thursday to a fall in crude oil prices and a rise in the value of
the dollar against overseas currencies.
   A stronger dollar boosts Americans' purchasing power for foreign
goods and also tends to make U.S. exports more expensive. U.S.
export prices rose 2 percent during the July-September quarter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the air in Wall Street's merger balloon
has leaked out as takeover stocks plunged and investors fretted over
the fragility of the new mega-deals.
   Market watchers weren't ready Thursday to proclaim the recent
burst of merger mania had turned to merger phobia, but it was clear
euphoria was giving way to caution.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 24.35 points to
2,140.83, while several takeover-related stocks dropped sharply.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. has taken its $20.3
billion takeover offer for RJR Nabisco Inc. directly to
shareholders, while a rival group headed by company managers has
picked up an ally on Wall Street.
   Salomon Brothers Inc. on Thursday joined Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. in backing the group of top managers at RJR Nabisco who are
contemplating a challenge to Kohlberg Kravis for control of the food
and cigarette giant.
   The entry of Salomon Brothers means two of the most powerful
members of the Wall Street establishment are teaming up against
Kohlberg Kravis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC of Britain has extended
by one week its unsolicited $5.2 billion offer to buy Pillsbury Co.,
saying the food and restaurant company has pursued a costly strategy
to prevent shareholders from considering the all-cash offer.
   A Pillsbury spokesman said Thursday that the company had not
received official word of the extension from Grand Met and therefore
could not comment.
   Grand Met made public a letter to Pillsbury saying the U.S.
company has refused to meet with Grand Met to discuss the offer,
which Grand Met has said is negotiable.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. had industry earnings record
of $859.2 million for the third quarter, eclipsing rival Ford Motor
Co., while Chrysler Corp. says its earnings dropped 54.3 percent for
the period.
   GM said Thursday its quarterly earnings, which amount to $2.46 a
share, came on sales of $25.04 billion. On Wednesday, Ford reported
third-quarter earnings of $856.3 million, or $1.78 a share, on sales
of $17.73 billion.
   Chrysler said it earned $112.5 million, or 50 cents a share, on
sales of $7.01 billion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
