<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   10-28 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0555</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coniston Partners said it was launching a $456.75
million tender offer today as a first step in acquiring majority
control of food services giant TW Services Inc., which earlier this
month rejected a lower merger proposal.
   Coniston said Thursday it planned eventually to pay $29 a share
to acquire all of the roughly 39.27 million outstanding TW shares it
does not already own.
   That gives its overall buyout offer an indicated value of about
$1.14 billion.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines and the parent of United Airlines report that
strong passenger traffic boosted their third-quarter profit
substantially from a year earlier.
   UAL Corp. said Thursday its net income in the three months ended
Sept. 30 more than quadrupled to $402.4 million, or $18.68 a share,
from $82.3 million, or $1.41 a share, a year earlier.
   Delta said its third-quarter profit jumped 69 percent to $99.95
million, or $2.03 a share, from $59.1 million, or $1.22 a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new law requiring employers to give workers 60
days' notice of plant closings or mass layoffs could profoundly
affect Wall Street, where many firms are considering a second round
of post-crash staff reductions.
   Labor lawyers said Thursday that the plant closing bill, which by
its name suggests only blue-collar industries, applies to firms
employing at least 100 people.
   In the financial services business, that includes everyone from
the $8-an-hour computer clerk to the $500,000-a-year securities
research analyst.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elderly people who are ``house rich and cash
poor'' will be able to apply for government-backed reverse mortgages
that could pay them up to several hundred dollars a month for the
rest of their lives, under a new plan.
   The demonstration project announced Thursday, sponsored by the
Department of Housing and Urban Development and backed by federal
lending institutions, will provide 2,500 home equity conversion
mortgages beginning next April.
   The reverse mortgage, in effect, gives the elderly income in
exchange for a lien on their property.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has taken
a step toward shoring up struggling radio stations by voting to
allow common ownership of stations located closer together but still
in different markets.
   By relaxing its ownership rule, the FCC said Thursday it would
enable more station owners to take greater advantage of the cost
savings that result from joint ownership of stations.
   The new rule would reduce by about half the distance required
between two stations owned by the same person or company. It would
also allow common ownership of stations in adjacent markets.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tumbled Thursday in selling attributed to misgivings
over the recent wave of corporate buyout bids. The Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials dropped 24.35 points to 2,140.83.
   The dollar ended mostly higher. Gold prices declined in New York
after strengthening in Europe.
   Bond prices mostly advanced, benefitting from flight by some
investors out of the stock market.
   Wheat futures prices were mixed; corn and soybeans declined;
cattle prices were mostly lower; crude oil and heating oil rallied;
and gasoline prices were mostly lower.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
