<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Data Provide Further Evidence Of Slowing Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two government reports suggesting that consumers are spending
less and earning less on an inflation-adjusted basis provide further
evidence that the U.S. economy is slowing, according to some
analysts.
   The Commerce Department reported Thursday that consumer spending
slowed last month to its lowest level since a 0.2 percent decline
last October. Personal consumption spending, which accounts for
two-thirds of overall economic activity, was unchanged in September
following a 0.6 percent August rise.
   Taking the rise in prices into account, consumer spending
actually fell 0.5 percent last month, the department reported.
   In addition, the government said personal income rose 0.5 percent
but the gain was completely erased by rising inflation.
   ``Consumers are being more tight-fisted because their incomes are
going nowhere,'' said Bruce Steinberg, an economist with Merrill
Lynch & Co. Inc. ``They already have so much debt that they are
unwilling to borrow any more.''
   Some economists viewed the report as further evidence of an
economic slowdown following Wednesday's government report that the
gross national product _ the broadest measure of the economy _ grew
at a slower pace in the third quarter.
   The GNP rose at an annual rate of just 2.2 percent from July
through September, according to that report. It was the slowest rate
in almost two years and followed GNP growth of 3.2 percent in the
first half of 1988.
   Many economists believe the economy will continue slowing over
the next year, with the biggest question being whether growth will
become so weak that it could topple the country into a recession.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar firmed against most major
currencies after falling to its lowest level in four months on
Wednesday. Market observers attributed the currency's strength to
apparent central bank intervention, although some economists
predicted the dollar would continue to weaken. In New York trading,
the dollar rebounded to 126.08 yen from its 125.70-yen value
Wednesday.
   Also Thursday, stock prices tumbled in selling attributed to
investors' misgivings over the recent wave of corporate buyout bids.
The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 24.35 to 2,140.83.
   In other economic news Thursday,
   _The Labor Department said the prices Americans pay for imported
goods fell 1.1 percent from July through September. It was the first
decline in more than two years and was attributed to a fall in crude
oil prices and a rise in the value of the dollar.
   _A new study shows Midwest economies are growing faster than any
other region. Minneapolis, Detroit, Cincinnati, Kansas City, Mo.,
St. Louis, Cleveland and Pittsburgh are growing faster than New York
and other Eastern cities, according to Grant Thornton, a New
York-based accounting firm.
   _An economic forecast suggests rising mortgage interest rates and
high vacancy rates will push new construction contracts down 4
percent next year to a total of $241 billion. McGraw-Hill
Information Services Co. said new building contracting declined
about 3 percent in the first nine months of 1988 from the same 1987
period.
</TEXT>
