<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     10-28 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices remain mixed, amid a lack
of market-moving news.
   Analysts said technical factors continued dominating Thursday's
trading session, pushing home heating oil futures sharply higher,
boosting crude oil futures and depressing unleaded gasoline futures.
   ``I think we're going to continue to see this until some
substantial action comes out of OPEC,'' said Bob Baker, senior
energy analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was scheduled
to meet next month to discuss controlling production as a way of
propping up worldwide oil prices, which have fallen sharply in
recent weeks.
   Iran's oil minister said Thursday that his country would accept a
further fall in oil prices rather than agreeing to an OPEC
production quota equal to Iraq, Iran's foe in the 8-year Persian
Gulf War.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, gained 27 cents
Thursday to $13.68 a barrel after rising 15 cents on Wednesday.
Other contract months also rose.
   Among refined products, the November contract for unleaded
gasoline settled at 50.72 cents a gallon, down 0.95 cent. The
contract had declined slightly on Wednesday.
   The November contract for home heating oil, which rose 1.19 cents
in the previous session, closed up another 1.49 cents at 43.04 cents
a gallon.
   Baker said gasoline prices, which had risen recently, were too
high for this time of year. He said the shift toward heating oil
represented a ``rapid market correction.''
   ``The season puts the demand more focused on the heating oil,''
he said.
</TEXT>
