<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WallStreet-Layoffs Bjt   10-28 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street-Layoffs, Bjt,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plant Closing Law Gives Wall Street Something Else to Worry About</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street investment firms worried about how to
escape a post-crash malaise may have an unforeseen problem on their
hands: the new plant-closing law that could constrict their
flexibility to cut staff.
   Labor lawyers said Thursday that the plant closing bill, which by
its name suggests only blue-collar industries, applies to all
companies employing at least 100 people.
   The measure requires employers who close operations and lay off
large numbers of workers to give employees 60 days advance notice,
and penalizes those that do not.
   In the financial services business, affected workers could
include anyone from an $8-an-hour computer clerk to the
$500,000-a-year securities research analyst.
   ``I don't think the investment banking houses or brokerage houses
have focused on this,'' said Stuart Bompey, a labor lawyer at the
New York firm of Baer, Marks & Upham, which represents some big
financial services concerns such as Merrill Lynch & Co. and Dun &
Bradstreet Corp. ``People thought it affected only an industrial
facility, but it clearly affects every employer.''
   The bill, which became law Aug. 4, comes at a vulnerable time for
Wall Street, which has been struggling since the October 1987 market
crash. At least 15,000 people have been laid off since then and
there are expectations of that another 5,000 could lose their jobs.
   Moreover, considerable confusion surrounds the enforcement date
of the bill, which is supposed to take effect Feb. 4. It remains
unclear whether employers must notify workers of layoffs 60 days
before the February date, which would be Dec. 6.
   Some lawyers are telling Wall Street clients to send out the pink
slips now in case the Labor Department's Employment Training
Administration, which is drafting regulations to implement the new
law, decides Dec. 6 is the effective date.
   ``I know attorneys within my firm are advising clients who are
considering or planning layoffs that fall within the ambiguous
period to be safe and provide the notice,'' said Margaret Bryant, an
associate attorney at Jackson, Lewis, Schnitzler & Krupman in New
York, which specializes in labor law and counsels some of the
biggest Wall Street firms.
   ``There's a concern, especially as people become more aware of
it,'' she said. ``Certainly clients who call us saying, `We're
planning a layoff,' are going to be counseled to the max on what
this law's provisions are.''
   The Securities Industry Association, a trade group of brokerages,
first sounded the alarm by telling members in a memorandum last
month that the ``new `plant closing' bill applies to all firms.''
   The memo warned executives and personnel managers that ``the
statute is complex and should be carefully reviewed by you and-or
your legal counsel for its implications for your firm.''
   The Worker Adjustment and Retraining Notification Act, as it
officially is called, penalizes violators by making them pay
affected employees for each day in which adequate notice isn't
given, which in effect could amount to a maximum of two months'
worth of severance pay. Violators also must pay the local community
government $500 for each day's violation.
   Although the law provides for numerous exceptions, such as
unexpected changes in the economy or a natural disaster, many
manufacturers fought the law on grounds it reduced management
flexibility.
   The law's key author, Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, notes the
inspiration for the law came from the emotional issue of
manufacturing plant closings and mass layoffs, which put more than
400,000 people out of work last year.
   ``It is true that the senator didn't envision Wall Street when he
originally offered the bill,'' said Nancy Coffey, his press
secretary. ``But he also feels all workers deserve adequate notice
if they're going to be losing their jobs.''
   Officials of several big brokerages have indicated they are
considering new layoffs, but so far only Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
has done so. The firm confirmed earlier this week that it is laying
off about 1,000 people by year-end.
</TEXT>
