<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury Bjt   10-28 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, Bjt,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met Extends Buyout Offer By One Week; Criticizes Pillsbury
For Inaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. has pursued a ``costly
strategy'' to prevent its shareholders from considering an
unsolicited $60-a-share tender offer from Grand Metropolitan PLC,
the British suitor says in letter to Pillsbury Chairman Philip Smith.
   The letter was made public Thursday after Grand Metropolitan
extended by one week its $5.2 billion offer to purchase the
Minneapolis-based food and restaurant company. It said Pillsbury has
refused to meet with Grand Met to discuss the offer, which Grand Met
has said is negotiable.
   ``We do not understand how you can explore and investigate all
available alternatives without meeting with us to discuss our
proposal,'' the letter said. ``Based on your public disclosures, our
offer is the only existing third-party proposal to acquire Pillsbury
and you have not made any alternative proposals other than the vague
statement...that `remaining independent would be a superior
alternative over the long term.'''
   The letter was signed by Ian A. Martin, chief executive of Grand
Metropolitan's U.S. operations, and Allen Sheppard, chairman and
group chief executive in London.
   ``You have refused to meet with us,'' the letter said. ``Instead
you have pursued a costly strategy designed to prevent Pillsbury's
stockholders from having an opportunity to consider our offer.''
   Johhny Thompson, vice president of public relations for
Pillsbury, said the company had no response to the tender offer
extension or the letter.
   The tender offer was to expire Nov. 1 but has been extended at
the same price until Nov. 8, said Walter Montgomery, a spokesman for
Grand Metropolitan in New York.
   Smith announced Oct. 17 that Pillsbury's directors voted
unanimously to reject the offer as inadequate, and directed
management to pursue alternatives.
   In a letter to Pillsbury employees dated Wednesday, Smith said
the company was not ready to announce alternatives, but believed
Pillsbury shareholders should not tender their stock to Grand Met.
   Pillsbury stock tumbled $2.12{ a share to $58.87{ on Thursday as
takeover-related stocks took a beating on Wall Street.
   Steve Carnes, a former Pillsbury executive who is an analyst with
Piper Jaffray & Hopwood Inc. of Minneapolis, said the extension
gives Pillsbury some breathing room to plan.
   Pillsbury declined to comment on reports that its board of
directors met all day Wednesday to consider alternatives to the
Grand Met offer.
   Carnes said he believes Pillsbury's directors are favoring a
financial restructuring that could include the sale of Burger King
and other restaurants to raise cash for a special dividend to
shareholders.
   Pillsbury is pursuing lawsuits in state courts seeking to block
the takeover bid on the grounds that liquor producers are barred in
several states from selling alcohol at retail outlets.
   Grand Metropolitan, which has interests in distilling,
restaurants and consumer goods, has said it would sell off
Pillsbury's Steak & Ale and Bennigan's restaurants because of those
laws.
</TEXT>
