<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Economy     10-28 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Economy,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Current Account Surplus Falls 10 Percent From Previous Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's current account surplus dipped 10.6 percent
in September from a year earlier to $7.605 billion, but surged 52.4
percent from August, the Finance Ministry announced Friday.
   In another report, the Management and Coordination Agency
announced Japan's unemployment rate registered 2.5 percent in
September, down from 2.6 percent the previous month.
   The surplus in Japan's current account, the broadest measure of a
nation's trade and financial flows, has continued to decline from
year-earlier levels since January. In August, it registered $4.991
billion, while in September 1987 it totaled $8.509 billion.
   Japanese exports in September grew 14.2 percent from their
year-earlier level to $22.698 billion, while imports surged 25.6
percent to $13.891 billion, the ministry said.
   Ministry officials attributed the year-to-year decline in the
current account surplus to the growth of imports, particularly of
manufactured goods. They said imports would have increased faster in
value if they had not been held down by low international oil prices.
   But the officials said demand continued to grow overseas for
Japanese exports such as semiconductors, video tape recorders,
televisions and office equipment.
   Tourism payments showed a deficit of $1.398 billion, down
slightly from the record $1.582 billion deficit recorded the
previous month.
   The officials declined to predict future trends for Japan's trade
balance, but said exports were likely to remain strong, possibly
endangering efforts by Japan to reduce its trade surplus.
   The Management and Coordiantion Agency said Japanese companies
continued to actively hire new employees, with the number of workers
in the manufacturing and service sectors rising by 1.15 million or
2.6 percent from a year earlier to 45.23 million.
   It was the fifth consecutive month in which the number of
non-farm employees rose by 1 million or more. The total number of
people employed rose by 840,000, or 1.4 percent, to 60.64 million,
the agency said.
   Japan's jobless rate would be higher if it were measured by U.S.
and European standards. In Japan, armed forces personnel and people
employed more than one hour in the last week of the month _ when
statistics are tabulated _ are considered employed.
</TEXT>
