<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0923EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Earns-Autos     10-28 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Autos,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Sets 3rd Quarter Earnings Record, Outearns Ford for First Time
in a Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has posted an industry record
$859.2 million in third-quarter earnings, and in so doing broke out
from under the financial thumb of Ford Motor Co.
   While GM reported record earnings Thursday, Chrysler Corp. said
its third-quarter profits fell 54.3 percent when compared with the
same period last year.
   GM's earnings surprised Wall Street analysts and sent the
nation's largest automaker's stock up $2.87{ a share to $80.50 on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   The company's earnings, which translated to $2.46 a share, came
on sales of $25.04 billion. That was an increase of 104 percent from
$421 million, or $1.05 a share, on sales of $22.6 billion during the
third quarter last year, when GM's results reflected a one-time
accounting change.
   Thursday was the first time in five quarters that GM has
outearned Ford. On Wednesday, the No. 2 automaker reported
third-quarter earnings of $856.3 million, or $1.78 a share, on sales
of $17.73 billion.
   ``I was (predicting) up at the high end (at $2 a share) of where
the world was ...'' said analyst Maryann Keller of Furman Selz Mager
Dietz & Birney in New York.
   ``The consensus for guys on Wall Street for the third quarter was
a $1.50 (per share),'' said Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc. in New York.
   Keller, Heaney and GM agreed that GM's performance began a
rebound in North America, and continued to be strong overseas.
   For the first nine months of 1988, GM said it earned $3.46
billion, or $10.09 per share, up 27.4 percent from $2.72 billion, or
$7.70 per share, during the January-September period last year.
Sales for the first nine months of this year amounted to $81.38
billion, up 7.9 percent from the $75.4 billion in sales during the
first three quarters of 1987.
   Chrysler said it earned $112.5 million, or 50 cents a share, on
sales of $7.01 billion during the July-September period this year.
During the three-month period last year, Chrysler said it earned
$246 million, or $1.12 a share, on sales of $6.17 billion.
   The No. 3 automaker said its earnings were hurt by high costs of
incentives, used extensively by Chrysler to lure buyers into
showrooms, and the closing for the entire period of its Newark,
Del., assembly plant for retooling.
   That plant resumed production this week, beginning to make the
new Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim.
   For the first nine months of this year, Chrysler's earnings fell
34.4 percent to $616.6 million, or $2.77 a share, from $939.5
million, or $4.33 a share, last year. Sales for the first nine
months of 1988 amounted to $23.17 billion, compared with $18.61
billion in 1987, a 24.5 percent increase.
   Meanwhile, Chrysler Financial Corp. said Thursday it earned a
record $59 million in the third quarter, 20 percent more than the
$49 million it earned during the July-September period last year.
For the January-September period this year, the financial arm of the
corporation earned $185 million, a nine-month record and up 12
percent from the $166 million it earned during the first nine months
of last year.
</TEXT>
