<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-RJRNabisco 1stLd-Writethru   10-28 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco, 1st Ld-Writethru,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Establishment Gangs Up On Kohlberg Kravis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, RJR Nabisco's ..., to UPDATE with stock rising;
ADDS 1 graf to end on payment of $2.5 billion for fees and expenses.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two powerful members of the Wall Street
establishment have joined forces to challenge Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co.'s proposed $20.3 billion buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc.
   The investment firm Salomon Brothers Inc. said late Thursday it
was joining Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and a group of top managers
at RJR Nabisco who are considering a challenge to Kohlberg Kravis
for control of the Atlanta-based cigarette and food giant.
   ``The combination of Salomon Brothers and Shearson Lehman Hutton
forms a team with extraordinary capital strength and capabilities,''
F. Ross Johnson, the president and chief executive of RJR Nabisco,
said in a prepared statement.
   Johnson leads the group of managers who last week announced they
were considering offering to buy the company for $17 billion in
cooperation with Shearson. He said ``numerous'' other firms had
expressed interest in supporting a bid.
   RJR Nabisco's stock rose 75 cents a share to $82.75 in early
trading today on the New York Stock Exchange. It fell $2.75 a share
on Thursday, before Salomon's entry was announced.
   The price decline indicated doubts about the cash value of the
Kohlberg Kravis $90-a-share tender offer as well as broader concerns
about the health of the takeover business.
   Kohlberg Kravis, which launched its tender offer Thursday, said
in a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission it was
``extremely confident'' it could raise the money to complete the bid.
   Kohlberg Kravis has lined up some big-league Wall Street backers
of its own. It said in its SEC filing that Morgan Stanley & Co.,
Wasserstein, Perella & Co., Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets were assisting it in structuring and financing
the buyout offer.
   Analysts said they believed Kohlberg Kravis could raise the
money, but said that because the offer was not all cash, it actually
was worth less than $90 a share.
   RJR Nabisco's stock price had been inflated by expectations that
a higher bid might be forthcoming, and the price fell Thursday as
that speculation waned. The company's managers originally said they
were considering an offer of about $75 a share in cash.
   Dampening the speculative fever for takeover targets were
comments by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who has
contended banks should be cautious about lending too much money for
leveraged buyouts.
   In a sign that it still hoped to avoid full-scale hostilities,
Kohlberg Kravis said its offer for RJR Nabisco was conditioned on
signing a merger agreement with the board of directors.
   Since its founding in 1976, Kohlberg Kravis has never acquired a
company without the support of the target's board.
   Getting the support of directors and at least some managers would
ensure a smoother transition if Kohlberg Kravis succeeded in taking
over the company.
   Kohlberg Kravis made its tender offer to shareholders only after
failing to reach agreement with RJR Nabisco's managers and Shearson
on some kind of a joint bid for the company.
   Kohlberg Kravis, a privately-owned partnership, has become one of
the United States' largest industrial holding companies by buying
out companies with the participation of their managers.
   In its SEC filing, Kohlberg Kravis said it would require about
$20.15 billion to buy all of RJR Nabisco's shares and to pay related
fees and expenses. It said additional funds might be required to
cover RJR Nabisco's long-term debt, which it said is $5.11 billion.
   Kohlberg Kravis said that if its bid succeeded, it anticipated
selling some of the company's assets, but said it had no definite
plans.
   Investment firms participating in the deal will reap huge fees.
According to the SEC filing, about $2.5 billion of the money raised
for the deal would go for fees and expenses. It was not stated how
much would be for fees and how much for other types of expenses.
</TEXT>
