<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0278</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned upward today, rebounding
from Thursday's broad decline.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 9.60 to 2,150.43 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 2 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 329 up, 166 down and
313 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.39 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Thursday's drop hit hardest among stocks that were known or
rumored to be targets of takeovers and buyouts.
   The selling came as increasing numbers of analysts voiced concern
over the amounts of debt being built up in corporate America.
   But once having delivered that message, investors seemed willing
to look again today at individual deals that are likely to go
through, presenting the opportunity for trading profits.
   Also, analysts said the overall market got a lift from General
Motors, which issued a third quarter earnings report Thursday that
was much better than expected.
   GM shares, up 2~ on Thursday, rose another 2| to 83[ in early
trading today.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.82 to 156.99. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .79 at 301.43.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 24.35 to
2,140.83.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by nearly 4 to 1 on the
NYSE, with 310 up, 1,198 down and 438 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 196.54 million shares, against 181.55
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
