<DOCNO> AP881028-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WPPSSTrial     10-28 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS Trial,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utilities Weighing $200 Million-Plus Settlement Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys in the Washington Public Power Supply
System securities fraud trial are negotiating for a settlement of
$200 million or more, possibly involving all 15 remaining utility
defendants, sources in the case say.
   The trial in U.S. District Court in Tucson, Ariz., was recessed
suddenly Thursday by Judge William Browning, who said he sought the
break to assist efforts which ``may be productive in shortening the
trial.''
   The trial was adjourned until Wednesday, and several utility
officials confirmed meetings were scheduled as early as Monday to
discuss a settlement offer from attorneys for WPPSS bondholders.
   The suit was filed after WPPSS stopped making payments in 1983 on
$2.25 billion in bonds, the biggest default in municipal bond
history. The bonds had been issued to finance two nuclear power
projects that were scrapped in 1982.
   Sources said Thursday the proposed settlement could exceed $200
million, would involve the federal Bonneville Power Administration
and would require approval from the U.S. Department of Justice.
   At BPA headquarters in Portland, Ore., Bob Reed conceded ``there
is some activity'' but referred inquiries to Harvey Spigal, legal
counsel to the federal power-marketing agency, who was not available
late Thursday.
   ``Attorneys are working on something, and they say they'll tell
us on Monday,'' said BPA spokeswoman Karen Hoenes.
   BPA, which backed financing of three other WPPSS nuclear power
plants, sells and distributes electricity generated at federal dams
in the Pacific Northwest and is the region's largest power broker
with an annual budget of $3 billion.
   ``A proposal has been proposed that I have recommended my clients
take a look at and discuss,'' said Albert Malanca, attorney for
Tacoma City Light, one of the largest defendants in the case.
   Malanca said a special meeting of the Tacoma City Council and
Utility Board was set for Monday morning, about the same time as a
meeting of commissioners of the Cowlitz County Public Utility
District, another major defendant.
   ``They will discuss an offer of settlement by the plaintiffs,''
said Cowlitz PUD manager Bob McKinney said. He added that he
expected details of the offer to be disclosed at that time.
   Officials of the Klickitat County, Franklin County and Mason
County No. 3 PUDs also said meetings on the matter were scheduled or
likely early in the week.
   A meeting of Snohomish County PUD commissioners was set for
Tuesday.
   Mel Weiss, an attorney for the bondholders, said a settlement
announcement could come next week. He refused to comment further,
except to say that the trial would continue in any event.
   Besides the 15 utilities, defendants include two engineering
firms and a financial advice firm. There has been no talk of
settlement involving the professional firms, and attorneys with two
of the firms said Thursday there were no talks involving their
clients.
   In the trial, which began Sept. 7 and is expected to last as long
as a year, a class of more than 24,000 past and present bondholders
and Chemical Bank of New York, as trustee for bondholders, claim
there was a conspiracy to lie and hide information that might have
discouraged potential investors.
   Originally, defendants numbered more than 100, including 88
public utilities that contracted with WPPSS to build the plants, but
most _ including WPPSS itself _ reached settlements that total $365
million in cash and $96 million in contested insurance claims over
the past year.
   A $200 million settlement could bring total settlements to $650
million to $700 million. Though the default involved $2.25 billion
in bonds, claims in the suit amount to about $1.5 billion.
   Thus, the total settlements could approach 50 cents on the dollar
for bond investors before legal fees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
