<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TWServices 1stLd-Writethru   10-28 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TW Services, 1st Ld-Writethru,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coniston Announces Tender Offer for Majority of TW Services</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new 4th graf to UPDATE with no comment from TW; picks up
4th graf pvs bg'ng, Coniston said ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investor group whose buyout offer was snubbed
earlier this month by TW Services Inc. said it would begin a $29 a
share tender offer today as the first step of a proposed $1.14
billion takeover of the food services giant.
   Coniston Partners' cash tender offer for 15.75 million shares,
amounting to about $456.75 million, if successful would give it a
majority stake in TW Services, which on Oct. 12 rejected the group's
proposal for a $28 a share buyout.
   The group, which already owns about 19 percent of TW's 48.5
million common shares outstanding, said Thursday it intended
eventually to acquire the remaining shares of TW in a subsequent
merger for $29 a share, giving the entire buyout an indicated value
of about $1.14 billion.
   TW had no immediate comment on Coniston's new offer, TW spokesman
James Ryan said today. ``The board will consider it'' and issue a
statement afterwards, he said. Ryan said he couldn't specify when
the TW board will meet.
   Coniston said the two-step buyout plan was aimed at sidestepping
restrictions of the anti-takeover law of Delaware, where TW is
incorporated. The group also said it filed a suit in U.S. District
Court for Delaware to block the anti-takeover law.
   The statute prohibits a hostile acquirer who buys 15 percent of a
company's stock from completing a takeover for three years unless it
immediately gets approval from 85 percent of the company's
outstanding shares, excluding its own.
   Acquiring a majority stake would enhance Coniston's chances of
winning a shareholder election, and would give it substantial power
over the TW board of directors, which is empowered to exempt the
company from the takeover law.
   Coniston said that if it succeeded in blocking or setting aside
the law's requirements, it intended to consumate a $29-a-share
merger ``as soon as practicable.''
   TW Services is parent of the Denny's restaurant chain and a major
franchisee of Hardee's fast food restaurants. In rejecting
Coniston's $28 a share offer as inadequate, the company's board also
indicated it believed shareholders would be best served if the
company remained independent.
   Coniston indicated at that time it was considering a hostile
buyout offer.
   The tender offer was announced after the close of business on
Thursday, and a secretary said no one was available at TW Services'
New York headquarters to comment on the offer.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, TW closed at $25 share, unchanged
from Wednesday.
   Coniston, with a warchest estimated at about $700 million,
typically takes large positions in companies and uses that clout to
force management to sell the company or make changes that boost the
stock price. It successfully forced a buyout of Allegis Corp. in
1987 but recently lost a bid to force the sale of Gillette Co.,
although it won an agreement for the company to buy back its
Gillette stock.
   In making its initial offer for TW, Coniston stressed that it was
interested in owning rather than splitting up and selling the
company.
   When Coniston made its $28-a-share offer, Wall Street analysts
agreed with the partnership that the offer was reasonable, but some
estimated that TW's break-up value might be as high as $34 a share.
   In addition to its 1,200 Denny's and its 400 Hardee's fast food
franchise restaurants, New York-based TW also runs Canteen Corp., a
food services concern, and a small nursing home chain.
   TW reported net income of $47.2 million on sales of $2.5 billion
in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
