<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-28 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened modestly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid a lack of bullish news
beyond the Agriculture Department's expected announcement of a large
wheat sale to China.
   The sale to China of 500,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at
subsidized prices was rumored Thursday, as was a sale of U.S. corn
to Spain, so ``everything was already in the market,'' said Cathy
Leow, a grain and soybean market analyst with Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in New York.
   Planting conditions for corn and soybeans in South America have
improved markedly in the past week, putting pressure on U.S. prices
for those commodities, analysts said.
   And news that reduced domestic demand in Argentina has freed up
400,000 metric tons of corn for export added to the bearish tone in
the corn market.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.10{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1{ cents lower with December at $2.74 a bushel; oats
were { cent lower to { cent higher with December at $2.31} a bushel;
soybeans were 2{ cents to 5{ cents lower with November at $7.56{ a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .15 cent lower with December at
73.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .18 cent
higher with November at 81.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent
lower to .35 cent higher with December at 41.47 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .42 cent lower to .05 cent higher with
February at 48 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
