<DOCNO> AP881028-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 0553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv28   10-28 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 28,0743</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday Oct. 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Does Buyout Binge Serve the Public Interest?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple of decades ago, the head of one of the
nation's largest banks sought to assure the public about the surge
of high-yield loans being made to Third World and other nations.
   Great consternation was being expressed in various circles _
academe, the media, banking _ that the loans were overly risky and
might not be repaid. No fear, said the chairman, since most of these
loans were backed by governments.
   His goal was to impress on listeners the notion that any
government would do handstands to avoid default, since their credit
ratings, their interest costs and their very economic future would
be endangered.
   It didn't turn out that way, and the public paid for it, and
probably continues to do so, in the form of higher borrowing costs _
on credit cards, mortgages, business loans _ than can reasonably be
justified.
   Could something similar be occurring now in the allocation of
tens of billions of dollars to corporate takeovers? Like foreign
loans, these too provide big returns to lenders. Like foreign loans,
they could mean defaults.
   And, as it was with the foreign loans, there are fears being
expressed by sensible people that some of the loans aren't going to
be paid back on the terms agreed to in the contracts. Defaults?
Entirely possible.
   The level of concern was raised this week when Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan advised banks to examine different scenarios
that might have an impact on collections, such as recession or
periods of high inflation.
   In a recession, for example, a debt-burdened company might find
its repayments, already high by most standards, extremely difficult
to meet. What would it do? What would the bank be able to do?
   Inflation might pose an even more difficult situation, since most
loans these days rise with the general economic heat.
   High interest rates caused many business defaults in the 1970s,
and few real defenses against risk have been created since.
Moreover, recent history shows that high interest can be accompanied
by deep recession.
   Many companies that failed to survive previous bouts of inflation
and high interest were financially much healthier than some of
today's highly leveraged buyouts, which in the best of times might
fail if important assets _ an arm and a leg in human terms _ can't
be sold to meet payments.
   While the ideal and least damaging way to retire such debt is to
operate acquired companies more productively, that is, by reaching
higher levels of production efficiency, there is no assurance it can
be done.
   Instead, many of the companies will simply sell body parts to pay
bills, sometimes with seriously adverse impact on communities.
   Others will seek to retire debt by issuing stock _ becoming
public again _ just as they had retired the securities _ gone
private _ by taking on debt. Such activity might lessen credit
strains, but produce questionable shares.
   Even if companies bought out in highly leveraged deals continue
to carry their burden of debt there are implications for the general
public. Number one is that this debt burden tends to tie the hand of
the Federal Reserve.
   Since 1973, U.S. corporations have retired $270 billion in
equities while adding $600 billion in debt. In order to save
industry from disaster, the Fed might have to keep interest rates
low, thus risking a return of inflation.
   No matter what happens, the public is affected. Consider taxes.
Dividends are taxed, but debt not only is not, it brings a rebate
from Uncle Sam.
   There is one extremely beneficial effect. That benefit will come
if the companies now piling up debt manage to pay their bills by
operating more efficiently _ by producing goods and services at
increasingly lower costs.
   In that event, the companies and the entire economic community
would prosper through more jobs, greater job assurance, lower prices
and better wages, working conditions and goods.
   But, handled differently, the big debts of industry could mean
higher prices, poorer goods, higher interest rates, a poor quality
of stocks in which to invest and a superstructure of business that
would be vulnerable to spills.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday Oct 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
