<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Pepperell     10-28 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Pepperell,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Profit Gains for 4th Fiscal Qtr, Full Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc., the textile
manufacturer facing a takeover bid from the owner of Fruit of the
Loom underwear, said Friday its profit rose 12 percent to a record
in its fourth fiscal quarter.
   Pepperell said it earned $24.3 million, or 83 cents a share, for
the quarter ended Sept. 24, up from $21.7 million, or 69 cents a
share, a year earlier.
   Fourth-quarter sales climbed 41 percent to $677 million from $481
million.
   For the fiscal year, Pepperell said its earnings rose 18 percent
to $84.4 million, or $2.82 per share, from $71.6 million, or $2.38 a
share, a year earlier.
   Sales for the fiscal year rose 26 percent to $2.15 billion from
$1.7 billion for the previous year.
   The earnings figures include results from J.P. Stevens & Co.
Inc., which Pepperell acquired in May for $1.2 billion.
   Chairman and Chief Executive Officer J.L. Lanier Jr. said he
expects significant economies in the future from the bed and bath
products operations of Pepperell and Stevens. ``Barring a major
economic downturn, fiscal 1989 should be another good year,'' he
said.
   Chicago-based Farley Inc., owner of Fruit of the Loom, announced
this week a $1.4 billion takeover bid for Pepperell.
   Pepperell advised its stockholders not to take action until
receiving the company's recommendation.
</TEXT>
