<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-28 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Higher; Soybeans Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, led by the late-surging
soybean market. Corn finished substantially higher while wheat
futures were mixed.
   With no news to move the markets following an opening dip,
traders responded to technical signals from price charts that
indicated the soybean and corn markets were oversold and due for a
correction, said Cathy Leow, grain and soybean market analyst with
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``It looks like a huge, technically inspired rally,'' she said.
``The markets have been down pretty hard the last couple of weeks.
Today, we gapped lower at the opening but there was no
follow-through selling. Then toward the end of the day, people
started covering up (that is, buying to offset positions established
earlier in the day) and it just accelerated.''
   At the close, wheat was } cent to 2 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in December at $4.09{ a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 4{
cents higher with December at $2.79\ a bushel; oats were 2 cents to
4\ cents higher with December at $2.34} a bushel; soybeans were 5
cents to 8\ cents higher with November at $7.65 a bushel.
</TEXT>
