<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BritishSteel     10-28 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-British Steel,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Steel Expects 31 Percent Rise in Pre-Tax Profit This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government expects to announce on Nov.
23 the price of the shares it will be offering in its sale of stock
in state-owned British Steel PLC, it was announced Friday.
   Britain's largest steelmaker also announcved it expects to post a
pre-tax profit gain of at least 31 percent in its current fiscal
year.
   In a preliminary prospectus for the planned privatization, it
said it expects to report pre-tax profit of at least 550 million
pounds, or $968 million, for the year ending April 1, 1989 compared
with 419 million pounds, or $737 million, in the previous 12 months.
   Regarding the stock offering, the steelmaker said about one-third
of the 2 billion shares to be offered will be sold to foreign
investors in the United States, Japan, continental Europe and
Canada. The remaining shares will be sold to institutional and
individual investors in Britain, it said.
   The British government plans to close the offering Dec. 2 and
trading in the shares is expected to begin by Dec. 5.
   ``This sale demonstrates again the government's determination to
continue to extend the number of industries experiencing the
benefits of privatization,'' Trade Secretary Lord Young told a news
conference.
   The British Steel sell-off will be the first privatization since
the government's sale of its remaining one-third stake in British
Petroleum Co. PLC. That sale coincided with the October 1987 stock
market crash, and was a flop with investors.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government
successfully has sold off billions of dollars' worth of state assets
since 1979 to promote capitalism and encourage stock ownership in
Britain. British Airways PLC, Jaguar PLC and British Gas PLC are
just some of the other state-owned companies sold to the public.
</TEXT>
