<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-McDonnellDouglas     10-28 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-McDonnell Douglas,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor Posts Earnings Increase For Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. said Thursday increased
business in transport aircraft, space systems and missiles
contributed to a 4 percent increase in its third-quarter earnings.
   Earnings for the quarter were $83.5 million, or $2.18 per share,
companred with $80.3 million, or $1.98 per share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 15.2 percent to $3.72 billion from
$3.23 billion for the same period last year.
   Third quarter revenues were sharply higher in the transport
aircraft segment as a result of increased MD-80 and DC-10@KC-10
deliveries and growth in the C-17 program. Revenues were up sharply
in space systems and missiles, up slightly in combat aircraft and in
information systems.
   Combat aircraft earnings in this year's third quarter were
approximately equal to those of a year earlier despite rising
expenditures for development work connected with the U.S. Air
Force's Advanced Tactical Fighter competition, the company said.
   The company said its losses in information systems were about the
same as last year when non-recurring items were excluded.
   The company said its earnings for the first nine months slipped
7.3 percent to $205.1 million, or $5.34 per share, compared with
$220.4 million or $5.43 per share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue rose 6.1 percent to $10.4 billion from $9.8
billion last year.
   Disposition of the corporation's interest in a health maintenance
organization contributed a pre-tax gain of $26 million, or 43 cents
per share after tax, to information systems results in the third
quarter. However, the gain was fully offset by costs of a
restructuring program that involved work force reductions and
write-offs of certain assets and excess facilities.
   In the third quarter of 1987, information systems results
included a pre-tax gain of $15 million, or 21 cents per share after
tax, from the sale of the corporation's holdings in a computer
services company.
</TEXT>
