<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ComputerContract     10-28 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Contract,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATT Wins Pentagon Computer Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Telephone & Telegraph Co. on
Friday won a spirited competition to provide thousands of new
computers to the Defense Department, establishing its position in
the industry for years to come with what has been described as the
computer contract of the century.
   The contract awarded Friday was worth $929.1 million.
   AT&T officials said its value could ultimately exceed $1 billion,
depending on the options exercised.
   The Air Force, which acted as the agent for the other services in
overseeing the bidding, said an AT&T subsidiary, AT&T Technologies
Inc., had been selected over five competitors and would now be
expected to deliver some 20,000 mini-computers over the next five
years.
   Among the losers were the Zenith Data Systems Corp.; the Lockheed
Missiles & Space Co.; the Planning Research Corp.; Honeywell Federal
Systems, and International Business Machines Corp.
   Air Force leaders hailed the results of the competition, saying
the Pentagon had pushed the industry into a new round of
price-cutting.
   ``We are going to completely rewrite the industry's cost formulas
for equipment of this type with this contract,'' said Andrew E.
Bilinski, a deputy assistant secretary of the Air Force for
acquisition.
   The Air Force and Pentagon had originally estimated it would cost
up to $4.5 billion to acquire 20,000 of the machines.
   The Air Force is buying the computers for its own use as well as
that of the Army, Navy, Coast Guard, Defense Communications Agency
and Defense Logistics Agency. From the start, the contract was
recognized as being so large that it could ensure the winner a
strong position in the highly competitive industry for years to come.
   AT&T, although a relative newcomer to the computer ranks thanks
to the 1984 breakup of the Bell System, had widely been considered a
front-runner in the competition.
   That was because the Air Force, in a bid to standardize what is
now a maze of computer systems throughout the Defense Department,
specified that all bidders must propose computers that could operate
on UNIX _ a computer software program developed by AT&T.
   The UNIX system, although owned by AT&T, is now widely licensed
to other vendors and can be used to operate many different
computers. The Air Force's decision, however, prompted a legal
challenge that delayed the award for almost a year and ultimately
ended with two industry giants _ the Digital Equipment Corp. and
Wang Laboratories _ withdrawing from the competition.
   Digital and Wang charged, unsuccessfully, the Air Force had
rigged the competition with the decision to specify UNIX
compatibility.
   AT&T was allowed to enter unregulated markets like computer
manufacturing thanks to its 1984 settlement of an antitrust suit
filed by the Justice Department. By agreeing to spin off its 23
local Bell System companies, AT&T was granted the freedom to pursue
virtually any business lines it wanted.
   Herb Linnen, an AT&T spokesman in Washington, hailed Friday's
award, describing it as the ``largest computer contract ever awarded
by the federal government.''
   Linnen said the contract ``has a potential value in excess of $1
billion, depending upon the options exercised.''
   ``Winning this contract firmly establishes AT&T as a leader in
the federal computer marketplace,'' added Warren G. Corgan, the vice
president of AT&T's Federal Systems Division.
   ``This project is a very large systems integration undertaking,
an assignment that plays to AT&T's strength,'' he added.
   Robert M. Kavner, the president of AT&T's Data Systems Group,
said the contract also was the largest AT&T had won since it entered
the computer business commercially four years ago.
   ``It is a great shot in the arm for our data systems business,''
he said.
   The Air Force, in announcing the award, said AT&T would perform
most of the work in Greensboro, N.C., and Oklahoma City, Okla. It
said 363 bids were solicited and six proposals were received.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
