<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-28 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines; Gold Moves Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell Friday in thin trading that was
dominated by rumors and continued bearish sentiment toward the U.S.
currency.
   Gold prices rose following false rumors that Syria had invaded
parts of Lebanon it does not already control. Republic National Bank
of New York said gold bullion was bid at $412.25 an ounce as of 4
p.m. EDT, up from $407.50 late Thursday.
   Tension in the Middle East drives investors toward gold as a safe
haven.
   The Syrian rumor pushed the dollar higher as well, but only
temporarily.
   Hurting the dollar was an announcement in West Germany of a small
tax break to West German citizens who own government bonds, said
Peter van der Mespel, corporate foreign exchange chief for Deutsche
Genossenschaftsbank in New York.
   The dollar fell against the West German mark, and that led to a
general decline for the currency, van der Mespel said.
   ``The market is still very bearish toward the dollar,'' said
Stephen Dakin, foreign exchange trading manager for Union Bank of
Switzerland in New York.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.18 Japanese yen to a closing 126.08 yen. Later in
London, it fell to 125.75 yen. In New York, the dollar fell to
125.63 yen from 126.08 Thursday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7680 from $1.7695 late
Thursday. Later in New York, the pound rose to $1.7720 from $1.7675
Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.7719 West German marks, down from
1.7783; 1.4938 Swiss francs, down from 1.4982; 1.2038 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2050; 6.0525 French francs, down from 6.0680;
and 1,319.25 Italian lire, down from 1,323.12.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.7755 West German marks, up from 1.7725; 1.4970
Swiss francs, up from 1.4915; 6.0750 French francs, up from 6.0455;
2.0010 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9977; 1,321.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,320.00; and 1.2035 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2024.
   In Hong Kong, gold bullion rose 65 cents to close at a bid
$409.87 a troy ounce. Later in Europe, the Mideast rumors drove gold
up. In London, gold bullion rose to $410.50 an ounce from $407.50
Thursday. In Zurich, it rose to $411.25 an ounce from $407.20.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $412.40 a troy ounce from $407.60.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $6.31 a troy
ounce from $6.21 bid late Thursday. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $6.289 a troy ounce from $6.200.
</TEXT>
