<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1730EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-GMRedux Bjt   10-28 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM Redux, Bjt,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Do 3rd-Qtr Results Foretell GM Comeback? Yes and No</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s report of record
third-quarter earnings has left auto analysts split over whether the
automaker is headed back to significant profitability.
   GM, the world's largest indutrial corporation, reported Thursday
that it earned $859.2 million during the July-to-September period.
   Analyst Wendy Beale of Smith Barney Inc. said Friday that she
felt the results indicated GM was on the way back.
   ``The cost-cutting was there in the second quarter and most
people ignored it,'' she said. ``It was there in the third quarter,
too.''
   But analyst Douglas Laughlin of Bear, Stearns & Co. was skeptical.
   ``About 99 percent of the analysts can delineate the turnaround
story,'' he said. ``I'm in the `don't' camp.''
   The size of GM's profit for the third quarter, which amounted to
$2.40 a share, surprised many analysts, some of whom were predicting
earnings of a dollar a share less.
   If a one-time accounting change GM exercised in the third quarter
of 1987 is taken into account, the company's profit for the quarter
doubled over the July-September period last year. If it isn't taken
into account, GM's earnings increased 5.8 percent.
   The profit also broke a four-quarter streak in which Ford Motor
Co. outearned the much-larger GM. On Wednesday, Ford reported a
$856.3 million third-quarter profit, an industry record that held
for one day.
   GM said its earnings came on healthy North American sales, strong
overseas performance and a cost-cutting program that was beginning
to take hold.
   ``We are seeing increasingly strong bottom-line benefits of the
reindustrialization undertaken by GM in the 1980s ...'' GM Chairman
Roger B. Smith and President Robert Stempel said in a joint
statement Thursday. ``It's clear that our year-to-year earnings
improvement is the result of the efforts of the entire GM team to
build outstanding vehicles and to cut costs.''
   Another of those taking a wait-and-see approach about GM's
prospects was Beth Fusco of Moody's Investor Services.
   ``The problem is when a company's had a bunch of
less-than-stellar management decisions, you're always trying to
second guess them,'' she said. ``I think a healthy degree of
skepticism is in order until proved otherwise.''
   Analyst Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. said GM
may have turned a financial corner.
   ``I think it signals the beginnings of the turnaround; the big
question is sustainability,'' he said. ``If the market softens,
their earnings are going to be in trouble.''
   Most financial analysts expect industrywide sales would fall
somewhere below the 15.6 million cars and light trucks sold during
the 1988 model year.
   For the past year, GM has been steadily increasing its earnings
until the third quarter, when profits typically are lower because of
factory retooling in preparation for the model year which
traditionally begins Oct. 1.
   During that year, however, GM's market share has slipped from
around 51 percent to around 49 percent, a development that is a
concern to all analysts.
   ``That's the problem,'' Phillippi said. ``This is a lot of good
news, but they've still got a market share problem. ... If auto
sales stay (constant) and they don't start to score some market
share gains .... they're going to be facing an inventory bubble in
the latter part of the fourth quarter.''
   ``With a continuing erosion in market share, push has got to come
to shove,'' Fusco said. ``They've got to push those cars out the
door with incentives ... (but) incentives are going to hit them on
the other side.''
   Chrysler Corp. knows about that kind of damage.
   The nation's No. 3 automaker, which relied heavily on
profit-eating incentives during the third-quarter, reported its
earnings fell 54.3 percent to $112.5 million in the period this year
compared with $246 million in the same period last year.
</TEXT>
