<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-NationalIntergroup     10-28 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-National Intergroup,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Unit Gives Parent Company a $50.3 Million Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Intergroup Inc., a multi-industry
holding company, reported a $50.3 million second-quarter loss
Friday, largely because of poor results in its FoxMeyer Corp. drug
distributor unit.
   ``While we are, of course, deeply disappointed with the losses of
FoxMeyer overall, we are pleased with the results from our aluminum
business and with our sales progress in our FoxMeyer drug company
subsidiary,'' National Intergroup Chairman Howard M. Love said.
   The $50.3 million loss on sales of $731.1 million for the three
months ended Sept. 30 compares with earnings of $2.8 million, or 6
cents per share, on sales of $652.2 million a year earlier. Sales
climbed 12 percent, largely due to gains in wholesale drug
distribution and aluminum.
   For the first half, National Intergroup reported a loss of $40.9
million on sales of $1.4 billion, vs. earnings of $6.3 million or 16
cents per share on sales of $1.8 billion a year earlier.'
   Besides FoxMeyer, one of the nation's largest pharmceutical
distributors, National Intergroup also owns National Aluminum, a
leading producer of specialized aluminum products. The company also
has interests in steel production and energy transportation.
</TEXT>
