<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilPrices     10-28 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mostly Higher in Pre-Weekend Buying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices rebounded toward the $14-a-barrel
level Friday, largely because of pre-weekend account reconciling
among professional traders.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the near-month contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark crude, rose sharply at the
opening and finished 17 cents higher at $13.85 per barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale unleaded
gasoline rose 1.04 cents a gallon to 51.76 cents, and wholesale
home-heating oil rose 0.29 cent a gallon to 43.33 cents.
   Analysts said the maneuverings of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, which had caused prices to plunge early in the
week, weren't influencing the market. Some predicted OPEC's
activities would likely be discounted at least until key cartel
ministers meet again late next month.
   ``Today we had book squaring before the weekend,'' said Peter
Beutel, an assistant director of Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
``We also had trade buying, refiner buying. With prices so cheap, it
makes sense to buy crude and turn it into products.''
</TEXT>
