<DOCNO> AP881028-0334 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1744EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RJRNabisco 2ndLd-Writethru   10-28 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RJR Nabisco, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohlberg Charges RJR Mangers Trying To Sell Off Assets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs to ADD no comment from Nabisco; uppicks 7th
graf pvs: RJR Nabisco ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. charged Friday that
managers of RJR Nabisco Inc. may be trying to sell off
``substantial'' pieces of the food and tobacco giant, a move that
would make it less attractive in the face of the investment firm's
$20.3 billion tender offer.
   In a letter to Charles Hugel, chairman of RJR Nabisco's special
committee of outside directors, Kohlberg Kravis said it had been
advised that RJR Nabisco managers and their partners were ``actively
attempting to sell significant portions of the company and ... may
have provided potential buyers with financial and other information
about the businesses they seek to sell.''
   The powerful buyout firm declined to identify which businesses it
believed RJR Nabisco President F. Ross Johnson and his financial
partners, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and Salomon Inc., were trying
to sell.
   However, when Johnson announced last week that management was
considering a $17 billion plan to take Nabisco private, he indicated
he would sell off much of the company's Nabisco food operations.
   RJR Nabisco's managers ended talks with Kohlberg Kravis on
Wednesday about making a joint offer to buy the company from
stockholders.
   A spokeswoman at RJR Nabisco's headquarters in Atlanta said the
company had no comment on Kohlberg Kravis's letter. A spokesman for
Shearson said the investment house had no immediate comment.
   RJR Nabisco stock rose $3 a share to $85 in composite New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   Kohlberg Kravis said it believed food business competitors of
Nabisco were among the potential buyers already lining up for sale
talks.
   Selling assets to competitors ``could be detrimental to the
company's business from a competitive point of view and have a
deleterious effect on the employees of those businesses,'' the
letter said.
   Kohlberg Kravis essentially is alleging that RJR Nabisco may be
in the process of employing a ``scorched-earth policy,'' which is
the name Wall Street has given the tactic of a takeover target
selling off assets in an attempt to make itself less attractive.
   ``It makes the company less than whole ... it can make it
impossible to do the deal,'' said Edward Froelich, an analyst at
Pershing & Co.
   If Kohlberg Kravis is serious about the charge, analysts said, it
likely will file suit seeking to prevent RJR Nabisco from proceeding
with the sale of any assets.
   ``If they dismember the animal, obviously you have to change your
bid,'' Froelich said, referring to the $90-a-share tender offer
Kohlberg Kravis launched on Thursday.
   Kohlberg Kravis said in the letter that it did ``not contemplate
dismemberment of the company's operations.'' The firm said it would
retain all of RJR Nabisco's tobacco businesses and ``a significant
portion'' of the food operations if its takeover bid succeeded.
   RJR Nabisco has a plethora of high-profile brand name products _
including Oreo cookies and Ritz crackers _ that analysts say are
extremely attractive properties.
   ``They've got tons of stuff that already has shelf space and
(market) domination,'' Froelich said.
   On the tobacco side, the company's R.J. Reynolds unit makes
Winston and Camel cigarettes, among others.
   Separately, Kohlberg Kravis offered in its letter to allow ``a
significant number'' of RJR Nabisco managers an equity investment in
the takeover. The firm also noted that it intended to retain
``substantially all of the company's employees in the operations
which are not divested.''
   Principals Henry Kravis and George Roberts indicated that they
met on Thursday with Hugel, president of Stamford, Conn.-based
Combustion Engineering Inc. The letter outlined the points Kravis
and Roberts made in that meeting.
   According to their impression of the meeting, Hugel indicated a
``willingness to establish a process providing us with an
opportunity to meet with management'' and have access to certain
non-public information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
