<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1752EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OSHA-Morrell-Plant     10-28 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OSHA-Morrell-Plant,0785</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Congratulates OSHA; History of Strife Cited</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-OSHA-Morrell Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's record health
and safety fine levied Friday against John Morrell & Co. follows
years of disputes over working conditions at the company's
meatpacking plant here.
   In announcing the $4.33 million levy, the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration said the Cincinnati-based company did little
or nothing in light of hundreds of serious injuries caused by jobs
requiring repetitive motion on the meatpacking line.
   OSHA officials said they conducted a six-month investigation
after workers complained.
   Morrell, the nation's fifth largest meatpacker, said it would
seek a federal court order on Monday blocking the fine.
   The fine drew praise from the leader of the meatpackers union
local at the plant.
   ``We actually congratulate OSHA for doing their job. During this
present administration, we found that getting OSHA to do their job
sometimes was very difficult,'' said Jim Lyons, president of Local
304A of the United Food and Commercial Workers union.
   Lyons' union bargains for workers at the Sioux Falls plant. A
six-month strike ended in November 1987, but only about 500 union
workers got their jobs back. The remainder of the estimated
2,000-member work force is made up of replacement workers.
   Lyons charged Morrell did nothing to alleviate work place
problems despite many complaints from workers.
   ``We brought that problem to them. We addressed it with them many
times,'' he said. ``They knew ways of preventing it, and not only
that, we found their medical mismanagement to be incredible, a large
incredible problem, and obviously OSHA found our account to be
accurate.''
   Morrell officials contended the company was being singled out for
penalties in what is a national safety and health problem affecting
many industries.
   It was the seventh time in almost two years that the meatpacker
had been cited for safety problems.
   In April 1987, OSHA fined Morrell $690,000 for alleged
record-keeping violations dealing with injuries. It was the largest
OSHA fine against the company prior to Friday's announcement.
   An administrative law judge in Denver dismissed the fine earlier
this week, however, saying the time limit for levying the fine had
expired.
   The most recent OSHA fine was in September _ a $28,900 fine for
alleged safety violations stemaming from a plant inspection last
spring. The company also contested that citation.
   Workers have complained that Morrell increased the speed of its
production lines at the meatpacking plant and that injury rates
soared accordingly.
   When word of the potential OSHA fine leaked earlier this year,
Steve Crim, the plant manager, wrote a memo to employees saying the
problems were in the past. ``They occurred before new management
took over, both here and in Cincinnati,'' he said.
   Donald Slotkin, former president and chief executive officer,
resigned a year ago and was replaced by Milton Schloss. Corporate
offices were moved from a Chicago suburb to Cincinnati in April.
Morrell is owned by United Brands Co. of Cincinnati.
   Morrell hired a full-time safety director in January to help at
its plants in Sioux Falls and Sioux City, Iowa. Company officials
contend the injury rates have been reduced, but Lyons said Friday
that company records show more than half the work force has had
injuries or illnesses during the first eight months of the year.
   The company said the Sioux Falls plant had the best safety record
in company history in September.
   But union officials said Morrell documents do not include injured
workers who get first aid and are sent back to work.
   OSHA officials said the incidents of repetitive motion-related
disorders at the Sioux Falls plant was nine times higher than the
industry average and 600 times the rate for all U.S. industries.
   Morrell, however, said the injuries that had to be reported fell
from 70.5 per 1,000 full-time workers in January to 16.75 in October.
   Safety and work conditions at the aging plant have been points of
contention many times between the company and the union. The oldest
parts of the plant were built in 1909.
   Morrell and the union have been at loggerheads dozens of times,
including strikes, contract deadlocks, lawsuits and appearances
before regulatory boards.
   The company and the union are in the middle of talks for a new
contract at the plant. Morrell has asked for wage cuts ranging from
$1.25 an hour to $1.75 an hour, to a base rate of $8 an hour. Union
officials have said that if the company continues to push for wage
cuts, a strike is possible.
   The contract expires Nov. 20.
</TEXT>
