<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-28 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0816</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Rebound Sharply From 10-Cent Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices skyrocketed Friday on New York's Commodity
Exchange with the contract for December delivery soaring more than 7
cents a pound in a decisive technical move that analysts said
portends even higher prices.
   On other markets, precious metals also rallied strongly; soybeans
scored sharp gains while grains were mixed; energy futures were
mostly higher; livestock and meat were mixed; and stock-index
futures advanced.
   Copper for delivery in December settled 7.05 cents higher at
$1.397 a pound; the lightly traded spot November contract gained
9.95 cents, settling at $1.4445.
   The fundamental copper factors of strong demand and tight
supplies exacerbated by a nearly 2-week-old Peruvian miners' strike
were unchanged Friday, analysts said.
   The Commodity Exchange's release of weekly statistics showing a
further drawdown of warehouse copper stocks to 6,863 short tons
confirmed that U.S. supplies have continued to shrink, and
expectations that the London Metal Exchange will report a further
drawdown of its warehouse stocks on Monday prompted some of Friday's
buying.
   But analysts said copper's stongest buy signal was its own chart
pattern. The past week's 10-cents-a-pound decline was simply too
small and too slow to represent a real turnaround in the market's
nearly straight-up advance over the past two months.
   ``It was a pretty good decline but when a market like copper is
going to decline it usually is going to do it a little more
dramatically,'' said Craig Sloane, metals futures analyst with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co. ``When it goes, it goes too fast for
anyone to get in.''
   Similar chart interpretations encouraged bullish speculators to
re-enter the copper market in hopes that prices will rise even
higher, perhaps as high as $1.75 a pound.
   ``There's no way of telling how high this thing will go,'' Sloane
said.
   Analyst Peter Cardillo of Josephthal & Co. in New York said the
South American supply situation would dictate the market's direction.
   ``Until you see a definite end to that (Peruvian) strike, we're
going to continue to go higher,'' he said.
   Precious metals prices leaped in early trading and finished
sharply higher on unconfirmed rumors that Syrian troops had invaded
Lebanon.
   There was little other news to affect the precious metals Friday
but Cardillo said investors both in the U.S. and abroad appeared to
be shifting their money from stocks to the relative safety of the
metals.
   On the Comex, gold settled $4.80 higher across the board with
December at $414.90 a troy ounce; silver was 8.7 cents to 8.8 cents
higher with December at $6.335 a troy ounce.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, platinum settled $10.60 to
$11.70 higher with January at $543.80 a troy ounce.
   Soybean futures prices soared late in the session on the Chicago
Board of Trade, pulling corn and oats higher while wheat finished
mixed.
   With no news to move the markets following an opening dip,
traders responded to chart signals that indicated the soybean market
was oversold and due for a correction, said Cathy Leow, grain and
soybean market analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New
York.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents lower to \ cent higher with December at
$4.10 a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 4\ cents higher with December at
$2.78} a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 5 cents higher with December
at $2.35\ a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to 14 cents higher with
November at $7.68 a bushel.
   Crude oil prices climbed modestly on the New York Merc while
heating oil was mostly lower and gasoline rallied sharply.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 17 cents to 19 cents higher
with December at $13.85 a barrel; heating oil was .21 cent lower to
.29 cent higher with November at 43.33 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .24 cent to 1.04 cents higher with November at 51.76
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures finished mostly lower on sluggish boxed-beef
demand and weak technical factors, analysts said.
   Frozen pork belly futures prices dropped sharply on speculation
that inventories of fresh bellies were accumulating in cold storage
at a record pace. Hog futures were mixed.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .45 cent lower with December at
73.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .55 cent lower to .28 cent
higher with November at 81.80 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent
lower to .35 cent higher with December at 41.20 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .70 cent to 1.45 cents lower with February
at 46.90 cents a pound.
   Stock index futures gained slightly on the Chicago Merc, with the
contract for December delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500 up .30
point at 279.55.
</TEXT>
