<HEAD>Bond Prices Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices finished higher in light trading
Friday, amid lingering investor concern about risky takeover
financing and strengthening conviction that the economy is slowing.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond climbed 9-32 point,
or about $2.80 for every $1,000 in face value.
   Its yield, which moves inversely to price and often indicates
interest rate trends, declined to 8.80 percent from 8.83 percent
late Thursday.
   Dealers said investors were continuing to move away from equities
and corporate securities and into government-backed Treasury issues.
Investors say the rash of recent corporate takeovers and takeover
attempts has raised the risk of investing in stocks and corporate
bonds.
   While the stock market recouped most of Thursday's losses, the
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials ended the week with a net loss
of 33.61 points.
   ``There was a leftover flight to quality from yesterday,'' said
Kevin Flanagan, an economist with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Bond prices weakened early in the day after a spurt in precious
metals prices prompted by false rumors of possible Syrian hostility
against Lebanon, analysts said.
   December gold futures jumped to $419 a troy ounce on the
Commodity Exchange in New York, up $8.90 from Thursday's close.
   Investors traditionally turn to gold as a safe haven during
international turmoil because it is considered immune from the
economic volatility, such as higher inflation, that may accompany
the unrest.
   Gold futures later lost about half of their early gains and bond
prices bounced back.
   Analysts said bond prices also continued to be influenced by
government reports this week that showed the economy is slowing,
suggesting inflation is under control and that the Federal Reserve
will not tighten credit and raise interest rates.
   ``There is a growing conviction that economic growth is
decelerating and there is not a serious acceleration of inflation,''
said Elliott Platt, research director of Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette
Securities Inc.
   Inflation erodes the value of fixed-income securities such as
bonds and notes.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues were unchanged to 1-32 point higher, intermediate
maturities were up between 1-16 point and [ point, and long-term
issues gained 3-16 point, according to figures provided by Telerate
Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, advanced 1.72 to 1,156.34.
   Corporate bonds showed slight gains despite the anxiety over the
recent takeover wave. Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index,
which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities
of five years or longer, rose 0.66 to 295.45.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, were unchanged
at 7.61 percent as the discount remained at 7.37 percent. Yields on
six-month bills rose to 7.88 percent with the discount up 2 basis
points to 7.49 percent. Yields on one-year bills advanced to 8.07
percent while the discount rose 2 basis points to 7.51 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, stood at 8\ percent, down from 85-16 percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
