<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Kellogg     10-28 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Kellogg,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kellogg's Profit Up 22.1 Percent Earnings Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kellogg Co. reported Friday that its
third-quarter profit rose 22.1 percent from a year earlier, due to
rising cereal sales and lower taxes.
   The cereal maker said its net income in the three months ended
Sept. 30 rose to $145.7 million, or $1.18 a share, from $119.3
million, or 96 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue was up 13 percent, to $1.14 billion from
$1.01 billion.
   The quarterly earnings were the highest in Kellogg's history,
company officials said.
   ``Sales volumes of ready-to-eat cereal products continued to grow
during the third quarter, with particular strength in international
markets,'' said Chairman William E. LaMothe.
   ``This performance contributed to our increase in earnings, as
did the lowered U.S. statutory income tax rate.''
   In the first nine months of the year, Kellogg earned $379.5
million, or $3.08 a share, up from $313.6 million, or $2.53 a share,
a year earlier.
   Revenue totaled $3.26 billion for the nine months, up from $2.83
billion.
</TEXT>
