<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1846EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RiceFight 2ndLd-Writethru   10-28 0969</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rice Fight, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0993</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Decides Not to Fight Japanese Ban on Rice Imports</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs pvs 9th graf, ``Yeutter, a,'' with 11 grafs of further
detail and reaction; picks up at pvs 10th graf, ``The rice;''
deletes last 2 grafs pvs, redundant; subs 4th graf to include reason
for earlier rejection of petition; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the first test of a new, tougher trade law,
the Reagan administration on Friday rejected a request from U.S.
rice farmers that it launch an investigation into charges that the
Japanese government is unfairly blocking rice imports into that
country.
   The announcement by U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter
came as something of a surprise because supporters of the petition
were hoping the pressure of presidential politics would force a
different outcome.
   Yeutter called Japan's barriers against rice imports
``intolerable.'' But he said he believed the matter could be better
handled through a new round of trade negotiations now being carried
out under the 97-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, or
GATT, rather than in direct confrontation.
   The administration had rejected a similar petition in 1986
because it wanted to give Tokyo time to negotiate changes in its ban
on rice imports.
   ``We are shocked and dismayed that Ambassador Yeutter once again
would reject the U.S. rice industry's request,'' said J. Stephen
Gabbert, president of the Rice Millers Association, which had filed
the petition along with the Rice Council for Market Development, a
growers' group.
   The petition, filed Sept. 14, is the first major case under the
new Omnibus Trade Act, which President Reagan signed into law in
August. The new law, which took three years to get through Congress,
makes it harder for the administration to avoid taking action on
complaints alleging unfair trade.
   Two of the biggest election battlegrounds, California and Texas,
are rice-growing states and backers of the petition believed the
administration would not run the risk of appearing weak on trade by
rejecting the petition.
   Both Republican presidential nominee George Bush and Democratic
candidate Michael Dukakis have voiced support for the rice
industry's position.
   In California last month, Bush said he would urge Yeutter to
approve the complaint ``so we can maintain the pressure against
barriers to our exports around the world.''
   Yeutter, a strong supporter of Bush who has campaigned for the
Republican ticket, said he had listened to Bush but believed other
factors outweighed the arguments in favor of launching an
investigation.
   In a second trade matter, Yeutter announced successful resolution
of negotiations with the government of South Korea over charges that
country was unfairly keeping American films out of South Korean
theaters.
   The negotiations were launched after the Motion Picture
Assocation of America filed a complaint. Yeutter said U.S. and South
Korean negotiators had successfully cleared up all matters of
dispute.
   On the rice issue, Yeutter said he believed that an unfair-trade
investigation against Japan, which could have resulted in the United
States slapping retaliatory tariffs on Japanese goods, would have
been counterproductive to U.S. goals in the current round of world
trade negotiations.
   This round of GATT talks, known as the Uruguay round, is coming
to a critical review session in early December in Montreal.
   Yeutter said he would be looking for support from Japan on the
U.S. goal of eliminating all farm subsidies by the year 2000. He
said the trade ministers will also negotiate in Montreal short-term
subsidy reductions which could include rice.
   Yeutter said if Japan does not demonstrate its commitment to open
up its markets to U.S. farm products during the Montreal talks, he
would welcome a refiling of the rice petition. He promised he would
rule on the issue before the Reagan administration leaves office on
Jan. 20.
   But Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., whose district includes some of the
biggest rice farms in the United States, said the decision proved
officials in the Reagan administration ``are patsies when it comes
to doing battle against even blatantly illegal trade barriers.''
   California's senators, Democrat Alan Cranston and Republican Pete
Wilson, also expressed dismay. ``This refusal by the U.S. to take
direct action under our new, tougher trade law could well serve to
reaffirm the practice of protectionism by the Japanese and resound
negatively throughout the U.S. economy,'' said Wilson, who is in a
tight re-election race.
   But Mitsugu Horiuchi, president of Japan's Central Union of
Agricultural Cooperatives, said in a statement: ``I feel certain
that this decision was based on the broader need for economic and
political friendship between the United States and Japan and on the
recognition that agricultural trade between the United States and
Japan is the largest amd most stable in the world.''
   The rice issue has received a large amount of attention in Japan,
where rice farmers remain a potent political force. The Japanese
government permits only a small amount of rice imports into the
country and is committed to supporting the domestic industry, even
though it is inefficient.
   As a result, Japanese consumers pay from six to 10 times the
world price of rice, a staple of the Japanese diet.
   Tokyo maintains that it is essential for the country to protect
its domestic industry because rice, which has been grown in Japan
for more than 2,000 years, carries almost a mystical significance to
the Japanese people.
   Japanese Ambassador Nobuo Matsunaga last month delivered a long
position paper to U.S. officials explaining the critical position
rice plays in Japanese society.
   The Japanese parliament passed a resolution last month declaring
rice ``closely related to the Japanese culture'' which ``helps to
maintain and develop the wholesomeness of the Japanese society.''
   Japanese rice farmers have even sought to bring Emperor Hirohito
into the dispute, contending that an adverse decision would be an
insult to the ailing monarch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881028-0341 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Amhoist     10-28 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amhoist,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amhoist To Acquire CoastAmerica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Hoist & Derrick Co. said Friday
it has entered into a definitive agreement to buy all the stock of
Denver-based CoastAmerica Corp. for $10.50 a share or $110 million.
   Under the deal, American Hoist will begin a cash tender offer
within five business days, followed by a cash merger at $10.50 for
each share not previously tendered.
   CoastAmerica said the holders of 63 percent of its outstanding
shares have agreed to tender their stock in the offer.
   ``This represents a unique opportunity to realize in one
transaction our plan of creating a national hardware distribution
company,'' said Robert H. Nassau, Amhoist's president and chief
executive officer.
   Nassau said the acquisition will combine three of the nation's
leading hardware suppliers.
   ``Our Farwell, Ozmun, Kirk & Co. hardware distribution business,
CoastAmerica and Globe all have demonstrated their abilities in
certain regions of the country,'' he said.
   Richard H. Bard, chairman and president of CoastAmerica, said,
``Our buying power will be enhanced and our true national presence
will increase our growth opportunities.''
   CoastAmerica is in the process of completing its acquisition of
Globe Distribution, a privately held distributor based in Lincoln,
R.I., Amhoist said. Globe, a distributor of automotive products,
including hardware and paint, will become part of Amhoist after
CoastAmerica is acquired, Amhoist said.
   The acquisition, when complete, will make Amhoist's distribution
business the fifth largest wholesale hardware distributor in the
United States and the largest that is not dealer-owned, Amhoist
said. It said that after the acquisition, it will have annual sales
of more than $800 million.
</TEXT>
